{"title_page": "Nigerians in Japan", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Nigerians in Japan<BR/>{{nobold|{{Nihongo2|\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba}}}}\n|population = 2,797 (Dec 2016)<ref>{{harvnb|MOFA|2010|loc=[http://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/area/nigeria/data.html \u57fa\u790e\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf]}}</ref>\n|popplace   = [[Tokyo]]\n|langs      = [[English language|English]] ([[Nigerian English]]), [[Igbo language|Igbo]] and other [[languages of Nigeria]]; [[Japanese language|Japanese]]<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n|rels       = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Nigerians in Japan'''|\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba|Zainichi Naijeriajin}} form a significant immigrant community, with around 2800 living in the country, mostly belonging to the Nigerian Union in Japan which is divided into sub-unions based on states of origin. The vast majority of [[Nigeria]]ns arrived in [[Japan]] from the mid-1980s onwards.\n\n==Migration history==\nNigerians and other [[West Africa]]n migrants began coming to Japan in the mid-1980s as migrant workers.<ref name=\"Kawada172\">{{harvnb|Kawada|2008|p=172}}</ref> Legal migrants often enter via student visas, which allow them to work for a limited number of hours each week.<ref name=\"Cybriwsky138\">{{harvnb|Cybriwsky|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NvMOfX1XG3UC&pg=PA138 138]}}</ref> As of 2017 Japan has significantly eased restrictions on skilled immigrants gaining permanent right-to-remain visas, making them a logical follow-on from student visas.<ref>[http://uk.businessinsider.com/how-to-move-to-japan-2017-3?r=US&IR=T/#the-final-step-if-you-havent-already-embrace-japanese-culture-7 It just got easier to become a permanent resident of Japan] Business Insider. Chris Weller. 08/03/17. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref>\n\nThere are a number of organizations for Nigerian immigrants in Japan. The Nigerian Union in Japan, the oldest one, was founded in 1990. The Nigerian Union restarted twice, most recently in 2010. The [[Imo State]] Union, founded in 2002, replaced it to become the largest and most active, and has formally applied for non-profit status under Japanese law.<ref name=\"Richard\">{{citation|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20110719zg.html|title=Japan's Nigerians pay price for prosperity: Facing apathy within and racism without, a disunited community struggles to thrive on society's periphery|first=Dreux|last=Richard|date=2011-07-19|accessdate=2012-12-09|periodical=The Japan Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018190626/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20110719zg.html|archivedate=2012-10-18}}</ref>\n\n==Business and employment==\nSome Nigerian migrants during the 1980s found work in factories.<ref name=\"Kawada172\"/> Later, after the end of the [[Japanese asset price bubble]] reduced opportunities for such work, they shifted into the night-life industry in Tokyo's entertainment districts such as [[Kabukich\u014d, Tokyo|Kabukich\u014d]] or [[Roppongi]], a line of employment with a high level of public visibility. Many of the bars in these areas were previously owned by [[Chinese people in Japan|Chinese]] or [[Koreans in Japan|Koreans]], but during a police crackdown in 2002, closed down; Nigerians took advantage of the resulting business vacuum to open their own bars, and hired their fellow countrymen as workers.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\">{{citation|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fd20070218pb.html|periodical=Japan Times|title='Africans in Japan' . . . not from the quill of Ishihara, thank God|last=Brasor|first=Philip|date=2007-02-18|accessdate=2011-06-25}}</ref> Typically, Nigerians can be seen on the street as touts and bouncers for bars. Many of the migrants working in this industry are in training for or have completed qualifications for professional positions such as engineering in institutions in their home countries or in Japan, but were unable to find any other kind of work in Japan suited to their level of education.<ref>{{harvnb|Cybriwsky|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NvMOfX1XG3UC&pg=PA140 140]}}</ref> There are many Nigerian organizations in Japan. Most are affiliated with the Houston, Texas USA-based Nigerian Union Diaspora (NUD), which is the umbrella Non-Governmental Organization (NGO) for the economic and political empowerment of the people of Nigerian descent outside Nigeria.\n\n==Interethnic relations==\nNigerians have a very poor public image in Japan, with public reports of their activities often focused on crime and scams in bar districts to the exclusion of other aspects of the community. Some Nigerian bar and club owners have been known to spike alcoholic drinks and rob their customers.<ref>[https://japantoday.com/category/crime/tokyo-bar-owner-3-hostesses-arrested-for-drugging-robbing-customer Tokyo bar owner, 3 hostesses arrested for drugging, robbing customer] Japan Today. 02/09/13. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref> These incidents have become associated with a racist stereotype towards the Nigerian community by much of the Japanese population, inflaming tensions further.<ref>[https://japantoday.com/category/features/lifestyle/the-other-side-of-tokyos-nigerian-community The other side of Tokyo's Nigerian community] Japan Today. Dreux Richard. 02/08/11. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nFrom 2011-2016, American author Dreux Richard worked as The Japan Times' Special Correspondent covering the African community in Japan, publishing a series of feature articles on the Nigerian community in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://features.japantimes.co.jp/nigerians-in-japan/|title=Sincerely, Little Nigeria|last=Times|first=The Japan|website=features.japantimes.co.jp|access-date=2016-03-23}}</ref> The Japan Times' stories included coverage of civic organizations, cultural groups, religious institutions, the red light districts, marriage and family life, and claims of an emerging 'integration gap' separating well-integrated African immigrants from those struggling after arriving in Japan.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{further|:Category:Japanese people of Nigerian descent}}\n* [[Ado Onaiwu]], professional [[football player]]\n* [[Andy Ologun]], [[K-1]] kickboxer and professional [[mixed martial artist]]\n* [[Bobby Ologun]], ''[[gaijin tarento]]''<ref name=\"JapanTimes\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation|last=Cybriwsky|first=Roman Adrian|title=Roppongi Crossing: The Demise of a Tokyo Nightclub District and the Reshaping of a Global City|publisher=University of Georgia Press|year=2011|isbn=9780820338316}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru] |script-title=ja:\u6771\u4eac\u306e\u897f\u30a2\u30d5\u30ea\u30ab\u7cfb\u51fa\u8eab\u8005\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u6226\u8853 : \u516d\u672c\u6728\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u696d\u5f93\u4e8b\u8005\u3092\u4e8b\u4f8b\u3068\u3057\u3066 |trans-title=Life tactics of West African migrants in Tokyo: a study of service-industry workers in Roppongi |journal={{asiantitle|\u6176\u5fdc\u7fa9\u587e\u5927\u5b66\u5927\u5b66\u9662\u793e\u4f1a\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u79d1\u7d00\u8981|||j}}|volume=60|pages=71&ndash;92|url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/120002317597|year=2005|ref=CITEREFKawada2005|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru] |script-chapter=ja:\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u3068\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u65e5\u7c73\u6bd4\u8f03\u2014\u2014\u95a2\u6771\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u30c6\u30ad\u30b5\u30b9\u5dde\u306e\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u4e8b\u4f8b\u304b\u3089 |trans-chapter=USA-Japan comparison of life and capital formation among Nigerian migrants: based on migrants in Kanto and Texas|date=December 2008|series=Intriguing Asia|volume=117|pages=172\u2013179|isbn=978-4-585-10414-8|title={{asiantitle|\u65e5\u672c\u3067\u66ae\u3089\u3059\u5916\u56fd\u4eba||Foreigners living in Japan|j}}|publisher=Bensey Publishing|oclc=294935624|ref=CITEREFKawada2008}}\n** Summary presentation available online: {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|url=http://www.gakkai.ne.jp/jss/research/point/04/004_072.pdf|journal=Annual meeting of the Japan Sociological Society|volume=81 |script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u3068\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u4e8b\u4f8b\u5831\u544a\u2014\u2014\u95a2\u6771\u5730\u57df\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u30c6\u30ad\u30b5\u30b9\u5dde\u306e\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u304b\u3089\u306e\u805e\u304d\u53d6\u308a\u8abf\u67fb\u304b\u3089 |trans-title=Community and capital formation among Nigerian migrants in Japan and the United States: based on research among migrants in Texas and Kanto | date=November 2008 |accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|author=\u548c\u5d0e\u6625\u65e5 [Wazaki Haruka]|script-title=ja:\u6ede\u65e5\u30a2\u30d5\u30ea\u30ab\u4eba\u306e\u30a2\u30bd\u30b7\u30a8\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u8a2d\u7acb\u884c\u52d5\u3068\u96c6\u4f1a\u6d3b\u52d5 |trans-title=Group activities and association formation activities among Africans staying in Japan|url=http://ir.nul.nagoya-u.ac.jp/jspui/bitstream/2237/10560/1/%E5%92%8C%E5%B4%8E%E3%80%80%E6%98%A5%E6%97%A5%E3%80%80p.1-19.pdf|journal={{asiantitle|\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u5927\u5b66\u6587\u5b66\u90e8\u7814\u7a76\u8ad6\u96c6|||j}}|volume=54| date=March 2008 |pages=1&ndash;19|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/area/nigeria/index.html|script-chapter=ja:\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u9023\u90a6\u5171\u548c\u56fd|title={{asiantitle|\u5404\u56fd\u30fb\u5730\u57df\u60c5\u52e2}}|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Japan|publication-place=Tokyo|year=2010|accessdate=2011-06-25|ref=CITEREFMOFA2010}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|year=2006|script-title=ja:\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u306e\u5171\u540c\u6027\u306e\u69cb\u7bc9\u2500\u30a4\u30e2\u5dde\u540c\u90f7\u4eba\u56e3\u4f53\u304c\u3064\u306a\u3050\u30a4\u30dc\u6c11\u65cf\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u4e16\u754c |trans-title=Structure of cooperation among Nigerians in Japan: Imo State migrant organisations and Ibo people's lives|journal={{asiantitle|\u751f\u6d3b\u5b66\u8ad6\u53e2|||j}}|volume=11|pages=127&ndash;138}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru] |script-title=ja:\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u306e\u5f62\u6210\u2015\u2015\u76f8\u4e92\u6276\u52a9\u3092\u4ecb\u3057\u305f\u8d77\u696d\u5bb6\u306e\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210 |trans-title=Community formation among Nigerians in Japan: Mutual assistance through entrepreneurial capital formation|journal=Kantoh Sociological Association Annual Review|number=20|date=July 2007}}\n* {{citation|first=Djamila|last=Schans|chapter=Lost in Translation? Marriages between African immigrants and Japanese women|title=IMISCOE conference on Interethnic Relations: Multidisciplinary Approaches|date=2009-05-23|publication-place=Lisbon, Portugal|url=http://imiscoecrosscluster.weebly.com/uploads/4/6/9/4/469440/schans_imiscoemay2009.pdf|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nigerianunionjapan.net/ Nigerian Union in Japan]\n\n{{Nigerian diaspora}}\n{{Igbo topics}}\n{{Immigration to Japan}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese people of Nigerian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Nigerian diaspora in Asia|Japan]]\n[[Category:Igbo diaspora|Japan]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Nigerians in Japan<BR/>\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\n|population = 2,797 (Dec 2016)<ref>{{harvnb|MOFA|2010|loc=[http://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/area/nigeria/data.html \u57fa\u790e\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf]}}</ref>\n|popplace   = [[Tokyo]]\n|langs      = [[English language|English]] ([[Nigerian English]]), [[Igbo language|Igbo]] and other [[languages of Nigeria]]; [[Japanese language|Japanese]]<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n|rels       = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Nigerians in Japan'''|\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba|Zainichi Naijeriajin}} form a significant immigrant community, with around 2800 living in the country, mostly belonging to the Nigerian Union in Japan which is divided into sub-unions based on states of origin. The vast majority of [[Nigeria]]ns arrived in [[Japan]] from the mid-1980s onwards.\n\n==Migration history==\nNigerians and other [[West Africa]]n migrants began coming to Japan in the mid-1980s as migrant workers.<ref name=\"Kawada172\">{{harvnb|Kawada|2008|p=172}}</ref> Legal migrants often enter via student visas, which allow them to work for a limited number of hours each week.<ref name=\"Cybriwsky138\">{{harvnb|Cybriwsky|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NvMOfX1XG3UC&pg=PA138 138]}}</ref>. As of 2017 Japan has significantly eased restrictions on skilled immigrants gaining permanent right-to-remain visas, making them a logical follow-on from student visas.<ref>[http://uk.businessinsider.com/how-to-move-to-japan-2017-3?r=US&IR=T/#the-final-step-if-you-havent-already-embrace-japanese-culture-7 It just got easier to become a permanent resident of Japan] Business Insider. Chris Weller. 08/03/17. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref>\n\nThere are a number of organizations for Nigerian immigrants in Japan. The Nigerian Union in Japan, the oldest one, was founded in 1990. The Nigerian Union restarted twice, most recently in 2010. The [[Imo State]] Union, founded in 2002, replaced it to become the largest and most active, and has formally applied for non-profit status under Japanese law.<ref name=\"Richard\">{{citation|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20110719zg.html|title=Japan's Nigerians pay price for prosperity: Facing apathy within and racism without, a disunited community struggles to thrive on society's periphery|first=Dreux|last=Richard|date=2011-07-19|accessdate=2012-12-09|periodical=The Japan Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018190626/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20110719zg.html|archivedate=2012-10-18}}</ref>\n\n==Business and employment==\nSome Nigerian migrants during the 1980s found work in factories.<ref name=\"Kawada172\"/> Later, after the end of the [[Japanese asset price bubble]] reduced opportunities for such work, they shifted into the night-life industry in Tokyo's entertainment districts such as [[Kabukich\u014d, Tokyo|Kabukich\u014d]] or [[Roppongi]], a line of employment with a high level of public visibility. Many of the bars in these areas were previously owned by [[Chinese people in Japan|Chinese]] or [[Koreans in Japan|Koreans]], but during a police crackdown in 2002, closed down; Nigerians took advantage of the resulting business vacuum to open their own bars, and hired their fellow countrymen as workers.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\">{{citation|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fd20070218pb.html|periodical=Japan Times|title='Africans in Japan' . . . not from the quill of Ishihara, thank God|last=Brasor|first=Philip|date=2007-02-18|accessdate=2011-06-25}}</ref> Typically, Nigerians can be seen on the street as touts and bouncers for bars. Many of the migrants working in this industry are in training for or have completed qualifications for professional positions such as engineering in institutions in their home countries or in Japan, but were unable to find any other kind of work in Japan suited to their level of education.<ref>{{harvnb|Cybriwsky|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NvMOfX1XG3UC&pg=PA140 140]}}</ref> There are many Nigerian organizations in Japan. Most are affiliated with the Houston, Texas USA-based Nigerian Union Diaspora (NUD), which is the umbrella Non-Governmental Organization (NGO) for the economic and political empowerment of the people of Nigerian descent outside Nigeria.\n\n==Interethnic relations==\nNigerians have a very poor public image in Japan, with public reports of their activities often focused on crime and scams in bar districts to the exclusion of other aspects of the community. Some Nigerian bar and club owners have been known to spike alcoholic drinks and rob their customers.<ref>[https://japantoday.com/category/crime/tokyo-bar-owner-3-hostesses-arrested-for-drugging-robbing-customer Tokyo bar owner, 3 hostesses arrested for drugging, robbing customer] Japan Today. 02/09/13. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref> These incidents have become associated with a racist stereotype towards the Nigerian community by much of the Japanese population, inflaming tensions further.<ref>[https://japantoday.com/category/features/lifestyle/the-other-side-of-tokyos-nigerian-community The other side of Tokyo's Nigerian community] Japan Today. Dreux Richard. 02/08/11. Retrieved: 17/05/18</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nFrom 2011-2016, American author Dreux Richard worked as The Japan Times' Special Correspondent covering the African community in Japan, publishing a series of feature articles on the Nigerian community in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://features.japantimes.co.jp/nigerians-in-japan/|title=Sincerely, Little Nigeria|last=Times|first=The Japan|website=features.japantimes.co.jp|access-date=2016-03-23}}</ref> The Japan Times' stories included coverage of civic organizations, cultural groups, religious institutions, the red light districts, marriage and family life, and claims of an emerging 'integration gap' separating well-integrated African immigrants from those struggling after arriving in Japan.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{further information|:Category:Japanese people of Nigerian descent}}\n* [[Ado Onaiwu]], professional [[football player]]\n* [[Andy Ologun]], [[K-1]] kickboxer and professional [[mixed martial artist]]\n* [[Bobby Ologun]], ''[[gaijin tarento]]''<ref name=\"JapanTimes\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation|last=Cybriwsky|first=Roman Adrian|title=Roppongi Crossing: The Demise of a Tokyo Nightclub District and the Reshaping of a Global City|publisher=University of Georgia Press|year=2011|isbn=9780820338316}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|title=\u6771\u4eac\u306e\u897f\u30a2\u30d5\u30ea\u30ab\u7cfb\u51fa\u8eab\u8005\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u6226\u8853 : \u516d\u672c\u6728\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u696d\u5f93\u4e8b\u8005\u3092\u4e8b\u4f8b\u3068\u3057\u3066 {{bracket|Life tactics of West African migrants in Tokyo: a study of service-industry workers in Roppongi}}|journal={{asiantitle|\u6176\u5fdc\u7fa9\u587e\u5927\u5b66\u5927\u5b66\u9662\u793e\u4f1a\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u79d1\u7d00\u8981|||j}}|volume=60|pages=71&ndash;92|url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/120002317597|year=2005|ref=CITEREFKawada2005|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|chapter=\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u3068\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u65e5\u7c73\u6bd4\u8f03\u2014\u2014\u95a2\u6771\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u30c6\u30ad\u30b5\u30b9\u5dde\u306e\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u4e8b\u4f8b\u304b\u3089 [USA-Japan comparison of life and capital formation among Nigerian migrants: based on migrants in Kanto and Texas]|date=December 2008|series=Intriguing Asia|volume=117|pages=172\u2013179|isbn=978-4-585-10414-8|title={{asiantitle|\u65e5\u672c\u3067\u66ae\u3089\u3059\u5916\u56fd\u4eba||Foreigners living in Japan|j}}|publisher=Bensey Publishing|oclc=294935624|ref=CITEREFKawada2008}}\n** Summary presentation available online: {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|url=http://www.gakkai.ne.jp/jss/research/point/04/004_072.pdf|journal=Annual meeting of the Japan Sociological Society|volume=81|title=\u65e5\u672c\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u3068\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u4e8b\u4f8b\u5831\u544a\u2014\u2014\u95a2\u6771\u5730\u57df\u3068\u7c73\u56fd\u30c6\u30ad\u30b5\u30b9\u5dde\u306e\u79fb\u4f4f\u8005\u304b\u3089\u306e\u805e\u304d\u53d6\u308a\u8abf\u67fb\u304b\u3089 {{bracket|Community and capital formation among Nigerian migrants in Japan and the United States: based on research among migrants in Texas and Kanto}}| date=November 2008 |accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|author=\u548c\u5d0e\u6625\u65e5 [Wazaki Haruka]|title=\u6ede\u65e5\u30a2\u30d5\u30ea\u30ab\u4eba\u306e\u30a2\u30bd\u30b7\u30a8\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u8a2d\u7acb\u884c\u52d5\u3068\u96c6\u4f1a\u6d3b\u52d5 {{bracket|Group activities and association formation activities among Africans staying in Japan}}|url=http://ir.nul.nagoya-u.ac.jp/jspui/bitstream/2237/10560/1/%E5%92%8C%E5%B4%8E%E3%80%80%E6%98%A5%E6%97%A5%E3%80%80p.1-19.pdf|journal={{asiantitle|\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u5927\u5b66\u6587\u5b66\u90e8\u7814\u7a76\u8ad6\u96c6|||j}}|volume=54| date=March 2008 |pages=1&ndash;19|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n* {{citation|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/area/nigeria/index.html|chapter=\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u9023\u90a6\u5171\u548c\u56fd|title={{asiantitle|\u5404\u56fd\u30fb\u5730\u57df\u60c5\u52e2}}|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Japan|publication-place=Tokyo|year=2010|accessdate=2011-06-25|ref=CITEREFMOFA2010}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|year=2006|title=\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u306e\u5171\u540c\u6027\u306e\u69cb\u7bc9\u2500\u30a4\u30e2\u5dde\u540c\u90f7\u4eba\u56e3\u4f53\u304c\u3064\u306a\u3050\u30a4\u30dc\u6c11\u65cf\u306e\u751f\u6d3b\u4e16\u754c [Structure of cooperation among Nigerians in Japan: Imo State migrant organisations and Ibo people's lives]|journal={{asiantitle|\u751f\u6d3b\u5b66\u8ad6\u53e2|||j}}|volume=11|pages=127&ndash;138}}\n* {{citation|author=\u5ddd\u7530\u85ab [Kawada Kaoru]|title=\u5728\u65e5\u30ca\u30a4\u30b8\u30a7\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30b3\u30df\u30e5\u30cb\u30c6\u30a3\u306e\u5f62\u6210\u2015\u2015\u76f8\u4e92\u6276\u52a9\u3092\u4ecb\u3057\u305f\u8d77\u696d\u5bb6\u306e\u8cc7\u672c\u5f62\u6210 [Community formation among Nigerians in Japan: Mutual assistance through entrepreneurial capital formation]|journal=Kantoh Sociological Association Annual Review|number=20|date=July 2007}}\n* {{citation|first=Djamila|last=Schans|chapter=Lost in Translation? Marriages between African immigrants and Japanese women|title=IMISCOE conference on Interethnic Relations: Multidisciplinary Approaches|date=2009-05-23|publication-place=Lisbon, Portugal|url=http://imiscoecrosscluster.weebly.com/uploads/4/6/9/4/469440/schans_imiscoemay2009.pdf|accessdate=2011-06-25}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nigerianunionjapan.net/ Nigerian Union in Japan]\n\n{{Nigerian diaspora}}\n{{Igbo topics}}\n{{Immigration to Japan}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese people of Nigerian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Nigerian diaspora in Asia|Japan]]\n[[Category:Igbo diaspora|Japan]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Japan]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref work: script-title, quote, zh in Publisher, etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigerians_in_Japan"}
{"title_page": "Dagenham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{infobox UK place\n| static_image_name = File:Beam valley park and turbine 1.jpg\n| static_image_caption = The southern Dagenham skyline includes structures of the Ford plant and [[Dagenham wind turbines|wind turbines]].\n| country = England\n| region = London\n| official_name = Dagenham\n| post_town = DAGENHAM\n| postcode_area = RM\n| postcode_district = RM8, RM9, RM10\n| london_borough = Barking and Dagenham\n| dial_code = 020\n| os_grid_reference = TQ485845\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5397|0.1422|display=inline,title}}\n| constituency_westminster = [[Dagenham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Dagenham and Rainham]]\n| constituency_westminster1 = [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]]\n| charingX_distance_mi = 11.5\n| charingX_direction = W\n| population = 106,247\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref>Dagenham is made up of 100 wards in the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham: Alibon, Becontree, Eastbrook, Goresbrook, Heath, Mayesbrook, Parsloes, River, Valence, and Village. {{cite web|url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi = \n}}\n'''Dagenham''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|\u0261|\u0259n|\u0259|m}}) is a district and [[suburban]] town in East [[London]], England.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.london.gov.uk/thelondonplan/images/maps-diagrams/jpg/map-5c-1.jpg | title=North East London sub-region | accessdate=12 August 2012 | publisher=Greater London Authority | author=Mayor of London }}</ref> In the [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]], it is 11.5 miles (18.5&nbsp;km) east of [[Charing Cross]]. Historically a [[Civil parish#Ancient Parish|parish]] in the county of [[Essex]], it was an agrarian village and remained mostly undeveloped until 1921, when the [[London County Council]] began construction of the large [[Becontree]] estate. The population of the area significantly increased in the 20th century, with the parish of Dagenham [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham|becoming an urban district]] in 1926 and a municipal borough in 1938. It has formed part of [[Greater London]] since 1965 and is a predominantly residential area, with some areas of declining industrial activity, including the [[Ford Dagenham]] plant. The southern part of Dagenham, adjacent to the [[River Thames]], forms part of the [[London Riverside]] section of the [[Thames Gateway]] redevelopment area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/worst-places-to-live-in-the-uk-barking-and-dagenham-come-first-in-top-ten-list-dominated-by-nine-10442606.html|title=Nine out of ten of the worst places to live in the UK are in London|date=2015-08-06|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The total population of Dagenham, including the Becontree estate, was 106,247 as of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:10px;\"\n|+'''Dagenham (parish) population'''\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1881\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3,411\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1891\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4,324\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1901\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6,091\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1911\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7,930\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1921\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9,127\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1931\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 89,362\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1941\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| #\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1951\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 114,568\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1961\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 108,368\n|-\n|style=\"font-size:smaller\" colspan=2|# no census was held due to war\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size:smaller; text-align:center;\"|source: UK census\n|}\n\n===Toponomy===\nDagenham first appeared in a document (as ''D\u00e6ccanhaam'') in a charter of [[Barking Abbey]] dating from 666 AD (though alternative 7th century dates have been suggested for the charter). The name almost certainly originated with a small farmstead, the \"ham\" or farm of a man called Daecca, as ''D\u00e6ccan hamm'' in [[Old English]] means ''home of a man called D\u00e6cca''.<ref name=mills29>{{Harvnb|Mills|2001|p=64}}</ref> The charter was made to reflect a transfer of land from Aethelred, kinsman of [[Saebbi of Essex|King Saebbi of Essex]], to Barking Abbey.<ref>On the context of the charter https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol5/pp190-214</ref>\n\n===Manor of Barking===\nDagenham has been historically defined by its [[Civil Parish#Ancient parishes|Ancient Parish]] boundaries, which were subsequently re-used by the [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham]] up until 1965. The parish of Dagenham was formed in the medieval period to serve - along with parish of [[Barking, London|Barking]] (which included [[Ilford|Great Ilford]] until the 19th century)<ref>on the history of the Manor of Barking https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol5/pp190-214</ref> - the people of the huge manor of Barking, which was owned by the Nunnery of [[Barking Abbey]]. This reversed the usual situation where a parish would serve one or more manors.\nAs with other manors, the area held by the declined over time, but the parish boundaries based on its former extent remained constant. Barking Abbey was dissolved in 1539.\n\n===Pre-urban landscape===\nLike most Essex [[River Thames|Thames-side]] parishes, Dagenham was laid out on a N-S axis to give it a share of the marshes by the river, the agricultural land in the centre and the woods and commons on the poorer soils on the high ground in the north. Dagenham included a significant part of the now mostly lost [[Hainault Forest]].\n\n===Dagenham Breach===\nDagenham was protected from the Thames by defences built in the 17th century by Dutch engineers. In 1704 an exceptionally high tide swept away fourteen feet of embankment and flooded nearly 5,000 acres of land. The breach widened over time to a width of 400 feet, allowing the Thames to strip  the top layer of marsh clay from the flood plain and deposited it as a mud bank in the Thames where it became a danger to shipping.\n\nThe gap in the wall was replaced by 1714 in a celebrated act of civil engineering. The closure of the gap left behind a large lake, known as Dagenham Breach, which became a popular spot for anglers. The lake is still there, but much has silted up or been filled in, and it is now surrounded by industry.<ref>http://www.barkinghistory.co.uk/dagenham-breach.html</ref>\n\n===Whitebait Dinners===\nDagenham was formerly home to the famous annual whitebait feast. The custom appears to have been started by the King's Commissioner of Works to celebrate the closure of the breach in the seawall around 1714\u201320, and was held every subsequent spring, on or around [[Trinity Sunday]].\n\nMany years later, [[Sir Robert Preston, 6th Baronet|Sir Robert Preston MP]], invited his friend [[George Rose (politician)|George Rose]] the Secretary of the Treasury and others to celebrate the feast, and on another occasion Rose invited the Prime Minister, [[William Pitt the Younger|William Pitt]]. Thereafter it became an obligatory ritual of government for the entire cabinet to come to Dagenham and celebrate the security of the Thames and over time this simple but hearty meal based on Whitebait and local Essex Ale grew more lavish, including turtle, grouse, champagne and a range of other luxury food and drink. Eventually the cabinet tired of the long trip to Dagenham and moved the event to [[Greenwich]].<ref>Simon Schama \u2013 Landscape and Memory p352-354</ref>\n\n===Economic development===\n[[File:Ford Dagenham.jpg|left|thumb|[[Ford Dagenham|Ford Dagenham Terminal]]]]\nIn 1931 the [[Ford of Britain|Ford Motor Company]] relocated from [[Trafford Park]] in Manchester, to a [[Ford Dagenham|plant in Dagenham]], which was already the location of supplier Briggs Motorway Bodies. A 500-acre (2&nbsp;km\u00b2) riverside site was developed to become Europe's largest car plant, a vast [[Vertical integration|vertically integrated]] site with its own [[blast furnace]]s and power station, importing iron ore and exporting finished vehicles. By the 1950s Ford had taken over Briggs at Dagenham and its other sites at [[Doncaster]], [[Southampton]], [[Croydon]] and [[Romford]]. At its peak the Dagenham plant had {{convert|4000000|ft2}} of floor space and employed over 40,000 people, although this number gradually fell during the final three decades of the 20th century as production methods advanced and Ford invested in other European factories as well.<ref>Ford UK \u2013 [http://www.ford.co.uk/ie/htg_fib/-/htg_fib_WW21970/-/-/-/- History of Ford in Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217091509/http://www.ford.co.uk/ie/htg_fib/-/htg_fib_WW21970/-/-/-/- |date=17 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2002, full production was discontinued due to overcapacity in Europe and the relative difficulty of upgrading the 60-year-old site compared with other European sites such as [[Almussafes]] ([[Valencia (province)|Valencia]], [[Spain]]) and [[Cologne]]. Other factors leading to the closure of the Auto-assembly line were the need of the site for the new Diesel Centre of Excellence, which produces half of Ford's Diesel Engines worldwide, and the UK employment laws when compared to Spanish, German and Belgian laws. In 2005 Cummins went into a joint venture and offered $15 million (US) to reinstate the factory. Ford and Cummins offered a good redundancy package, billed as one of the best in UK manufacturing. It is the location of the [[Dagenham wind turbines]].<ref name=gla>Greater London Authority \u2013 ''[http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/planning_decisions/strategic_dev/2003/jun0403/wind_turbines_report_havering.rtf Wind Turbines, Ford Estate, Dagenham planning application] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604095224/http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/planning_decisions/strategic_dev/2003/jun0403/wind_turbines_report_havering.rtf |date=4 June 2011 }}''. 4 June 2003.</ref> Some 4,000 people now work at the Ford plant.<ref>[http://www.thedetroitbureau.com/2009/05/milestones-ford-dagenham-estate-celebrates-80-years-of-manufacturing/ Milestones: Ford Dagenham Estate Celebrates 80 Years of Manufacturing]. TheDetroitBureau.com (13 May 2009). Retrieved on 2012-08-08.</ref> The movie ''[[Made in Dagenham]]'' (2010) is a dramatisation of the [[1968 Ford sewing machinists strike]] at the plant, when female workers walked out in protest against sexual discrimination and unequal pay.\n\n[[Sterling Armaments Company|Sterling]] who were famous for manufacturing British Army weapons and Jaguar car parts were also based in Dagenham until they went bankrupt in 1988.  Other industrial names once known worldwide were [[British Ever Ready Electrical Company|Ever Ready]], whose batteries could be found in shops throughout the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], [[Asian Paints|Bergers Paint]] and the chemical firm of [[May & Baker]] who in 1935 revolutionized the production of [[antibiotics]] with their synthetic sulfa-drug known as [[Sulfapyridine|M&B 693]].  The May & Baker plant, owned and run by [[Sanofi-Aventis]], occupied a 108-acre site in Rainham Road South, near [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East Underground station]].  It was abandoned in 2013 when the company closed it.  The council has decided how to use the vacant site.  They will redevelop it with a new shopping centre: stores announced so far are a [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket and a pub restaurant.  More stores will be announced in the future.\n\n===Local government===\nDagenham was an ancient, and later civil, parish in the [[Becontree (hundred)|Becontree]] hundred of [[Essex]].<ref>British History Online \u2013 [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/image.aspx?compid=42721&filename=fig13.gif&pubid=280 The Hundred of Becontree]</ref> The [[Metropolitan Police District]] was extended in 1840 to include Dagenham. The parish formed part of the [[Romford Rural District]] from 1894.<ref name=parish>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 Dagenham parish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001032034/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 |date=1 October 2007 }} ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 historic map] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930225859/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }})</ref><ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 Romford RD] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181214/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }} ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 historic map]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181611/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }})</ref> Dagenham Parish Council offices were located on Bull Street.\n\nThe expansion of the Greater London conurbation into the area caused the review of local government structures, and it was suggested in 1920 that the Dagenham parish should be abolished and its area divided between [[Municipal Borough of Ilford|Ilford Urban District]] and [[Municipal Borough of Barking|Barking Town Urban District]].<ref name=barking/> Separately, the London County Council proposed that its area of responsibility should be expanded beyond the [[County of London]] to cover the area.<ref>''Greater London: Case for Central Authority: Area and Powers''. ''The Times.'' 14 December 1921.</ref> Instead, in 1926 the Dagenham parish was removed from the Romford Rural District and designated as an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]].<ref name=parish/> In 1938, in further recognition of its development, Dagenham became a [[municipal borough]].<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025928 Dagenham MB] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001043633/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025928 |date=1 October 2007 }}</ref> In 1965 the [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham]] was abolished and its former area became part of the [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham|London Borough of Barking]],<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10166901 Barking LB]</ref> which was renamed Barking and Dagenham in 1980.<ref>Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council \u2013 [http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/9-democracy/mayor/mayor-past.html The Mayor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926223705/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/9-democracy/mayor/mayor-past.html |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Market gardens to suburban estate===\n[[File:Dagenham village.jpg|thumb|The [[St Peter and St Paul, Dagenham|church of St Peter and St Paul]] formed the heart of the former village]]\n\nIn 1205 Dagenham was large enough to have a [[chaplain]], and the [[St Peter and St Paul's Church, Dagenham|Parish Church of St Peter and St Paul]] was probably built at around that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/dag-village/dvil-main-menu.html |title=Old Dagenham Village |publisher=Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council |work=Heritage and History |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104182814/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/dag-village/dvil-main-menu.html |archivedate=4 January 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1854, the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]] was built through the south of Dagenham, near the River Thames. In 1885 a new direct route from Barking to Pitsea, via Upminster, was built with [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham]] station opened just north of the village. [[Dagenham Dock railway station|Dagenham Dock]] station opened on the original southern route in 1908. Dagenham was still an undeveloped village, when building of the vast [[Becontree]] estate by the [[London County Council]] began in the early 1920s.<ref>Olechnowicz, A., ''Working-Class Housing in England Between the Wars: The Becontree Estate'' (1997)</ref> The building of the enormous council estate, which also spread into the neighbouring parishes of [[Ilford]] and [[Barking, London|Barking]],<ref name=barking>British History Online \u2013 ''[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=42729&strquery=barking The borough of Barking]''. Date accessed: 5 May 2007.</ref> caused a rapid increase in population.<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043&add=N Dagenham population]</ref> In 1932 the electrified [[District line]] of the [[London Underground]] was extended to [[Upminster]] through Dagenham with stations opened as ''Dagenham'' and ''Heathway'' and today called [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East]] and [[Dagenham Heathway tube station|Dagenham Heathway]].<ref>Rose, D., ''The London Underground: A diagrammatic history'', (1999)</ref> Dagenham East was the location of the [[Dagenham East rail crash]] in 1958.<ref>Railways Archive \u2013 [http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_Dagenham1958.pdf Report on the collision at Dagenham East \u2013 30.01.58]</ref> Services on the London Tilbury & Southend line at Dagenham East were withdrawn in 1962.\n\n==Governance==\nThe wards of Eastbrook, Heath, River, Village and Whalebone are in the [[Dagenham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Dagenham and Rainham Parliamentary Constituency]]. The wards of Alibon, Mayesbrook, Parsloes, Thames and Valence are in the [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking Parliamentary Constituency]]. Each ward elects three councillors to [[Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council]]. The whole area is within the [[City and East (London Assembly constituency)|City and East London Assembly Constituency]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Beam valley park.jpg|thumb|The [[River Rom|River Beam]] in the south of Dagenham]]\nDagenham is located approximately {{convert|11.5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Charing Cross]] in Central London. The [[Becontree]] estate is largely in the pre-1965 borough of Dagenham, which also  also included [[Becontree Heath]], part of [[Rush Green, London|Rush Green]], Old Dagenham village, and the southern section around [[Dagenham Dock]] and adjacent to the [[River Thames]]. This southern section, which includes [[Ford Dagenham]], is part of the [[London Riverside]] section of the [[Thames Gateway]] redevelopment zone. The Dagenham [[post town]] includes the whole of the Becontree estate, including those sections that were in the former (pre 1965) boroughs of Barking and Ilford. Parts of the former borough of Dagenham - part of Chadwell Heath, part of Collier Row and part of Rush Green - are in the Romford Post town.\n\n(Dagenham is the name of a post town, and of a pre-1965 borough (and parish before that) with very different boundaries to the post town. Perhaps because of the name 'London Borough of Barking & Dagenham', adopted on 1 January 1980 to replace 'London Borough of Barking', there is an apparent popular - but incorrect - assumption that everywhere in that borough is either in Barking or in Dagenham. From 1965 it was true to say that everywhere in the then new London Borough was in one of the two former boroughs, but in the mid 1990s substantial areas of the London Borough of Redbridge were transferred to the borough, such that the entire Becontree and Padnall Estates were in LB Barking and Dagenham. Furthermore, parts of three post towns - Barking, Dagenham and Romford - cover the borough. The parliamentary constituency of Dagenham, formed in 1945, ceased to exist from the 2010 General Election, the six easternmost wards of LB Barking & Dagenham having become part of the Dagenham & Rainham Constituency,  with three wards in LB Havering, leaving most LB Barking & Dagenham wards in the enlarged Barking constituency.)\n\n==Demography==\nDagenham is a working class area. During the 2000s [does this mean 2000-09?] there was a large influx of migrants, in particular Africans.<ref name=\"observer article industrial history\">{{cite news | author = Asthana, Anushka |author-link=Anushka Asthana| title = Dagenham's heyday: 'It was all just one big happy family then' | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 21 March 2010 | pages = 18\u201319 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/mar/21/dagenham-barking-ford-industrial-history | accessdate = 23 March 2010}}</ref> The current population of the former (pre 1965) Borough of Dagenham could be approximated from the population of the current wards which together most closely match the area, but the former boundary between the borough and neighbouring Barking, with which it merged in 1965, no longer corresponds to any ward boundaries.\n\nAt the time of the 2011 census, the Alibon ward (north of Heathway station) was 61% White British and 15% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/alibon-e05000027|title=Alibon - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Goresbrook ward (southwest from Heathway) was 57% White British and 17% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/goresbrook-e05000033|title=Goresbrook - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> River ward (south of Heathway) was 51% White British and 19% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/river-e05000038|title=River - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Village ward (east from Heathway) was 58% White British and 19% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/village-e05000041|title=Village - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Eastbrook ward (around Eastbrookend Country) was 69% White British and 11% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/eastbrook-e05000030|title=Eastbrook - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Heath ward (north of Heathway) was 60% White British and 17% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/heath-e05000034|title=Heath - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nDagenham is connected to the [[London Underground]] services from three stations, [[Becontree tube station|Becontree]] (in the pre-1965 borough of Barking), [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East]] and [[Dagenham Heathway tube station|Dagenham Heathway]], all on the [[District line]].  [[c2c]], part of [[National Rail]] operated by [[Trenitalia]] since February 2017, runs a train service through [[Dagenham Dock railway station|Dagenham Dock station]].<ref>c2c \u2013 [http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/templates/Generic.aspx?id=461 Stations and route map]</ref> [[TfL Rail]] services also operate from nearby [[Chadwell Heath railway station|Chadwell Heath]] station.\n\nA proposed, and as yet unfunded [[Docklands Light Railway]] [[Docklands Light Railway extension to Dagenham Dock|extension]] from [[Gallions Reach DLR station|Gallions Reach]] to [[Dagenham Dock]]. It was anticipated that the project could be completed and open for use by 2017.<ref name=dlr_next>Transport for London - [http://developments.dlr.co.uk/extensions/dagenham/whatnext.asp Docklands Light Railway - Dagenham Dock: Key Project Milestones] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615075056/http://developments.dlr.co.uk/extensions/dagenham/whatnext.asp |date=15 June 2009 }}</ref> However the [[public inquiry]] has been postponed due to concerns about funding.\n\nDagenham Heathway is served by the following [[Transport for London]] contracted routes: [[London Buses]] routes 145,173,174,175,287]] and 364.<ref>[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tfl/gettingaround/maps/buses/pdf/dagenhamheathway-2065.pdf Transport for London \u2013 Buses from Dagenham Heathway -]</ref> Routes 5, 103, 128, 150, 173, 174, 175, 499, and N15 and [[East London Transit]] service EL2 operate from [[Becontree Heath]] or the nearby Dagenham Civic Centre. Route 128 and EL1 runs a 24-hour service, while the N15 runs through the night.<ref>287,62 and many other buses run through this area.[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tfl/gettingaround/maps/buses/pdf/becontreeheath-2020.pdf Transport for London \u2013  Buses from Beacontree Heath \u2013]</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[Valence House Museum|Valence House]], in Becontree Avenue, is the only surviving of the five manor houses of Dagenham.<ref>[http://www.lbbd.gov.uk/museumsandheritage/valencehousemuseum/pages/home.aspx Valence House museum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722073902/http://www.lbbd.gov.uk/museumsandheritage/valencehousemuseum/pages/home.aspx |date=22 July 2012 }}. lbbd.gov.uk</ref>\nDating back to the 13th century, it is sited in parkland and is partially surrounded by a moat. Valence House is the London Borough of Barking & Dagenham's local history museum, displaying artifacts and archives that tell the story of the lives of the people of Barking and Dagenham. The collection also includes portraits, family papers and other mementos of the Fanshawe family, who occupied [[Parsloes Manor]], since demolished, from the sixteenth century.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080904220540/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/local-history/fanshawe-family.html The Fanshawe Family, London Borough of Barking and Dagenham], barking-dagenham.gov.uk</ref>\nThe Fanshawe collection is \"one of the best collections of gentry portraits in the country and is of international importance\", according to Valence House.<ref name=b1>[[Elizabeth Ogborne]], [https://archive.org/details/b22009061/page/61 The History of Essex: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time], Printed for the Proprietors by R.H. Kelham, London, 1814, p. 61.</ref>\nAmong members of the Fanshawe family was the diplomat [[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet]], whose portrait is at Valence House. Nine successive members of the Fanshawe family served as [[Remembrancer]] to the Crown, following Henry Fanshawe's appointment to the position by [[Queen Elizabeth I]] in 1566. The appointment made possible the family's rise to prominence.\n\nIn the post town of Romford and the pre-1965 borough of Dagenham, on the corner of Whalebone Lane and the Eastern Avenue, diagonally opposite the [[Moby-Dick]] public house, is the site of Marks Manor House, a large 15th-century moated building demolished in the early 19th century. During [[World War II]] the adjoining fields were used by the [[Royal Artillery]] for an anti-aircraft battery; later a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] for Germans was erected there. Further south down Whalebone Lane on the corner of the High Road is the Tollgate pub. This stands on the site of the [[milestone]] which marked the ten mile (16&nbsp;km) limit from the [[City of London]] and the [[Turnpike trust|turnpike]] [[toll-gate]].\n\n[[Dagenham Roundhouse|The Roundhouse]] public house on the junction of Porters Avenue and Lodge Avenue (in the pre-1965 borough of Barking) became East London's premier rock-music venue between 1969 and 1975, incorporating the ''Village Blues Club''. Notable performers at the pub included [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]], [[Supertramp]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]], and [[Led Zeppelin]] (on 5 April 1969). The [[Eastbrook, Dagenham|Eastbrook]] is a [[listed building|Grade II* listed]] pub.<ref name=EnglishHeritage>{{NHLE|desc=Eastbrook public house|num=1393600|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\n[[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]], based the London Borough of Barking & Dagenham Stadium (in Victoria Road, Dagenham) were relegated to the  {{English football updater|Dagenh&R}} in the 2015/16 season from the [[Football League Two]], after being relegated from the [[Football League One]] which they had reached having been promoted as [[2010 Football League Two play-off Final|playoff-winners of League two after beating]] [[Rotherham United F.C.]] 3\u20132, in the 2010/11 season. They were the Nationwide Conference champions in the 2006/07 season.\n\nMotorcycle speedway was staged at the greyhound stadium in Ripple Road in the mid to late 1930s. The club run events focussed on training but a team called the Dagenham Daggers did take part in local competitions. It is possible that the venture was operational as early as 1931 a meeting at Caxton (Cambridgeshire) was advertised as Caxton Speedway v Dagenham Speedway.\n\nDagenham's leading cricket club [[Goresbrook Cricket Club]] are based at the May & Baker Sports Club in Rainham Road South, in 2011 the club won the Essex County Cricket League for the first time in its history.\n\nDagenham has a [[List of King George V Playing Fields (Greater London)|King George's Field]] in memorial to [[George V of the United Kingdom|King George V]]. The park, which has been in existence for over a century [give date], was renamed in 1953 by [[Queen Elizabeth II]]. Dagenham also has many other parks such as Valence - and Parsloes (which lies partly in the pre-1965 borough of Barking). '''Dagenham Crusaders Drum and Bugle Corps''', founded by John Johnson, was the first British Drum Corps and performed in America [USA?] for the first time in 1983. They have recently [when?] reformed to perform for DCUK's 30th anniversary, and in 2010 fielded a competitive corps for the first time in 22 years.\n\nThe town is also home to the [[Dagenham Girl Pipers]], a [[bagpipe]] [[marching band]] founded in 1930 by the Revd Joseph Waddington Graves.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Barking and Dagenham}}. Please see 'Geography' above for various definitions of 'Dagenham'.\n* Revd [[Abraham Blackborne]], one of the longest-serving vicars of Dagenham.<ref>{{acad|id=BLKN733A|name=Blackburne, Abraham}}</ref>\n* England international footballer and World Cup-winning manager [[Alf Ramsey]] was born in Dagenham in 1920.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Alf Ramsey|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7624023/Sir-Alf-Ramsey.html|accessdate=6 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 May 1999|location=London}}</ref>\n* St Peter and Paul's Church in Dagenham was once the Parish Church of the former [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]].\n*Musician and comedian [[Dudley Moore]] was brought up in Dagenham,<ref>{{cite web |last=Parkinson|first=David|title=Moore, Dudley Stuart John (1935\u20132002)|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography. Online ed|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/abstract/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-76775?rskey=8AdRhn&result=1 |publisher=Oxford: OUP|edition=Online|date=January 2011}}</ref> which was the home of [[Peter Cook]] and Dudley Moore's famous comic alter-egos ''[[Pete and Dud]]''.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Peter|last1=Cook|first2=Dudley|last2=Moore|year=2003|title=Dud and Pete The Dagenham Dialogues |publisher=Methuen|isbn=978-0-413-77347-0}}</ref>\n*[[Sandie Shaw]], 1960s pop singer, who had a string of hit singles in the decade and won the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in 1967 with [[Puppet on a String]]\n* [[Rap]] artist [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]] is from Dagenham.\n*Actor, comedian, screenwriter, producer and author [[Nick Frost]] is from Dagenham.\n*Depeche Mode member [[Martin Gore]] was born in Dagenham.\n*[[Cage Warriors]] matchmaker Ian Dean is from Dagenham.\n*Australian singer [[John Farnham]]  was born in Dagenham  before migrating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=QIk1DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11&dq=John+Farnham+Dagenham&source=bl&ots=N-conpeTB6&sig=bGAgMCsAqacyBpj_MjShEQJ6xKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRmZrWi93UAhWGJ5QKHQNUBBAQ6AEIYzAJ#v=onepage&q=John+Farnham+Dagenham&f=false|title=Playing to Win: The Definitive Biography of John Farnham|first=Jeff|last=Apter|date=30 October 2016|publisher=Nero|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*Former darts player [[Wayne Mardle]] was born in Dagenham before living in Romford.\n*British singer, TV presenter, and personality [[Stacey Solomon]] is from Dagenham.\n*Rotund Waverley 3rd grade coach [[Scott Sarson]] was born in Dagenham, now living in Coogee.\n\n *Grime MC Syer B grew up in Dagenham\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|title=Dictionary of London Place Names|year=2001|surname=Mills|first=A.D.|publisher=Oxford|ISBN=0-19-280106-6}}\n*{{citation | url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42731| publisher=[[British History Online]] | title=Dagenham, A History of the County of Essex: Volume 5 |series= [[Victoria County History]] | year=1966 | last=Powell | first= W.R. (Edr.)  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n{{refend}}\n* Terry Cooper Death by Dior: Fran\u00e7oise Dior, (Dynasty Press, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-9568038-6-3}})\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation |publisher = Cassell & Co. |publication-place = London |title = Greater London |author = [[Edward Walford]] |publication-date = 1883 |oclc = 3009761 |chapter=Dagenham |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/greaterlondonnar01walf#page/527/mode/1up }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons-inline}}\n\n{{LB Barking & Dagenham}}\n{{London Districts}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Dagenham]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacture in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|static_image_name          = File:Beam valley park and turbine 1.jpg\n|static_image_caption       = The southern Dagenham skyline includes structures of the Ford plant and [[Dagenham wind turbines|wind turbines]].\n|country                    = England\n|region                     = London\n|official_name              = Dagenham\n|post_town                  = DAGENHAM\n|postcode_area              = RM\n|postcode_district          = RM8\u2013RM10\n|london_borough             = Barking and Dagenham\n|dial_code                  = 020\n|os_grid_reference          = TQ485845\n|coordinates                = {{coord|51.5397|0.1422|display=inline,title}}\n|constituency_westminster   = [[Dagenham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Dagenham and Rainham]]\n|constituency_westminster1  = [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]] \n|charingX_distance_mi       = 11.5\n|charingX_direction         = W\n|population = 106,247\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref>Dagenham is made up of 100 wards in the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham: Alibon, Becontree, Eastbrook, Goresbrook, Heath, Mayesbrook, Parsloes, River, Valence, and Village. {{cite web|url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|area_total_sq_mi           = \n}}\n'''Dagenham''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|\u0261|\u0259n|\u0259|m}}) is a district and [[suburban]] town in East [[London]], England.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.london.gov.uk/thelondonplan/images/maps-diagrams/jpg/map-5c-1.jpg | title=North East London sub-region | accessdate=12 August 2012 | publisher=Greater London Authority | author=Mayor of London }}</ref> In the [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]], it is 11.5 miles (18.5&nbsp;km) east of [[Charing Cross]]. Historically a [[Civil parish#Ancient Parish|parish]] in the county of [[Essex]], it was an agrarian village and remained mostly undeveloped until 1921, when the [[London County Council]] began construction of the large [[Becontree]] estate. The population of the area significantly increased in the 20th century, with the parish of Dagenham [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham|becoming an urban district]] in 1926 and a municipal borough in 1938. It has formed part of [[Greater London]] since 1965 and is a predominantly residential area, with some areas of declining industrial activity, including the [[Ford Dagenham]] plant. The southern part of Dagenham, adjacent to the [[River Thames]], forms part of the [[London Riverside]] section of the [[Thames Gateway]] redevelopment area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/worst-places-to-live-in-the-uk-barking-and-dagenham-come-first-in-top-ten-list-dominated-by-nine-10442606.html|title=Nine out of ten of the worst places to live in the UK are in London|date=2015-08-06|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The total population of Dagenham, including the Becontree estate, was 106,247 as of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:10px;\"\n|+'''Dagenham (parish) population'''\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1881\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3,411\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1891\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4,324\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1901\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6,091\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1911\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7,930\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1921\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9,127\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1931\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 89,362\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1941\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| #\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1951\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 114,568\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1961\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 108,368\n|-\n|style=\"font-size:smaller\" colspan=2|# no census was held due to war\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size:smaller; text-align:center;\"|source: UK census\n|}\n\n===Toponomy===\nDagenham first appeared in a document (as ''D\u00e6ccanhaam'') in a charter of [[Barking Abbey]] dating from 666 AD (though alternative 7th century dates have been suggested for the charter). The name almost certainly originated with a small farmstead, the \"ham\" or farm of a man called Daecca, as ''D\u00e6ccan hamm'' in [[Old English]] means ''home of a man called D\u00e6cca''.<ref name=mills29>{{Harvnb|Mills|2001|p=64}}</ref> The charter was made to reflect a transfer of land from Aethelred, kinsman of [[Saebbi of Essex|King Saebbi of Essex]], to Barking Abbey.<ref>On the context of the charter https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol5/pp190-214</ref>\n\n===Manor of Barking===\nDagenham has been historically defined by its [[Civil Parish#Ancient parishes|Ancient Parish]] boundaries, which were subsequently re-used by the [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham]] up until 1965. The parish of Dagenham was formed in the medieval period to serve - along with parish of [[Barking, London|Barking]] (which included [[Ilford|Great Ilford]] until the 19th century)<ref>on the history of the Manor of Barking https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol5/pp190-214</ref> - the people of the huge manor of Barking, which was owned by the Nunnery of [[Barking Abbey]]. This reversed the usual situation where a parish would serve one or more manors.\nAs with other manors, the area held by the declined over time, but the parish boundaries based on its former extent remained constant. Barking Abbey was dissolved in 1539.\n\n===Pre-urban landscape===\nLike most Essex [[River Thames|Thames-side]] parishes, Dagenham was laid out on a N-S axis to give it a share of the marshes by the river, the agricultural land in the centre and the woods and commons on the poorer soils on the high ground in the north. Dagenham included a significant part of the now mostly lost [[Hainault Forest]].\n\n===Dagenham Breach===\nDagenham was protected from the Thames by defences built in the 17th century by Dutch engineers. In 1704 an exceptionally high tide swept away fourteen feet of embankment and flooded nearly 5,000 acres of land. The breach widened over time to a width of 400 feet, allowing the Thames to strip  the top layer of marsh clay from the flood plain and deposited it as a mud bank in the Thames where it became a danger to shipping.\n\nThe gap in the wall was replaced by 1714 in a celebrated act of civil engineering. The closure of the gap left behind a large lake, known as Dagenham Breach, which became a popular spot for anglers. The lake is still there, but much has silted up or been filled in, and it is now surrounded by industry.<ref>http://www.barkinghistory.co.uk/dagenham-breach.html</ref>\n\n===Whitebait Dinners===\nDagenham was formerly home to the famous annual whitebait feast. The custom appears to have been started by the King's Commissioner of Works to celebrate the closure of the breach in the seawall around 1714\u201320, and was held every subsequent spring, on or around [[Trinity Sunday]].\n\nMany years later, [[Sir Robert Preston, 6th Baronet|Sir Robert Preston MP]], invited his friend [[George Rose (politician)|George Rose]] the Secretary of the Treasury and others to celebrate the feast, and on another occasion Rose invited the Prime Minister, [[William Pitt the Younger|William Pitt]]. Thereafter it became an obligatory ritual of government for the entire cabinet to come to Dagenham and celebrate the security of the Thames and over time this simple but hearty meal based on Whitebait and local Essex Ale grew more lavish, including turtle, grouse, champagne and a range of other luxury food and drink. Eventually the cabinet tired of the long trip to Dagenham and moved the event to [[Greenwich]].<ref>Simon Schama \u2013 Landscape and Memory p352-354</ref>\n\n===Economic development===\n[[File:Ford Dagenham.jpg|left|thumb|[[Ford Dagenham|Ford Dagenham Terminal]]]]\nIn 1931 the [[Ford of Britain|Ford Motor Company]] relocated from [[Trafford Park]] in Manchester, to a [[Ford Dagenham|plant in Dagenham]], which was already the location of supplier Briggs Motorway Bodies. A 500-acre (2&nbsp;km\u00b2) riverside site was developed to become Europe's largest car plant, a vast [[Vertical integration|vertically integrated]] site with its own [[blast furnace]]s and power station, importing iron ore and exporting finished vehicles. By the 1950s Ford had taken over Briggs at Dagenham and its other sites at [[Doncaster]], [[Southampton]], [[Croydon]] and [[Romford]]. At its peak the Dagenham plant had {{convert|4000000|ft2}} of floor space and employed over 40,000 people, although this number gradually fell during the final three decades of the 20th century as production methods advanced and Ford invested in other European factories as well.<ref>Ford UK \u2013 [http://www.ford.co.uk/ie/htg_fib/-/htg_fib_WW21970/-/-/-/- History of Ford in Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217091509/http://www.ford.co.uk/ie/htg_fib/-/htg_fib_WW21970/-/-/-/- |date=17 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2002, full production was discontinued due to overcapacity in Europe and the relative difficulty of upgrading the 60-year-old site compared with other European sites such as [[Almussafes]] ([[Valencia (province)|Valencia]], [[Spain]]) and [[Cologne]]. Other factors leading to the closure of the Auto-assembly line were the need of the site for the new Diesel Centre of Excellence, which produces half of Ford's Diesel Engines worldwide, and the UK employment laws when compared to Spanish, German and Belgian laws. In 2005 Cummins went into a joint venture and offered $15 million (US) to reinstate the factory. Ford and Cummins offered a good redundancy package, billed as one of the best in UK manufacturing. It is the location of the [[Dagenham wind turbines]].<ref name=gla>Greater London Authority \u2013 ''[http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/planning_decisions/strategic_dev/2003/jun0403/wind_turbines_report_havering.rtf Wind Turbines, Ford Estate, Dagenham planning application] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604095224/http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/planning_decisions/strategic_dev/2003/jun0403/wind_turbines_report_havering.rtf |date=4 June 2011 }}''. 4 June 2003.</ref> Some 4,000 people now work at the Ford plant.<ref>[http://www.thedetroitbureau.com/2009/05/milestones-ford-dagenham-estate-celebrates-80-years-of-manufacturing/ Milestones: Ford Dagenham Estate Celebrates 80 Years of Manufacturing]. TheDetroitBureau.com (13 May 2009). Retrieved on 2012-08-08.</ref> The movie ''[[Made in Dagenham]]'' (2010) is a dramatisation of the [[1968 Ford sewing machinists strike]] at the plant, when female workers walked out in protest against sexual discrimination and unequal pay.\n\n[[Sterling Armaments Company|Sterling]] who were famous for manufacturing British Army weapons and Jaguar car parts were also based in Dagenham until they went bankrupt in 1988.  Other industrial names once known worldwide were [[British Ever Ready Electrical Company|Ever Ready]], whose batteries could be found in shops throughout the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], [[Asian Paints|Bergers Paint]] and the chemical firm of [[May & Baker]] who in 1935 revolutionized the production of [[antibiotics]] with their synthetic sulfa-drug known as [[Sulfapyridine|M&B 693]].  The May & Baker plant, owned and run by [[Sanofi-Aventis]], occupied a 108-acre site in Rainham Road South, near [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East Underground station]].  It was abandoned in 2013 when the company closed it.  The council has decided how to use the vacant site.  They will redevelop it with a new shopping centre: stores announced so far are a [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket and a pub restaurant.  More stores will be announced in the future.\n\n===Local government===\nDagenham was an ancient, and later civil, parish in the [[Becontree (hundred)|Becontree]] hundred of [[Essex]].<ref>British History Online \u2013 [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/image.aspx?compid=42721&filename=fig13.gif&pubid=280 The Hundred of Becontree]</ref> The [[Metropolitan Police District]] was extended in 1840 to include Dagenham. The parish formed part of the [[Romford Rural District]] from 1894.<ref name=parish>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 Dagenham parish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001032034/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 |date=1 October 2007 }} ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 historic map] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930225859/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }})</ref><ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 Romford RD] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181214/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }} ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 historic map]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181611/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10025370&c_id=10001043 |date=30 September 2007 }})</ref> Dagenham Parish Council offices were located on Bull Street.\n\nThe expansion of the Greater London conurbation into the area caused the review of local government structures, and it was suggested in 1920 that the Dagenham parish should be abolished and its area divided between [[Municipal Borough of Ilford|Ilford Urban District]] and [[Municipal Borough of Barking|Barking Town Urban District]].<ref name=barking/> Separately, the London County Council proposed that its area of responsibility should be expanded beyond the [[County of London]] to cover the area.<ref>''Greater London: Case for Central Authority: Area and Powers''. ''The Times.'' 14 December 1921.</ref> Instead, in 1926 the Dagenham parish was removed from the Romford Rural District and designated as an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]].<ref name=parish/> In 1938, in further recognition of its development, Dagenham became a [[municipal borough]].<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025928 Dagenham MB] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001043633/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10025928 |date=1 October 2007 }}</ref> In 1965 the [[Municipal Borough of Dagenham]] was abolished and its former area became part of the [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham|London Borough of Barking]],<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10166901 Barking LB]</ref> which was renamed Barking and Dagenham in 1980.<ref>Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council \u2013 [http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/9-democracy/mayor/mayor-past.html The Mayor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926223705/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/9-democracy/mayor/mayor-past.html |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Market gardens to suburban estate===\n[[File:Dagenham village.jpg|thumb|The [[St Peter and St Paul, Dagenham|church of St Peter and St Paul]] formed the heart of the former village]]\n\nIn 1205 Dagenham was large enough to have a [[chaplain]], and the [[St Peter and St Paul's Church, Dagenham|Parish Church of St Peter and St Paul]] was probably built at around that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/dag-village/dvil-main-menu.html |title=Old Dagenham Village |publisher=Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council |work=Heritage and History |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104182814/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/dag-village/dvil-main-menu.html |archivedate=4 January 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1854, the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]] was built through the south of Dagenham, near the River Thames. In 1885 a new direct route from Barking to Pitsea, via Upminster, was built with [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham]] station opened just north of the village. [[Dagenham Dock railway station|Dagenham Dock]] station opened on the original southern route in 1908. Dagenham was still an undeveloped village, when building of the vast [[Becontree]] estate by the [[London County Council]] began in the early 1920s.<ref>Olechnowicz, A., ''Working-Class Housing in England Between the Wars: The Becontree Estate'' (1997)</ref> The building of the enormous council estate, which also spread into the neighbouring parishes of [[Ilford]] and [[Barking, London|Barking]],<ref name=barking>British History Online \u2013 ''[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=42729&strquery=barking The borough of Barking]''. Date accessed: 5 May 2007.</ref> caused a rapid increase in population.<ref>Vision of Britain \u2013 [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10238456&c_id=10001043&add=N Dagenham population]</ref> In 1932 the electrified [[District line]] of the [[London Underground]] was extended to [[Upminster]] through Dagenham with stations opened as ''Dagenham'' and ''Heathway'' and today called [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East]] and [[Dagenham Heathway tube station|Dagenham Heathway]].<ref>Rose, D., ''The London Underground: A diagrammatic history'', (1999)</ref> Dagenham East was the location of the [[Dagenham East rail crash]] in 1958.<ref>Railways Archive \u2013 [http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_Dagenham1958.pdf Report on the collision at Dagenham East \u2013 30.01.58]</ref> Services on the London Tilbury & Southend line at Dagenham East were withdrawn in 1962.\n\n==Governance==\nThe wards of Eastbrook, Heath, River, Village and Whalebone are in the [[Dagenham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Dagenham and Rainham Parliamentary Constituency]]. The wards of Alibon, Mayesbrook, Parsloes, Thames and Valence are in the [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking Parliamentary Constituency]]. Each ward elects three councillors to [[Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council]]. The whole area is within the [[City and East (London Assembly constituency)|City and East London Assembly Constituency]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Beam valley park.jpg|thumb|The [[River Rom|River Beam]] in the south of Dagenham]]\nDagenham is located approximately {{convert|11.5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Charing Cross]] in Central London. The [[Becontree]] estate is largely in the pre-1965 borough of Dagenham, which also  also included [[Becontree Heath]], part of [[Rush Green, London|Rush Green]], Old Dagenham village, and the southern section around [[Dagenham Dock]] and adjacent to the [[River Thames]]. This southern section, which includes [[Ford Dagenham]], is part of the [[London Riverside]] section of the [[Thames Gateway]] redevelopment zone. The Dagenham [[post town]] includes the whole of the Becontree estate, including those sections that were in the former (pre 1965) boroughs of Barking and Ilford. Parts of the former borough of Dagenham - part of Chadwell Heath, part of Collier Row and part of Rush Green - are in the Romford Post town.\n\n(Dagenham is the name of a post town, and of a pre-1965 borough (and parish before that) with very different boundaries to the post town. Perhaps because of the name 'London Borough of Barking & Dagenham', adopted on 1 January 1980 to replace 'London Borough of Barking', there is an apparent popular - but incorrect - assumption that everywhere in that borough is either in Barking or in Dagenham. From 1965 it was true to say that everywhere in the then new London Borough was in one of the two former boroughs, but in the mid 1990s substantial areas of the London Borough of Redbridge were transferred to the borough, such that the entire Becontree and Padnall Estates were in LB Barking and Dagenham. Furthermore, parts of three post towns - Barking, Dagenham and Romford - cover the borough. The parliamentary constituency of Dagenham, formed in 1945, ceased to exist from the 2010 General Election, the six easternmost wards of LB Barking & Dagenham having become part of the Dagenham & Rainham Constituency,  with three wards in LB Havering, leaving most LB Barking & Dagenham wards in the enlarged Barking constituency.)\n\n==Demography==\nDagenham is a working class area. During the 2000s [does this mean 2000-09?] there was a large influx of migrants, in particular Africans.<ref name=\"observer article industrial history\">{{cite news | author = Asthana, Anushka |author-link=Anushka Asthana| title = Dagenham's heyday: 'It was all just one big happy family then' | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 21 March 2010 | pages = 18\u201319 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/mar/21/dagenham-barking-ford-industrial-history | accessdate = 23 March 2010}}</ref> The current population of the former (pre 1965) Borough of Dagenham could be approximated from the population of the current wards which together most closely match the area, but the former boundary between the borough and neighbouring Barking, with which it merged in 1965, no longer corresponds to any ward boundaries.\n\nAt the time of the 2011 census, the Alibon ward (north of Heathway station) was 61% White British and 15% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/alibon-e05000027|title=Alibon - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Goresbrook ward (southwest from Heathway) was 57% White British and 17% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/goresbrook-e05000033|title=Goresbrook - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> River ward (south of Heathway) was 51% White British and 19% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/river-e05000038|title=River - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Village ward (east from Heathway) was 58% White British and 19% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/village-e05000041|title=Village - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Eastbrook ward (around Eastbrookend Country) was 69% White British and 11% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/eastbrook-e05000030|title=Eastbrook - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref> Heath ward (north of Heathway) was 60% White British and 17% Black African.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/heath-e05000034|title=Heath - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nDagenham is connected to the [[London Underground]] services from three stations, [[Becontree tube station|Becontree]] (in the pre-1965 borough of Barking), [[Dagenham East tube station|Dagenham East]] and [[Dagenham Heathway tube station|Dagenham Heathway]], all on the [[District line]].  [[c2c]], part of [[National Rail]] operated by [[Trenitalia]] since February 2017, runs a train service through [[Dagenham Dock railway station|Dagenham Dock station]].<ref>c2c \u2013 [http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/templates/Generic.aspx?id=461 Stations and route map]</ref> [[TfL Rail]] services also operate from nearby [[Chadwell Heath railway station|Chadwell Heath]] station.\n\nA proposed, and as yet unfunded [[Docklands Light Railway]] [[Docklands Light Railway extension to Dagenham Dock|extension]] from [[Gallions Reach DLR station|Gallions Reach]] to [[Dagenham Dock]]. It was anticipated that the project could be completed and open for use by 2017.<ref name=dlr_next>Transport for London - [http://developments.dlr.co.uk/extensions/dagenham/whatnext.asp Docklands Light Railway - Dagenham Dock: Key Project Milestones] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615075056/http://developments.dlr.co.uk/extensions/dagenham/whatnext.asp |date=15 June 2009 }}</ref> However the [[public inquiry]] has been postponed due to concerns about funding.\n\nDagenham Heathway is served by the following [[Transport for London]] contracted routes: [[London Buses]] routes 145,173,174,175,287]] and 364.<ref>[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tfl/gettingaround/maps/buses/pdf/dagenhamheathway-2065.pdf Transport for London \u2013 Buses from Dagenham Heathway -]</ref> Routes 5, 103, 128, 150, 173, 174, 175, 499, and N15 and [[East London Transit]] service EL2 operate from [[Becontree Heath]] or the nearby Dagenham Civic Centre. Route 128 and EL1 runs a 24-hour service, while the N15 runs through the night.<ref>287,62 and many other buses run through this area.[http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tfl/gettingaround/maps/buses/pdf/becontreeheath-2020.pdf Transport for London \u2013  Buses from Beacontree Heath \u2013]</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[Valence House Museum|Valence House]], in Becontree Avenue, is the only surviving of the five manor houses of Dagenham.<ref>[http://www.lbbd.gov.uk/museumsandheritage/valencehousemuseum/pages/home.aspx Valence House museum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722073902/http://www.lbbd.gov.uk/museumsandheritage/valencehousemuseum/pages/home.aspx |date=22 July 2012 }}. lbbd.gov.uk</ref>\nDating back to the 13th century, it is sited in parkland and is partially surrounded by a moat. Valence House is the London Borough of Barking & Dagenham's local history museum, displaying artifacts and archives that tell the story of the lives of the people of Barking and Dagenham. The collection also includes portraits, family papers and other mementos of the Fanshawe family, who occupied [[Parsloes Manor]], since demolished, from the sixteenth century.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080904220540/http://www.barking-dagenham.gov.uk/4-heritage/local-history/fanshawe-family.html The Fanshawe Family, London Borough of Barking and Dagenham], barking-dagenham.gov.uk</ref>\nThe Fanshawe collection is \"one of the best collections of gentry portraits in the country and is of international importance\", according to Valence House.<ref name=b1>[[Elizabeth Ogborne]], [https://archive.org/details/b22009061/page/61 The History of Essex: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time], Printed for the Proprietors by R.H. Kelham, London, 1814, p. 61.</ref>\nAmong members of the Fanshawe family was the diplomat [[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet]], whose portrait is at Valence House. Nine successive members of the Fanshawe family served as [[Remembrancer]] to the Crown, following Henry Fanshawe's appointment to the position by [[Queen Elizabeth I]] in 1566. The appointment made possible the family's rise to prominence.\n\nIn the post town of Romford and the pre-1965 borough of Dagenham, on the corner of Whalebone Lane and the Eastern Avenue, diagonally opposite the [[Moby-Dick]] public house, is the site of Marks Manor House, a large 15th-century moated building demolished in the early 19th century. During [[World War II]] the adjoining fields were used by the [[Royal Artillery]] for an anti-aircraft battery; later a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] for Germans was erected there. Further south down Whalebone Lane on the corner of the High Road is the Tollgate pub. This stands on the site of the [[milestone]] which marked the ten mile (16&nbsp;km) limit from the [[City of London]] and the [[Turnpike trust|turnpike]] [[toll-gate]].\n\n[[Dagenham Roundhouse|The Roundhouse]] public house on the junction of Porters Avenue and Lodge Avenue (in the pre-1965 borough of Barking) became East London's premier rock-music venue between 1969 and 1975, incorporating the ''Village Blues Club''. Notable performers at the pub included [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]], [[Supertramp]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]], and [[Led Zeppelin]] (on 5 April 1969). The [[Eastbrook, Dagenham|Eastbrook]] is a [[listed building|Grade II* listed]] pub.<ref name=EnglishHeritage>{{NHLE|desc=Eastbrook public house|num=1393600|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\n[[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]], based the London Borough of Barking & Dagenham Stadium (in Victoria Road, Dagenham) were relegated to the  {{English football updater|Dagenh&R}} in the 2015/16 season from the [[Football League Two]], after being relegated from the [[Football League One]] which they had reached having been promoted as [[2010 Football League Two play-off Final|playoff-winners of League two after beating]] [[Rotherham United F.C.]] 3\u20132, in the 2010/11 season. They were the Nationwide Conference champions in the 2006/07 season.\n\nMotorcycle speedway was staged at the greyhound stadium in Ripple Road in the mid to late 1930s. The club run events focussed on training but a team called the Dagenham Daggers did take part in local competitions. It is possible that the venture was operational as early as 1931 a meeting at Caxton (Cambridgeshire) was advertised as Caxton Speedway v Dagenham Speedway.\n\nDagenham's leading cricket club [[Goresbrook Cricket Club]] are based at the May & Baker Sports Club in Rainham Road South, in 2011 the club won the Essex County Cricket League for the first time in its history.\n\nDagenham has a [[List of King George V Playing Fields (Greater London)|King George's Field]] in memorial to [[George V of the United Kingdom|King George V]]. The park, which has been in existence for over a century [give date], was renamed in 1953 by [[Queen Elizabeth II]]. Dagenham also has many other parks such as Valence - and Parsloes (which lies partly in the pre-1965 borough of Barking). '''Dagenham Crusaders Drum and Bugle Corps''', founded by John Johnson, was the first British Drum Corps and performed in America [USA?] for the first time in 1983. They have recently [when?] reformed to perform for DCUK's 30th anniversary, and in 2010 fielded a competitive corps for the first time in 22 years.\n\nThe town is also home to the [[Dagenham Girl Pipers]], a [[bagpipe]] [[marching band]] founded in 1930 by the Revd Joseph Waddington Graves.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Barking and Dagenham}}. Please see 'Geography' above for various definitions of 'Dagenham'.\n* Revd [[Abraham Blackborne]], one of the longest-serving vicars of Dagenham.<ref>{{acad|id=BLKN733A|name=Blackburne, Abraham}}</ref>\n* England international footballer and World Cup-winning manager [[Alf Ramsey]] was born in Dagenham in 1920.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Alf Ramsey|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7624023/Sir-Alf-Ramsey.html|accessdate=6 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 May 1999|location=London}}</ref>\n* St Peter and Paul's Church in Dagenham was once the Parish Church of the former [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]].\n*Musician and comedian [[Dudley Moore]] was brought up in Dagenham,<ref>{{cite web |last=Parkinson|first=David|title=Moore, Dudley Stuart John (1935\u20132002)|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography. Online ed|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/abstract/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-76775?rskey=8AdRhn&result=1 |publisher=Oxford: OUP|edition=Online|date=January 2011}}</ref> which was the home of [[Peter Cook]] and Dudley Moore's famous comic alter-egos ''[[Pete and Dud]]''.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Peter|last1=Cook|first2=Dudley|last2=Moore|year=2003|title=Dud and Pete The Dagenham Dialogues |publisher=Methuen|isbn=978-0-413-77347-0}}</ref>\n*[[Sandie Shaw]], 1960s pop singer, who had a string of hit singles in the decade and won the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in 1967 with [[Puppet on a String]]\n* [[Rap]] artist [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]] is from Dagenham.\n*Actor, comedian, screenwriter, producer and author [[Nick Frost]] is from Dagenham.\n*Depeche Mode member [[Martin Gore]] was born in Dagenham.\n*[[Cage Warriors]] matchmaker Ian Dean is from Dagenham.\n*Australian singer [[John Farnham]]  was born in Dagenham  before migrating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=QIk1DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11&dq=John+Farnham+Dagenham&source=bl&ots=N-conpeTB6&sig=bGAgMCsAqacyBpj_MjShEQJ6xKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRmZrWi93UAhWGJ5QKHQNUBBAQ6AEIYzAJ#v=onepage&q=John+Farnham+Dagenham&f=false|title=Playing to Win: The Definitive Biography of John Farnham|first=Jeff|last=Apter|date=30 October 2016|publisher=Nero|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*Former darts player [[Wayne Mardle]] was born in Dagenham before living in Romford.\n*British singer, TV presenter, and personality [[Stacey Solomon]] is from Dagenham.\n*Rotund Waverley 3rd grade coach [[Scott Sarson]] was born in Dagenham, now living in Coogee.\n\n *Grime MC Syer B grew up in Dagenham\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|title=Dictionary of London Place Names|year=2001|surname=Mills|first=A.D.|publisher=Oxford|ISBN=0-19-280106-6}}\n*{{citation | url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42731| publisher=[[British History Online]] | title=Dagenham, A History of the County of Essex: Volume 5 |series= [[Victoria County History]] | year=1966 | last=Powell | first= W.R. (Edr.)  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n{{refend}}\n* Terry Cooper Death by Dior: Fran\u00e7oise Dior, (Dynasty Press, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-9568038-6-3}})\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation |publisher = Cassell & Co. |publication-place = London |title = Greater London |author = [[Edward Walford]] |publication-date = 1883 |oclc = 3009761 |chapter=Dagenham |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/greaterlondonnar01walf#page/527/mode/1up }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons-inline}}\n\n{{LB Barking & Dagenham}}\n{{London Districts}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Dagenham]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacture in London]]\n", "name_user": "BritishRaj10", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dagenham"}
{"title_page": "Foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Narendra Modi series}}\n\nThe '''foreign policy of the Modi government''' (also referred to as the '''Modi Doctrine''')<ref name=thediplomat>{{cite magazine|last1=Harsh V. Pant|title=Out With Non-Alignment, In With a 'Modi Doctrine'|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/out-with-non-alignment-in-with-a-modi-doctrine/|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=carnegie>{{cite web|last1=Christophe Jaffrelot|title=A Modi Doctrine?|url=http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/11/20/modi-doctrine|publisher=[[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]]|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> concerns the policy initiatives made towards other states by the current [[Narendra Modi|Modi]] government after he assumed office as the [[Prime Minister of India]] on 26 May 2014.\n\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]], headed by [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs Minister]] [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]] is responsible for executing the foreign policy of India. Modi's foreign policy is currently focused on improving relations with neighboring [[Country|countries]] in [[South Asia]],<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|last=Lakshmi |first=Rama |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/08/05/modis-speech-in-nepal-shows-india-is-paying-attention-to-its-neighbors/ |title=Modi's speech in Nepal shows India is paying attention to its neighbors |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date= |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> engaging the extended neighbourhood of [[Southeast Asia]] and the major global powers. In pursuit of this, he has made official visits to [[Bhutan]], [[Nepal]] and [[Japan]] within the first 100 days of his government, followed by visits to the [[United States]], [[Myanmar]], [[Australia]], and [https://thekootneeti.in/2018/03/26/india-fiji-soft-diplomacy/ Fiji].\nIt is noted that Modi is a leader who seemed to be interested in building his personal and national relationship among world leaders.\n\n==Background==\nWhile being [[List of chief ministers of Gujarat|Chief Minister of Gujarat]], and under sanctions of Western countries like the [[United States]], Modi made several foreign trips to foster his business links with major Asian economic powers. This included meeting [[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]], [[Shinzo Abe]] twice in [[2007]] and [[2012]] and building a personal rapport.<ref name=\"firstpost1\">{{cite news|author=Rajeev Sharma |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/modis-equation-with-shinzo-abe-will-make-mission-japan-a-success-1567795.html |title=Modi's equation with Shinzo Abe will make Mission Japan a success |work=Firstpost |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He also reached out for investment deals with [[China]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/sino-india-ties-set-for-big-boost-under-modi-chinese-media_935216.html |title=Sino-India ties set for \"big boost\" under Modi: Chinese media |publisher=Zeenews.india.com |date= |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> and Israel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/173767/modi-israels-new-best-friend |title=Is Narendra Modi, India's New Prime Minister, Israel's New Best Friend? |date=23 May 2014 |author=Moskowitz, Jeff |work=[[Tablet Magazine]] |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> who sought to increase economic ties beyond defense and [[agriculture]], according to outgoing Israeli [[Ambassador]] [https://embassies.gov.il/delhi/Documents/ISRAEL%20in%20INDIA%20August%20September%202011.pdf Alon Ushpiz].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/politics/israel-to-expand-ties-with-modi-govt-offers-help-in-ganga-clean-up/ |title=Israel to expand ties with Modi govt, offers help in Ganga clean-up |work=The Indian Express |date= |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He was widely appreciated for his endeavor to organize [[Vibrant Gujarat]], a biannual international business summit, to welcome investment in his home state which also helped build a pro-development and business friendly image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Vibrant-Gujarat-Summit-2013-Ratan-Tata-praises-Narendra-Modi/articleshow/17982666.cms |title=Vibrant Gujarat Summit 2013: Ratan Tata praises Narendra Modi |work=The Times of India |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== 2014 general election ==\n{{Copy edit|date=February 2020}}\nAlthough Modi made no major foreign policy speeches during the [[Campaigning in the Indian general election, 2014|general election campaign]] in 2014, he did call out China's potential aggression along the [[Line of actual control|border]] with [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/picture-gallery-others/in-arunachal-narendra-modi-warns-china/#narendramodi-arunachal |title=In Arunachal, Narendra Modi warns China |work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=23 February 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He also highlighted \"illegal immigration\" from [[Bangladesh]], making it an election issue, especially during the later part of his campaign in the [[East India|Eastern States]], including [[Assam]] and [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/column/ls-election-why-modi-is-right-on-the-bangladeshi-migrants-issue/20140513.htm |title= Why Modi is right on the Bangladeshi migrants' issue |work=[[Oneindia.in]] |date= 13 May 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> He also asserted that [[Hindu]]s outside the country would be able to seek asylum in [[India]] if they required it.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/indias-2014-elections-narendra-modi-says-some-illegal-immigrants-bangladesh-are-better-others |title=India's 2014 Elections: Narendra Modi Says Some Illegal Immigrants From Bangladesh Are Better Than Others |work=International Business Times |date=11 September 2001 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He emphasized upon the fact that he (born in [[1950]]) was going to be the first [[Prime Minister of India]] to be born after independence, therefore it would be natural to expect a shift in the world view from that of his predecessors. He also pledged to have a \"strong\" foreign policy, including engaging with [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/business/international/modi-pledges-strong-foreign-policy-1.1700748#.U528WthOVes |title=Modi pledges strong foreign policy |work=IOL.co.za |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He had asked for the External Affairs Ministry to focus more on trade deals instead of other geopolitical initiatives.<ref>{{cite news|last=Busvine |first=Douglas |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/16/us-india-election-diplomacy-idUSBREA4F0KC20140516 |title=Election landslide to embolden India's Modi on world stage |work=[[Reuters]] |date=16 May 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi's first foreign policy outlook was revealed during the run-up for the Prime Ministerial candidate in his party in 2013 when he was in a [[Network 18]] program called 'Think India, dialogue forum' he had outlined the following points:- {{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n* Improving relations with immediate [[South Asia|neighbors]] would be his priority as peace and tranquillity in [[South Asia]] are essential for realizing his development [[Political agenda|agenda]].\n* He pledged to introduce the concept of [[Paradiplomacy|para diplomacy]] in India where each state and city would have the liberty to forge special relations with countries or federal states or even cities of their interest.\n* Bilateral trade would dominate the relations with most countries except for a few important global powers with which [[India]] shares a [[strategic partnership]].\n\nModi further responded to the many congratulatory messages and phone calls from most [[world]] leaders that he received in the aftermath of his historic election victory.<ref>{{cite news|author=Aswathy |url=http://news.oneindia.in/india/lankan-govt-foreign-media-react-bjp-s-election-victory-lse-1448155.html |title=World leaders, media react to Narendra Modi led BJP's election victory |work=[[Oneindia.in]] |date=17 May 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Inauguration===\n{{Main|First swearing-in ceremony of Narendra Modi}}\nBefore Modi formally took office, as Prime Minister, he invited all the [[heads of state]]/[[heads of government]] of India's neighbors to his inauguration. In doing so, he downplayed his previous reputation as a hardliner. Modi's [[First swearing-in ceremony of Narendra Modi|swearing-in ceremony]] featured nearly all the [[SAARC]] leaders, along with [[Navin Ramgoolam]] of [[Mauritius]] who held observer status at the event. The guest list included Afghanistan's [[Hamid Karzai]], Bhutan's [[Tshering Tobgay]], the Maldives' [[Abdulla Yameen]], Nepal's [[Sushil Koirala]], Pakistan's [[Nawaz Sharif]], Sri Lanka's [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]], and Mauritius' [[Navin Ramgoolam]]. As Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] was traveling, parliamentary Speaker [[Shirin Sharmin Chaudhury]] came instead. [[Lobsang Sangay]], the Prime Minister of [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan Government-in-Exile]], was also seated in the spectators gallery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Krishna Uppuluri |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-narendra-modi-s-swearing-in-offers-a-new-lease-of-life-to-saarc-1991170 |title=Narendra Modi's swearing-in offers a new lease of life to SAARC |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> Previously critical of Modi's foreign policy, international media reacted positively to this event.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/pm-swearing-in-us-media-praises-modi-for-inviting-all-saarc-leaders-1543971.html |title=PM swearing-in: US media praises Modi for inviting all SAARC leaders |work=Firstpost |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Approach of P5 nations\n\nSoon after the new Government took over the office, important world leaders expressed their willingness to work with Modi Government to strengthen their relations with India as it provides them a bigger market. All 5 permanent member states of the [[United Nations Security Council]] sent their envoys to India within the first 100 days from inauguration which is significant, given India's long-standing bid to get a permanent membership at [[United Nations Security Council|UNSC]].\n* {{flagicon|China}} To take the early movers advantage China was first to send its envoy to India after the Modi government came into power, Chinese Foreign Minister [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]] visited [[New Delhi]] on 8 June and held bilateral talks with his counterpart, and also met [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister Modi]]. In other reactions, China indicated a willingness to reach a final settlement over their contested borders .<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-06-10/china-tries-to-woo-indias-prime-minister-narendra-modi |title=China Tries to Woo India's Prime Minister Narendra Modi |work=Businessweek |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Iftikhar Gilani |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-chinese-foreign-minister-wang-yi-seeks-narendra-modi-s-company-to-dominate-the-world-1994552 |title=Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi seeks Narendra Modi's company to dominate the world |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} Russian Deputy Chairman [[Dmitry Rogozin]] visited India on 18\u201319 June 2014 to reach out to the new government led by [[Narendra Modi]]. Where the two sides discussed the cooperation in joint defense production which was one of Modi's top agenda. Later Modi met [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in July on the sidelines of [[6th BRICS summit]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/697/Visit+of+Deputy+Chairman+of+the+Government+of+the+Russian+Federation+to+India+June+1819+2014 | title=Visit of Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation to India (June 18\u201319, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|France}} French Foreign Minister [[Laurent Fabius]] made an official visit to India from 29 June to 2 July and held high-level talks with both the External Affairs Minister and the Prime Minister. Strategic and defense cooperation was on top of his agenda and he expressed hope of speedy completion of [[Dassault Rafale|the Dassault Rafale]] Jet deal as part of the much delayed Indian [[MMRCA]] project under the new government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/702/Official+Visit+of+Foreign+Minister+of+French+Republic+to+India+June+29++July+2+2014 | title=Official Visit of Foreign Minister of French Republic to India (June 29 \u2013 July 2, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} British Foreign Secretary [[William Hague]] visited India on 7\u20138 July. During his meeting with Modi, he lobbied hard for the [[Eurofighter Typhoon]] to be considered for purchase instead of the [[Dassault Rafale]], for which the deal hadn't been signed yet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/703/Visit+of+Foreign+Secretary+of+United+Kingdom+to+India+July+78+2014 | title=Visit of Foreign Secretary of United Kingdom to India (July 7\u20138, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Prior to his India trip U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] emphasized the importance of US-India relations in the twenty-first century and borrowed \"Sabka saath, Sabka vikaas\", a [[Hindi]] slogan from Modi's campaign meaning \"everyone's support, everyone's development\" (or simply, inclusive growth) and said America shared this goal and was willing to work in full cooperation with the new government to realize it. He arrived in New Delhi on 1 August and held bilateral talks with his Indian counterpart to make the groundwork ready for Modi's upcoming USA visit and also lobbied to gain India's support for sanctions on Russia amidst the [[2014 Ukraine crisis]]. [[Sushma Swaraj|Swaraj]] said in regards to the appeal: \"There is no change in our policy. We think that foreign policy is in continuity. Foreign policy does not change with the change in the government.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140803/DEFREG01/308030008/ |title=Russia Sanctions: India Defiant, Finland Nervous |publisher=defensenews.com |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign policy team==\n{{Further|Sushma Swaraj's tenure as External Affairs Minister}}\n{{multiple image\n| header = Modi's 2018 foreign policy team\n| footer =\n| footer_align = center\n| align = right\n| image1 = Sushma Swaraj in 2014.jpg\n| width1 = 100\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 = <center>[[Sushma Swaraj]]<br />'''[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs Minister]]'''</center>\n| link1 = Sushma Swaraj\n| image2 = India's Minister of State for External Affairs Vijay Kumar Singh (15760995677) (cropped).jpg\n| width2 = 100\n| length2 =\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 = <center>[[V. K. Singh]]<br />'''[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]]'''</center>\n| link2 = V K Singh\n| image3 = Vijay Gokhale.jpg\n| width3 = 100\n| alt3 =\n| caption3 = <center>[[Vijay Keshav Gokhale]]<br />'''[[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary]]'''</center>\n| link3 = Vijay Gokhale\n| image4 = Ajit Doval 2014.jpg\n| width4 = 100\n| length4 = 120\n| alt4 =\n| caption4 = <center>[[Ajit Doval]]<br />'''[[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]]'''</center>\n| link4 = Ajit Doval\n| direction =\n| total_width =\n}}\n[[Sushma Swaraj]], one of the senior leaders of BJP, was given the portfolio of External Affairs which was going to be a very important ministry with India's growing role in international affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2621719/India-election-2014-DIPLOMATIC-DISPATCH-Who-Modi-appoint-foreign-minister.html|title=DIPLOMATIC DISPATCH: Who will Modi appoint as foreign minister?|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=7 May 2014|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> She was the first woman to hold the office. Earlier on her capacity of [[Leader of the Opposition (India)|leader of opposition in Lok Sabha]] from 2009\u20132014 She met a galaxy of visiting foreign leaders which apparently helped her understand foreign relations. Modi appointed [[Ajit Doval]], a seasoned intelligence officer, as National Security Advisor (NSA).\n\nAjit Doval is believed to be close to the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]], an organization Modi comes from.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/ex-spymaster-ajit-doval-appointed-nsa/article1-1224575.aspx|title=Ex-Intelligence Bureau chief Ajit Doval named NSA|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> On 28 January 2015, only a day after the US President Barack Obama's successful India visit, the Modi government sacked Foreign Secretary Sujatha Singh and appointed [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]] in her place, Jaishankar used to be as India's ambassador to the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/balancing-indias-right/|title=Balancing India's Right|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Modi himself was believed to be unhappy over Singh's ability to lead the foreign office and on the other hand impressed by Jaishankar's diplomatic skills in turning the flagging relationship with US into a flourishing partnership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Modi-tightens-grip-over-foreign-policy-BJP-Cong-lock-horns-over-Sujatha-sacking/articleshow/46052716.cms|title=Modi tightens grip over foreign policy; BJP, Cong lock horns over Sujatha sacking|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> His secondary aides also include [[Arvind Gupta (administrator)|Arvind Gupta]](dep uty NSA) and [[M. J. Akbar|MJ Akbar]](sworn in as the Minister of State for External Affairs).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/arvind-gupta-appointed-deputy-nsa/article6282651.ece|title=Arvind Gupta appointed deputy NSA|date=2014-08-05|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/mos-for-external-affairs-mj-akbar-to-be-nda-governments-e-ahamed/articleshow/53123890.cms|title=MoS for External Affairs MJ Akbar to be NDA government's E Ahamed \u2013 The Economic Times|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n\n==Policy initiative==\nFormer National Security Adviser & Foreign Secretary Shivshankar Menon, an academic at Brookings, opined that the Modi Government's foreign policy is one of \"strategic incoherence\", executed without an \"overarching conceptual framework\".<ref>Ravi Kumar Pillai Kandamath in the Journal of the Royal Society for Asian Affairs. See Ravi Kumar Pillai Kandamath (2018) Shivshankar Menon. Choices: Inside the Making of India\u2019s Foreign Policy, Asian Affairs, 49:1, 151\u2013154, DOI: 10.1080/03068374.2018.1416024</ref> There have been many policy initiatives since that has been taking the headlines:\n\n===Act East policy===\n{{Main|Act East policy}}\nFrom the very beginning the Modi led government made it ample clear that India would focus more and more on improving relations with [[ASEAN]], and other East Asian countries as per India's [[Look East policy (India)|Look East policy]] which was formulated during PM [[Narasimha Rao]]'s government in 1992 for better economic engagement with its eastern neighbours but successive government later successfully turned it into a tool for forging strategic partnership and security cooperation with countries in that region in general and Vietnam and Japan in particular.<ref name=\"Vietnam News Agency\">{{cite web |url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/government/89377/vietnam-among-pillars-of-india-s--look-east--policy.html |title=Vietnam among pillars of India's \"Look East\" policy |date=18 November 2013 |website=english.vietnamnet.vn |publisher=[[Vietnam News Agency]] |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> In her recent visit to [[Hanoi]], Vietnam Sushma Swaraj has stressed on the need for an \"Act East Policy\"<ref name=\"Firstpost\">{{cite web |url=http://firstbiz.firstpost.com/economy/modi-govt-give-greater-push-indias-look-east-policy-says-sushma-swaraj-94718.html|title=Modi govt to give greater push to India's Look East Policy, says Sushma Swaraj|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=2014-08-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> that she said should replace India's over two-decade-old \"Look East Policy\" emphasizing a more proactive role for India in this region.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-08-26/news/53243802_1_india-and-asean-countries-east-asia-strategically-important-region|title=Sushma Swaraj tells Indian envoys to Act East and not just Look East|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/modi-unveils-indias-act-east-policy-to-asean-in-myanmar/|title=Modi Unveils India's 'Act East Policy' to ASEAN in Myanmar|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/look-east-has-become-act-east-policy-pm-modi-at-asean/|title='Look East' has become 'Act East Policy': PM Narendra Modi at ASEAN|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Neighbourhood first policy===\n{{Main|Neighbourhood first policy}}\nOne of the major policy initiatives taken by Modi government is to focus back on its immediate neighbors in South Asia. Gujral doctrine was an important approach where India made its relation with its neighborhood which stands on five important principles. Even before becoming the Prime Minister, [[Narendra Modi]] hinted that his foreign policy will actively focus on improving ties with India's immediate neighbours which is being termed \"neighborhood first: policy in the media\"<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-07-03/news/51057722_1_prime-minister-narendra-modi-friendly-neighbours-nepal|title=Narendra Modi's push for strong relations with neighbours|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"India, Modi and the neighbourhood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatewayhouse.in/india-modi-and-the-neighbourhood/|title=India, Modi and the neighbourhood|publisher=Gateway House|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/nepal-enthralled-by-visit-of-india-s-prime-minister-who-hits-the-right-notes-570277?pfrom=home-otherstories |title=Nepal Enthralled by Visit of India's Prime Minister, Who Hits 'the Right Notes' |date=7 June 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> and he started well by inviting all heads of state/heads of government of South Asian countries in his inauguration and on the second day on office he held bilateral talks with all of them individually which was dubbed as a [[List of SAARC summits|mini SAARC summit]] by the media.<ref name=\"The mini SAARC summit\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/140601/editorial/the-mini-saarc-summit-100977.html|title=The mini SAARC summit|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=1 June 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Later during a launch event at [[ISRO]], he asked Indian scientists to take the endeavour to develop a dedicated [[SAARC satellite]]<ref name=\"claws.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/1248/saarc-satellite-to-strengthen-relations-with-neighbours-radhakrishna-rao.html|title=SAARC Satellite to Strengthen Relations with Neighbours|publisher=Center for Land and Warfare Studies|date=3 September 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> to share the fruits of the technology like tele-medicine, e-learning, etc. with the people across South Asia to complement the currently operating [[Indian Technical and Economic Cooperation Programme]] program in the region.\n\n===Indian Ocean outreach===\nThe [[Indian Ocean]] region (IOR), which has long been considered as India's nautical backyard, is steadily turning into a hotspot thanks to growing Chinese strategic presence over the region's numerous strategically located archipelagos.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/the-small-islands-holding-the-key-to-the-indian-ocean/|title=The Small Islands Holding the Key to the Indian Ocean|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> To counter the recent moves made by China on the name of President Xi's pet [[Maritime Silk Road]] project, India started to reach out its maritime neighbors in the IOR with proposals of enhanced economic and security cooperation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/india-mooring-in-foreign-shores/16031162|title=India: Mooring in foreign shores?|newspaper=[[Mid Day]]|date=3 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The policy towards IOR started to unfold during [[President of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan president]]'s visit to New Delhi in early February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=2104399&sr_no=0|title=Ocean diplomacy: Sirisena visit key for India to tackle China's Maritime Silk Route ambitions|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Following that Modi embarks on a three nations ''Yatraa'' (travel) to Mauritius, Seychelles and Sri Lanka,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/03032015-indian-ocean-modi-on-a-maritime-pilgrimage-analysis/ |title=INDIAN OCEAN: MODI ON A MARITIME PILGRIMAGE \u2013 ANALYSIS |publisher=[[Euresia Review]] |date=3 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304235915/http://www.eurasiareview.com/03032015-indian-ocean-modi-on-a-maritime-pilgrimage-analysis/ |archivedate=4 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-to-offer-sri-lanka-the-maldives-mauritius-and-seychelles-help-to-counter-china-influence/articleshow/46464956.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi to offer Sri Lanka, the Maldives, Mauritius and Seychelles help to counter China influence|work=[[Reuters]]|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> although Maldives was also initially part of this outreach but recent political turmoil in that country led to last-minute cancellation of the scheduled visit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/pm-modi-cancels-trip-to-maldives-is-it-because-of-yameen-govts-rebuttal-in-nasheed-casepm-modi-cancels-trip-to-maldives-is-it-because-yameen-govts-rebuttal-in-nasheed-case-2140761.html|title=PM Modi cancels trip to Maldives: Is it because of Yameen govt's rebuttal in Nasheed case?|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAhead of Modi's scheduled visit to Beijing in May 2015, India wanted to project that it commanded a strategic supremacy over the IOR and that its relations with its maritime neighbors were far more cordial than that of China's with particular reference to [[South China sea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govts-Indian-Ocean-gambit-gathers-pace/articleshow/46281400.cms|title=Govt's Indian Ocean gambit gathers pace|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=18 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/creating-a-security-architecture-for-the-indian-ocean/|title=Creating a Security Architecture for the Indian Ocean|magazine= [[The Diplomat]] |date=25 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/461888/delhi-expand-ties-indian-ocean.html|title=New Delhi to expand ties with Indian Ocean nations|newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Project Mausam===\n{{Main|Project Mausam}}\nOn the back of growing Chinese naval activity in the Indian Ocean region,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/Sri-Lanka-snubs-India-opens-port-to-Chinese-submarine-again/articleshow/45009064.cms|title=Sri Lanka snubs India, opens port to Chinese submarine again|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> which India considers its area of responsibility, the Modi administration have introduced '''[[Project Mausam]]''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaculture.nic.in/project-mausam|title=Mausam: Maritime Routes and Cultural Landscapes|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (India)]]|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> which is believed to rival the Chinese [[Maritime Silk Road]] (MSR) initiative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oneindia.com/feature/project-mausam-india-s-answer-china-s-maritime-might-expla-1523058.html|title=Project Mausam, India's answer to China's maritime might: Explained|publisher=OneIndia.com|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/09/project-mausam-indias-answer-to-chinas-maritime-silk-road/|title=Project Mausam: India's Answer to China's 'Maritime Silk Road'|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> ''Mausam'' (Hindi: \u092e\u094c\u0938\u092e) which means weather or season in many South and Southeast Asian languages is highlighted because of its profound role in cultural exchanges in region as in ancient time maritime trade used to depend on seasonal monsoon winds. The project which is still in the evolving phase, is being with the worked on with the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Cultural Ministry]], will focus on the ancient trade and cultural linkages and emphasize on future maritime cooperation in the Indian Ocean region stretching from Southeast Asia to East Africa with the central location of India, from where the ocean derived its name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Narendra-Modis-Mausam-manoeuvre-to-check-Chinas-maritime-might/articleshow/42562085.cms|title=Narendra Modi's 'Mausam' manoeuvre to check China's maritime might|newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=16 September 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cooperation with Pacific Islands===\n{{Main|Forum for India-Pacific Islands cooperation}}\nModi chose to visit Fiji soon after democracy was re-established in the island country after 8 years. There apart from bilateral meeting, he also met heads of state/government from 14 pacific island states to enhance India's engagement in the region and proposed a 'Forum for India- Pacific Islands Cooperation' (FIPIC) be held on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/PM-Modi-woos-Fiji-days-ahead-of-Xis-visit/articleshow/45211853.cms|title=PM Modi woos Fiji days ahead of Xi's visit|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=20 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> He conveyed there India's keenness to work closely with Pacific Island nations to advance their development priorities in this regard a number of measures to strengthen India's partnership in the region were proposed which include setting up of a 'special fund of $1 billion' for adapting climate change vis-a-vis clean energy, establishing a 'trade office' in India, 'Pan Pacific Islands e-network' to close the physical distance between the islands by improving digital connectivity, extending visa on arrival at Indian airports for all the fourteen Pacific Island countries, 'space cooperation' in space technology applications for improving the quality of life on the islands, 'training to diplomats' from Pacific Island countries to increase mutual understanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijilive.com/news/2014/11/modi-proposes-forum-for-india-pacific-cooperation/59709/ |title=Modi proposes Forum for India-Pacific |publisher=[[Fiji Live]] |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075131/http://fijilive.com/news/2014/11/modi-proposes-forum-for-india-pacific-cooperation/59709/ |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref> He also expressed his willingness to host the leaders in any of India's coastal town for the next summit in 2015. It was quite significant to see [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chinese President]] Xi following Modi's trail visited Fiji on 21 November (just 2 days after Modi's trip) to meet a similar gathering of leaders indicating a struggle for influence between the two Asian giants in the island countries of south pacific.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/1288/india-china-chase-now-extends-to-fiji-with-modi-and-xis-visits-dr-monika-chansoria.html|title=India-China Chase now Extends to Fiji with Modi and Xi's Visits|publisher=Centre for Land and Warfare Studies|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/fijian-stopover-as-narendra-modi-and-xi-jinping-charm-pacific/story-e6frg6nf-1227130089619|title=Fijian stopover as Narendra Modi and Xi Jinping charm Pacific|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fast-track Diplomacy===\nOn completion of the first 100 days of Modi government, the External Affairs Ministry published a booklet called '''\"Fast Track Diplomacy\"'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/in-focus-article.htm?23980/Fast+Track+Diplomacy|title=Fast Track Diplomacy}}</ref> show-casing the achievement made in the foreign policy arena. In her first media interaction, the minister [[Sushma Swaraj]] said the catchphrase for her tenure was \"fast-track diplomacy\" and said it had three faces \u2013 proactive, strong and sensitive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modis-100-days-sushma-swaraj-talks-tough-on-pakistan-china-and-us/articleshow/42059026.cms|title=PM Modi's 100 days: Sushma Swaraj talks tough on Pakistan, China and US|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2014-09-09 |accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> Since taking office the External Affairs Minister held round-table meeting with all Indian heads of missions to the SAARC region, ASEAN region and the Middle East separately as a follow up measure to carry forward the leads gained by high-profile visits and exchanges.\n\n===Para Diplomacy===\nOne of the innovative ideas of Modi government is the introduction of elements of [[Paradiplomacy|para diplomacy]] in India's foreign policy where each state and cities would be encouraged to forge special relation with countries or federal states of another country or even cities of their interest in order.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/paradiplomacy-a-new-way-for-indian-foreign-policy/|title=Paradiplomacy: A New Way for Indian Foreign Policy?|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the upcoming visit of Chinese President Xi Jinping [[Town twinning]] agreement between [[Mumbai]] and [[Shanghai]], [[Ahmedabad]] and [[Guangzhou]] and a similar 'sister states' agreement between [[Gujarat]] and [[Guangdong]] province of China will likely to be signed. Earlier [[Varanasi]] signed partnership agreement with [[Kyoto]], Japan.\n\n==East Asia policy==\n{{Main|Asian foreign policy of Narendra Modi government}}\nFrom the very beginning, the Modi led government made it ample clear that India would focus more and more on improving relation with [[ASEAN]] and other East Asian countries as per India's [[Look East policy (India)|Look East policy]] which was formulated during [[Narasimha Rao]]'s government in 1992 for better economic engagement with its eastern neighbors, but successive government later successfully turned it into a tool for forging strategic partnership and security cooperation with countries in that region in general and Vietnam and Japan in particular.<ref name=\"Vietnam News Agency\"/> In her recent visit to [[Hanoi]], Vietnam Sushma Swaraj has stressed on the need for an [[Act East policy]]<ref name=\"Firstpost\"/> that she said should replace India's over two decade-old Look East Policy emphasizing a more proactive role for India in this region.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\"/>\n\nEast Asia being the major focus area of his foreign policy, Modi and his foreign minister chose several Asian countries for their initial bilateral visits. He has made state visits to Bhutan and Nepal and Japan within the first 100 days of his government followed by visits of Myanmar and Australia and also hosted Asia leaders like Australian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]], Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]] and Vietnamese Prime Minister [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]] apart from inviting [[SAARC]] leaders in his inauguration ceremony. External Affairs Minister Swaraj has also made official visits to several Asian capitals like [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh, [[Kathmandu]], Nepal, [[Naypidaw]], Myanmar, [[Singapore]], [[Hanoi]], Vietnam, [[Manama]], Bahrain, [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, [[Dushanbe]], Tajikistan, [[Male]], Maldives, [[Abu Dhabi]], United Arab Emirates [[Seoul]], South Korea and [[Beijing]], China.\n\n===South China Sea disputes===\nThough India's exclusive economic zone does not extend into the [[South China Sea]], the region is geopolitically important to India as a high volume of its trade passes through the South China Sea. Modi intends India to act as a stabilizing force in the Indo-Pacific Region as a part of Modi's underlying [[Look East policy (India)|Act East]] foreign policy initiative .<ref>{{citation|title=Trump Is Driving Xi into Modi's Arms|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/04/27/trump-is-driving-xi-into-modis-arms/|publisher=[[Foreign Policy]]|date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==South Asia policy==\n{{Further|South Asian foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government}}\nEven before becoming the Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] hinted that his foreign policy will actively focus on improving ties with India's immediate neighbors which is being termed as \"neighborhood first\" policy in the media<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/><ref name=\"India, Modi and the neighbourhood\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> and he started well by inviting all heads of state/heads of government of South Asian countries in his inauguration and on the second day on office he held bilateral talks with all of them individually which was dubbed as a [[List of SAARC summits|mini SAARC summit]] by the media.<ref name=\"The mini SAARC summit\"/> Later during a launch event at [[ISRO]] he has asked Indian scientists to take the endeavor to develop a dedicated ''SAARC satellite''<ref name=\"claws.in\"/> to share the fruits of the technology like tele-medicine, e-learning etc. with the people across South Asia to complement the currently operating [[Indian Technical and Economic Cooperation Programme]] program in the region.\n\n==West Asia policy==\n{{Further|Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government}}\nIndian External Affairs Ministry refers to the region of 'Middle East' as West Asia and not as Middle East which is a more popular attribution, particularly in the western countries. The region plays a vital role in India's economy as it supplies nearly two third of India's total oil import, bilateral trade is also flourishing in recent years particularly with UAE and other Gulf states. Over the years millions of Indians mostly working class have migrated to the gulf looking for jobs and they account for a sizeable share in the total remittances received from abroad.\n\n===Link West policy===\nIn an attempt to strengthen ties with India's western neighbors specially the [[Persian gulf|gulf countries]], Modi proposed this policy to complement his [[Act East policy]] concerning East Asia. Although it is called 'Link West' (West of India) which gives it a bigger geographical connotation, it is most likely to focus on the [[Middle East|middle-east]] and some of India's strategic thinkers are calling it as Modi's middle-east policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/modi-and-the-middle-east-towards-a-link-west-policy/|title=Modi and the Middle East: Towards a Link West Policy|author=C Raja Mohan|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=5 October 2014|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref> The West Asia Approach of India<ref>[http://www.dnd.com.pk/the-west-asia-approach-of-india-and-its-relations-with-middle-east/103010]</ref> is working successfully and its relations with Middle East are improving since Modi came in power. The \"West Asia Approach\" of India is now its key strategy to win Middle East. Indian foreign policy makers say that India's interests in the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC countries]] are intimately linked with its energy security, trade, employment for Indians and remittances while Middle Eastern foreign policy experts believe that India has showcased itself as \"Security Partner\" during Modi's visit to UAE. Given the economic and human security interests, the stability and security of the GCC countries is crucial for India because huge flow of remittances comes from GCC to the Indian economy.<ref>{{citation |title=India suffers steep decline in remittances from GCC nations |url=http://m.thenational.ae/business/economy/india-suffers-steep-decline-in-remittances-from-gcc-nations |work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date=23 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Stand against ISIS===\nOn 16 December 2014, [[Home Minister of India|Home Minister]] [[Rajnath Singh]] announced in the Parliament that [[ISIS]] is banned as a terrorist organization under the United Nations schedule.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/indian-government-bans-islamic-state-terror-organisation/article6698369.ece|title=India bans IS|agency=Press Trust of India|work=The Hindu|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><!--public announcement says \"we have banned\"--> Following the arrest of few Indian individuals with ISIS connections, on 26 February 2015 India put fresh bans on 'The Islamic States/Islamic States of Iraq and Syria/Islamic States of Iraq and Levant' with all its manifestation and all its affiliates under the [[Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-bans-ISIS-under-UAPA/articleshow/46382427.cms|title=India bans ISIS under UAPA|publisher=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]/''[[The Times of India]]''|date=26 February 2015|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/terror-group-isis-to-be-banned-in-india-739417|title=Terror Group ISIS to be Banned in India|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=13 February 2015|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Israel-Hamas conflict===\n{{Duplication|section=yes|dupe=Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government#Israel|date=April 2018}}\nAt the height of the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|tension between Israel and Hamas]] in July, India offered a rhetorical condemnation holding both sides responsible for erupting violence and asked Israel to stop \"disproportionate use of force\" in Gaza which was read by many{{who|date=May 2017}} as departure from tradition of more vocal supports for the Palestinian cause. External Affairs Minister Swaraj insisted that \"there is absolutely no change in India's policy towards Palestine, which is that we fully support the Palestinian cause while maintaining good relations with Israel. \" clarifying India's current position on the issue. That might sound like fence-sitting, but it is a policy shared by all Indian governments of the past 20 years following the establishment of formal diplomatic relation in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/8/3/modi-israel-relations.html|title=Why Modi's India aligns more closely with Israel than with Palestinians|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=3 August 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nSushma Swaraj, a seasoned parliamentarian, had herself blocked the opposition demand in [[Rajya Sabha]] for passing a resolution condemning Israel for [[2014 Israel-Gaza conflict]] by saying that \"India has friendly relation with both Israel and Palestine and therefore any such move may impact its friendship negatively\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/report/modi-govts-dilemma-over-israel-palestine-conflict/20140716.htm|title=Modi govt's dilemma over Israel-Palestine conflict|publisher=[[Rediff]]|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Although later in a symbolic gesture, India joined other BRICS nations in voting at the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] for a probe into the alleged human rights violation in Gaza which generated mixed response among media and analysts in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/gaza-crisis-modi-govts-unhrc-vote-against-israel-must-be-lauded-1633149.html|title=Gaza crisis: Modi govt's UNHRC vote against Israel must be lauded|work=Firstpost|date=25 July 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Overseas Indian crisis===\n;Iraq\n{{Further|Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)|Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)}}\nWith the rise of [[ISIS]] in northern Iraq, where hundreds of thousands of Indian migrant workers live, the security of those overseas Indians came under threat. On 16 June, the Ministry of External Affairs (MEA) set up a 24-hour helpline at the Indian embassy in [[Baghdad]] for assistance of Indian nationals stranded in the conflict cities. It has been reported that 46 Indian nurses were abducted from the Iraqi town of Mosul<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/06/india-condemns-attacks-and-seizure-in-northern-iraq-by-terrorists/ |title=India condemns attacks and Seizure in Northern Iraq by terrorists |publisher=Bihar Prabha |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> who were later freed and flown back to India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-28173993 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |date=5 July 2014 |title=Indian nurses freed in Iraq given rapturous home welcome |work=[[BBC News]] }}</ref> Moreover, 39 Indian workers mainly from [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] were taken hostages and the fate of those workers still not known. There were widespread speculations about their lives and on 27 November 2014 ''[[ABP News]]'' reported, citing Bangladeshi migrant co-workers, death of all the 39 men. Although the following day, External Affairs Minister (EAM) Swaraj made a statement to the [[Parliament of India|parliament]] neither rejecting nor confirming such possibility and re-assured the nation about MEA's commitment for continuing search for the Indians in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/govt-sources-say-indians-kidnapped-by-isis-in-iraq-still-alive-efforts-on-to-trace-them-sushma-swaraj/|title=Govt believes 39 Indians held hostage by ISIS in Iraq still alive|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/39-indians-kidnapped-by-isis-in-iraq-are-alive-foreign-affairs-minister-sushma-swaraj-2863311/|title=39 Indians kidnapped by ISIS in Iraq are alive: Sushma Swaraj|date=2016-06-19|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n;Libya\n{{Further|2014 Libyan conflict}}\nA similar situation occurred in Libya where many Indian nationals are stranded because of the armed conflict that broke in [[Benghazi]] and other parts of the country. Swaraj informed the parliament that her ministry was evaluating all possibilities to secure the safe evacuation of all Indians stranded in both Iraq and Libya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-government-to-ensure-safe-return-of-indians-from-iraq-says-sushma-swaraj-2007861|title=Government to ensure safe return of Indians from Iraq, says Sushma Swaraj |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=4 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> A chartered flight from [[Djerba]], Tunisia brought over 200 nationals back to India. A further 216 nationals left on 8 August, with a total of another 1,500 nationals having been evacuated. About 3,000 more nationals registered with the embassy in Tripoli in order to return.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/200-more-Indians-evacuated-from-Libya/articleshow/39848755.cms |title=200 more Indians evacuated from Libya |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> On 5 August, 44 nurses returned to India on a special [[Air India]] flight; they were predominantly from Kerala with some from Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mahim Pratap Singh |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala-nurses-back-from-libya-thank-government/article6299247.ece |title=Nurses thank Indian Mission in Libya, MEA |work=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> A further three Goans were reported to be safe in Libya with full employment and had not requested repatriation. Goa's Director of NRI Affairs U. D. Kamat said that it was ascertaining whether there were Goan workers in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=PTI |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Goans-in-Libya-are-Safe-NRI-Commissionerate/2014/08/12/article2376098.ece |title=Goans in Libya are Safe: NRI Commissionerate |work=The New Indian Express |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Yemen\n{{Main|Operation Raahat (India)}}\nAfter the outbreak of aerial attacks by the Saudi led coalition following the coup by the [[Houthis|Houthi rebels]] in [[Yemen]], Government of India launched a massive rescue operation called ''[[Operation Raahat]]'' (meaning: Relief) to save hundreds of non-residential Indians located there.<ref name=onein2015>{{cite web | title=India evacuates 4,640 nationals, 960 others from Yemen | website=www.oneindia.com | date=2015-04-10 | url=http://www.oneindia.com/india/india-evacuates-4640-nationals-960-others-from-yemen-1711703.html | accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref> Minister of State for External Affairs General [[Vijay Kumar Singh|V K Singh]] himself oversaw the entire rescue operation right from the battle ground towns of [[Sana'a]] and [[Aden]] in Yemen and the Indian base of operation in [[Djibouti]]. In the process, the [[Indian Navy]] deployed its front line ships such as {{INS|Mumbai||6}}, [[INS Sumitra]] and others while the Indian Air Force too deployed its [[C-17 Globemaster]] tactical airlifter to airlift the stranded Indians and the national carrier [[Air India]] also took active part by ferrying passengers.<ref name=hindu-evac>{{cite news|title=India begins evacuating citizens|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-begins-evacuating-citizens/article7054994.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The operation was highly successful and received huge acclamation from across the globe as it rescued not only Indians but thousands of foreigners stranded in the war torn country too.<ref name=\"Firstposta2015\">{{cite web | title=1000 nationals from 41 countries: India's Yemen evacuation finally ends and the world is floored | website=Firstpost | date=2015-04-10 | url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/1000-nationals-41-countries-indias-yemen-evacuation-finally-ends-world-floored-2192271.html | accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"The Times2015\">{{cite web | title=India appreciates Pakistan's gesture of evacuating its nationals from Yemen | website=The Times of India | date=2015-04-08 | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/India-appreciates-Pakistans-gesture-of-evacuating-its-nationals-from-Yemen/articleshow/46852396.cms | accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with North and South America==\n===United States===\n[[File:President Trump's Trip to Germany and the G20 Summit (35741357046).jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] with Modi at the [[2017 G20 Hamburg summit|G20 Hamburg summit]] in July 2017.]]\n\nDuring the run-up to the general election there was wide-ranging scepticism regarding future of the [[India-USA relations|strategic bilateral relation]] under Modi's premiership as in 2005 he was, while [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]], denied a U.S. visa<ref>{{cite news|title=No entry for Modi into US: visa denied|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/No-entry-for-Modi-into-US-visa-denied/articleshow/1055543.cms|work=The Times of India|date=18 March 2005|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> during the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] for his alleged [[2002 Gujarat riots|poor]] human rights records.<ref name=WSJ-visa>{{cite news|last1=Mann|first1=James|title=Why Narendra Modi Was Banned From the U.S.|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303380004579520041301275638?mg=reno64-wsj|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2 May 2014}}</ref> However sensing Modi's inevitable victory well before the election, the [[United States Ambassador to India|US Ambassabor]] [[Nancy Powell]] had reached out to him as part of greater re-approachment from the west. Moreover, following his 2014 election as the Prime Minister of India [[Presidency of Barack Obama|President Obama]] congratulated him over telephone and invited him to visit the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/05/16/readout-president-s-call-prime-ministerial-candidate-narendra-modi-india|title=Readout of the President's Call with Prime Ministerial Candidate Narendra Modi of India|publisher=Whitehouse.gov|date=16 May 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker-may14\">{{cite news|last=Cassidy|first=John|title=What Does Modi's Victory Mean for the World?|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/05/narendra-modi-india-prime-minister-victory.html|accessdate=21 May 2014|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|date=16 May 2014}}</ref> U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] visited New Delhi on 1 August to prepare the grounds for Modi's first ever US visit as Prime Minister. In September 2014, days before visiting the US in an interview to [[CNN]]\u2019s [[Fareed Zakaria]], Modi said that \"India and the United States are bound together, by history and culture\" but acknowledged that there have been \"ups and downs\" in relations.<ref name=CNN-fareed>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/09/21/what-does-modis-cnn-interview-say-about-indias-relationship-with-the-u-s/|title=What Does Modi's CNN Interview Say About India's Relationship With the U.S.?|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=21 September 2014}}</ref> Modi travelled to US from 27\u201330 September 2014,<ref name=hectic>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/narendra-modi-has-hectic-schedule-lined-up-for-maiden-us-trip/articleshow/42122631.cms|title= Narendra Mosi has hectic schedule lined up for maiden US trip |publisher=' ' [[The Economic Times]] ''|date=2014-09-11|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref> beginning with his maiden address in the [[sixty-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly|United Nations general assembly]] followed by attending a gala public reception by the Indian American community in New York's [[Madison Square Garden]] before heading Washington, D.C. for the bilateral talk with Obama. While there, Modi also met several American business leaders and invited them to join his ambitious [[Make in India]] program in a bid to make India a manufacturing hub.<ref name=gmodi>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/28/narendra-modi-india-new-york-prime-minister|title=US turns on charm as Narendra Modi roadshow rolls into New York|last=Burke|first=Jason|date=28 September 2014|newspaper= The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=nytmodi>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/28/world/asia/narendra-modi-madison-square-garden-united-states-indian-diaspora.html|title=Indian Leader Narendra Modi, Once Unwelcome in U.S., Gets Rock Star Reception|last=Sinha|first=Shreeya|date=27 September 2014|newspaper= The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indias-modi-begins-rock-star-like-us-tour/2014/09/26/eeabe78b-9327-4643-a131-33ab5c59174a_story.html|title=India's Modi begins rock star-like U.S. tour|last=Gowen|first=Annie|date=26 September 2014|newspaper= Washington Post}}</ref> Later President Obama greeted Modi by calling him a \"Man of Action\" during their brief interaction at the Gala dinner hosted by Myanmar's President on the eve of [[Ninth East Asia Summit|ninth]] [[East Asia Summit]] this was their second meeting since Obama hosted a rare dinner for Modi at the White House on 29 September 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/barack-obama-meets-prime-minister-narendra-modi-calls-him-a-man-of-action/articleshow/45126409.cms|title=Barack Obama meets Prime Minister Narendra Modi; calls him a 'man of action'|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> On 9 December 2014 [[US Senate]] confirmed [[Richard Verma|Richard Rahul Verma]] as the US Ambassador to India, the first Indian American to hold the office, signalling the Obama administration's will to elevate the relation with India to a newer height. He assumed office in the US Embassy in New Delhi on 19 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/rich-verma-confirmed-as-us-ambassador-to-india/article1-1294981.aspx|title=Rich Verma confirmed as US ambassador to India|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi invited President Obama to be the first US President to grace the [[Republic Day of India|66th Republic Day]] celebration as [[List of state visits to India#Republic Day Parade Guests|Chief guest]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/republic-day-pm-modis-decision-to-invite-obama-aimed-at-sending-a-strong-message-to-china/articleshow/45243213.cms|title=Republic Day: PM Modi's decision to invite Obama aimed at sending a strong message to China |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=23 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> an honour typically reserved for India's closest ally. President Obama was the first US President to visit India twice in office and the two leaders now scheduled to hold back to back summits within six months which is being referred as Modi's diplomatic coup by the media.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/modis-diplomatic-chutzpah/|title=Modi's Diplomatic Chutzpah|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> \"This Republic Day, we hope to have a friend over\u2026 invited President Obama to be the 1st US president to grace the occasion as chief guest.\"- Modi tweeted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.economictimes.indiatimes.com/letterfromwashington/it-took-a-modi-to-finally-invite-a-us-president-for-republic-day/|title=It took a Modi to finally invite a US president for Republic Day|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2017, Modi met with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] in [[Washington, DC]] where they discussed trade, specifically airplanes and natural gas, and terrorism.<ref>Office of the Press Secretary. [https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/06/26/remarks-president-trump-and-prime-minister-modi-india-joint-press Remarks by President Trump and Prime Minister Modi of India in Joint Press Statement], The White House, Washington, DC, 26 June 2017. Retrieved 27 June 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=George |first=Steve |date=27 June 2017 |title=Trump and Modi reaffirm Indian-US relations with a hug |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/27/politics/modi-trump-india-us/index.html |work=[[CNN]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |access-date=27 June 2017 |quote=The first face-to-face meeting between US President Donald Trump and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi was sealed with a bear hug Monday, as the two leaders looked to publicly underscore their newfound friendship.}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\nNarendra Modi met the [[Brazilian President]], [[Dilma Rousseff]] on the sidelines of the [[6th BRICS summit]] in [[Brasilia]], [[Brazil]], in July 2014. Describing Brazil as a key global partner for India, Modi noted that as two democracies and major emerging economies, India and Brazil not only had vast potential for bilateral cooperation, but also to strengthen each other in international forums and advance the interest of the developing world at large. President Rousseff emphasized the special place this relationship enjoyed in Brazil's foreign policy, because of the potential for bilateral cooperation and the international significance of their partnership. She congratulated Narendra Modi for his victory in the elections and wished him all success for India's progress and development. The two leaders also agreed to take steps to further expand and diversify trade and investment flows and deepen cooperation in agriculture and dairy science, conventional and renewable energy, space research and applications, defence, [[Computer security|cyber security]] and environment conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/prime-minister-modi-meets-brazilian-president-dilma-rousseff-155147462.html|title=Prime Minister Modi meets Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff|date=16 July 2014|work=Yahoo News India|accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nIn April 2015 Modi visited [[Canada]] and was the first bilateral visit to that country by an [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] in 42 years. India made a nuclear deal with the Canada's biggest producer of uranium, [[Cameco]], signed a $280 million, five-year deal to supply uranium to fuel Indian nuclear reactors. The long-term deal announced later that Cameco will sell 7.1 million pounds of uranium to India, through 2020.<ref name=\"livemint\">{{cite news|title=10 takeaways from Narendra Modi's trip to France, Germany and Canada|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/Rpfdeth2dn2gPrptUJZhFO/10-takeaways-from-Narendra-Modis-trip-to-France-Germany-an.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=livemint|date=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nModi held bilateral talks with Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]], and signed various [[Memorandum of understanding|MoUs]] like in areas of cybersecurity, skill development, cooperation in the railways and civil aviation front.<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\nModi received \"rockstar\" reception in Canada where he addressed a crowd of over 10,000 at the [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]] Stage in [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"livemint\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=10,000 Indo-Canadians throng Narendra Modi's 'rockstar' show|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/10000-indocanadians-throng-narendra-modis-rockstar-show/540144-3.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=IBNLive|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Rockstar reception' awaits Modi in Toronto|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rockstar-reception-awaits-modi-in-toronto/article7106594.ece|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Hindu|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Indian community to give rock star welcome to Modi|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/canada-s-indian-community-to-give-rock-star-welcome-to-modi-115041500187_1.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=Business Standard|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with European Nations==\n{{See also|India\u2013European Union relations}}\n\n===France===\nFrance is a valuable strategic partner of India in western Europe. Both countries have invested political capital to deepen collaboration in the cultural, economic, social, technological and military realms. Modi met French President [[Francois Hollande]] at the 2014 G-20 Summit in Brisbane, and discussed bilateral strategic, space and defence issues besides committing to global cooperation against terrorism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-meets-french-president-francois-hollande-calls-for-common-fight-against-terror-697514|title=PM Narendra Modi Meets French President Francois Hollande, Calls For Common Fight Against Terror|publisher=[[NDTV]]/[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Following the January 2015 ''[[Charlie Hebdo shooting|Charlie Hebdo]]'' terror attack in Paris, Modi condemned the act of terror and called Hollande to convey condolences on behalf of the people of India as well as express solidarity with the people of France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/NXXrNTEWZRO0mFHjwI8JtM/Modi-calls-Hollande-condemns-Charlie-Hebdo-attack.html|title=Modi calls Hollande, condemns 'Charlie Hebdo' attack|publisher='[[Live Mint]]''date=10 January 2015|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\nFrench foreign minister Laurent Fabius made several visits to New Delhi to unlock stalled negotiations regarding [[Dassault Rafale]] fighter aircraft for [[Indian Air Force]] and the 9900 MW [[Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project|nuclear power plant in Jaitapur]] by the French firm [[Areva]].<ref name=\"Jaitapur n-reactors flagged off but liability concerns remain\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Jaitapur-n-reactors-flagged-off-but-liability-concerns-remain/721283|title=Jaitapur n-reactors flagged off but liability concerns remain|last=Roy|first=Shubhajit |date=7 December 2010|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=18 December 2010|location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Modi choose Paris as his first destination in Europe as part of his ''Link West'' outreach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-visit-france-in-april-invites-french-companies-737310|title=PM Narendra Modi to Visit France in April, Invites French Companies|publisher=[[NDTV]]/[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|date=5 February 2015|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Modi's visit resulted in a government-to-government deal for 36 [[Dassault Rafale]] fighter aircraft in fly-away condition. India and France signed an initial agreement between [[Nuclear Power Corporation of India]] and [[Areva]] regarding the setting up of Jaitapur nuclear power plant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/toi-edit-page/scripting-a-west-side-story-modis-visits-to-france-germany-and-canada-adapt-lessons-learnt-from-chinas-economic-miracle/|title=Scripting a west side story: Modi's visits to France, Germany and Canada adapt lessons learnt from China's economic miracle|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Modi toured the aircraft assembly facilities of [[Dassault Aviation]] in [[Bordeaux]] and [[Airbus]] in [[Toulouse]] where he promoted the ''[[Make in India]]'' campaign by urging the aerospace giants to cultivate manufacturing opportunities in India (Airbus committed to increase its outsourcing from India from current level of US$400 million to US$2 billion by 2020). Modi travelled to [[Lille]] in the north of France to pay hommage at [[Neuve-Chapelle Indian Memorial]] dedicated to the remembrance of 4742 soldiers of the [[Indian Army (1895\u20131947)|British Indian Army]] who died during World War I & II.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/modi-s-make-in-india-dream-takes-off-with-airbus/article1-1336207.aspx|title=Modi in France: Prime Minister visits Airbus facility, pays homage to Indian soldiers|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2015, Indian Prime-Minister Narendra Modi travelled to France for a 2-day visit to attend the ''COP 21'' [[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Modi set to travel 60,000 km in 30 days|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/modi-set-to-travel-60000-km-in-30-days/article7766970.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=16 October 2015}}</ref> Narendra Modi and Fran\u00e7ois Hollande jointly invited over 100 world leaders to join ''InSPA'' (International Agency for Solar Policy & Application) \u2013 a global initiative to promote low-carbon renewable solar energy technologies.<ref>{{cite news|title=France supports India's global solar alliance|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/france-supports-indias-global-solar-alliance/article7900712.ece|newspaper=Hindu Business Line|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paris climate meet: India-led global solar alliance to counter developed nations|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/world/paris-climate-meet-indialed-global-solar-alliance-to-counter-developed-nations/article7916353.ece|newspaper=Hindu Business Line|date=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Narendra Modi, Francois Hollande invite over 100 countries for solar alliance|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/narendra-modi-francois-hollande-invite-over-100-countries-for-solar-alliance/articleshow/49925633.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Climate Change Treaty itself was under threat with President Trump announcing the withdrawal of USA -one of the major polluters as such, USA did become a part of the International Solar Alliance and lauded the efforts of the Indian leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekootneeti.in/2018/03/24/int-solar-alliance-india/|title=International Solar Alliance: India's Expanding Diplomacy|date=2018-03-23|website=The Kootneeti|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIndia invited French President Francois Hollande to be the chief guest at the [[Delhi Republic Day parade|Republic Day parade]] in New Delhi on 26 January 2016. The invitation was conveyed through the visiting French Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius, making France the only country to be invited a record setting [[List of state visits to India#Republic Day Parade Guests|5 times]] to the highly symbolic national ceremonial event.<ref>{{cite news|title=French President Hollande invited as Republic Day guest|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/french-president-hollande-to-be-chief-guest-at-republic-day-celebrations-next-year/|newspaper=Indian Express|date=22 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hollande to be Republic Day chief guest|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/513294/hollande-republic-day-chief-guest.html|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=21 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Francois Hollande to be Chief Guest at 2016 Republic Day celebrations|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/francois-hollande-to-be-the-chief-guest-at-2016-republic-day-celebrations/article7903666.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUK Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] was one of the first world leaders to congratulate Modi soon after his landslide victory in the [[2014 Indian general election|election]]. The two leaders met for the first time on 14 November 2014 on the sidelines of the G20 leaders summit in [[Brisbane]], where the British Prime Minister said improving relations with India was the \"top priority\" of UK foreign policy. He also invited Modi to visit his country at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/relations-with-india-top-priority-david-cameron-to-narendra-modi/articleshow/45150377.cms|title=Relations with India top priority: David Cameron to Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nEarlier Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]] attributed the growth story of South Asia, which was going to grow fastest in 2014\u201315 outside the East Asia region, to the election of Prime Minister Modi and his recent efforts to turn around the economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uk-deputy-pm-nick-clegg-attributes-south-asias-growth-to-modi-dividend/articleshow/45120370.cms|title=UK Deputy PM Nick Clegg attributes South Asia's growth to \"Modi dividend\"|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref> UK hailed Modi's [[Make in India]] policy and is all set to invest in Rajasthan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uk-hails-make-in-india-campaign-plans-investment-in-rajasthan/articleshow/45127676.cms|title=UK hails Make in India camp|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi paid a state visit to the UK in late 2015, meeting [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and prime minister David Cameron. On 13 November 2015 Modi addressed a rally at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] at [[Wembley Park]], north-west [[London]]. 60,000 people, mostly [[British Indian]]s, attended.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34806511|title=Modi visit: UK and India's 'special relationship' hailed|work=BBC News|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nIn April 2015 Modi visited [[Germany]] where he held bilateral talks with [[Chancellor of Germany|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]]. Modi also inaugurated [[Hannover Messe|Hannover Fair 2015]]-world's largest industrial fair,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Modi set to inaugurate world's largest industrial fair in Germany|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-germany-hannover-messe-fair-chancellor-angela-merkel/1/429728.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=India Today|date=12 April 2015}}</ref> where India was the partner country.<ref>{{cite news|title=With Make in India on mind, Prime Minister Narendra Modi opens Hannover fair|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-04-13/news/61103173_1_hannover-fair-prime-minister-narendra-modi-angela-merkel|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nModi made the strongest pitch for the [[Make in India]] initiative in Hannover fair. He said, \"The entire world is looking at India. Demography, democracy and demand are attracting the world to India.\"<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\nThere were announcements of strengthened cooperation in sectors like energy, skill development, science & technology, and the Modi government's initiatives like [[Digital India]] and [[Swachh Bharat Abhiyan|Clean India]].<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\n==Relations with Eurasia==\n===Russia===\n[[File:Putin and Modi in New Delhi in 2014.jpeg|thumb|270px|Modi and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] shake hands in New Delhi in 2014]]\nRussia, India's long term strategically for more than half a century, enjoys a special privileged strategic cooperation unparalleled in India's foreign relations. But over the years especially after their end of cold war the relation experienced strain as India started diversifying its defence purchases from a totally Soviet-dominated one. But with Putin and Modi, both with [[Strongman (politics)|strongman]] image at their home country, at the helm of affairs in their respective foreign policy it is expected to get a push.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/for-a-warmer-russian-bear-hug/article6676864.ece?homepage=true|title=For a warmer Russian bear hug|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/india-russia-here-and-now/99/|title=India, Russia, here and now|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> During the 20th 'India-Russia Inter-Governmental Commission on Trade, Economic, Scientific, Technological and Cultural Cooperation' (IRIGC-TEC) held on 5 November 2014 in New Delhi Modi met the Russian deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin and had reassured the visiting side that the new dispensation in New Delhi will continue to attach very high importance to the time-tested and special strategic partnership with Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-attaches-high-importance-to-ties-with-russia-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45047950.cms|title=India attaches high importance to ties with Russia: PM Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=5 November 2014|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> The annual commission meeting had identified new areas of cooperation including prioritising the International North South Corridor Project (INSTC), start negotiating on a Free Trade Agreement between India and the Eurasian customs union, focusing on enhancing economic partnership in areas like energy, civil aviation and diamond trade along with Russian participation in Modi's smart city project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/india-and-russia-to-give-shape-to-joint-economic-vision-package/articleshow/45049613.cms|title=India and Russia to give shape to joint 'economic vision' package|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date= 5 November 2014|accessdate= 4 November 2014}}</ref> Earlier on his first meeting with Putin, emphasising Russia's indispensable position in India's foreign policy Modi went on to saying that even a child in India considers Russia as its ''best friend''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/narendra-modi-vladimir-putin-russia-friendship-brazil-brics-summit/1/372606.html|title=Narendra Modi Vladimir Putin Russia friendship Brazil BRICS summit |magazine=[[India Today]]|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> This meeting in Brazil at the sidelines of BRICS summit served well as the familiarisation between the two leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/pm-narendra-modi-meets-vladimir-putin-says-india-wants-to-deepen-ties-with-russia_947781.html|title=PM Narendra Modi meets Vladimir Putin says India wants to deepen ties with Russia|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nPresident Putin visited New Delhi on 11 December 2014 for the annual summit, first after Modi assumed office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/india-visit-productive-and-positive-vladimir-putin_1513812.html|title=India visit productive and positive: Vladimir Putin|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://inserbia.info/today/2014/11/putins-upcoming-visit-crucial-for-india/|title=Putin's Upcoming Visit Crucial For India|publisher=InSerbia News|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/op-edge/203719-india-russia-ties-summit/|title=Putin's India visit to focus on deeper trade & investment ties|publisher=[[Russia Today]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Trade and energy cooperation dominated the talks as they set a target of US$30 billion of bilateral trade by 2025 with equal amount of investment in each other's economy. On the backdrop of increasing western sanctions Putin earlier signed a gas deal with China worth US$400 billion believed to be heavily tilted in China's favour. India too was keen to strike an energy agreement on line of above.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-27/putin-to-deepen-india-energy-ties-as-modi-seeks-china-treatment.html|title=Putin Eyes India Energy Deals as Modi Seeks China Treatment|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> During the summit both sides agreed for a joint feasibility study of building gas pipeline through China.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/vladimir-putins-productive-india-visit/|title=Vladimir Putin's Productive India Visit|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The two sides signed a total of 16 agreements and memorandum of understanding on various fields. Agreements on long term oil and gas cooperation have been signed between [[ONGC Videsh]] and [[Essar Oil]] of India and Russia's [[Rosneft]], [[Gasprom]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/putin-for-reversing-decline-in-bilateral-trade-with-india/articleshow/45441910.cms|title=Putin for reversing decline in bilateral trade with India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Putin also vowed to install 10 more nuclear reactors in next 20 years including adding more units to [[Kudankulam Nuclear Power Plant|Kudankulam plant]]. Another burgeoning aspect in bilateral relations emerged in the form of Diamond trading, While Russia is the largest producer of raw diamond, India is the global hub of cutting and polishing raw diamonds. Russia has agreed to export raw diamonds to India directly bypassing mediators like Dubai and Belgium. On this occasion the two leaders also attended a ''World Diamond Conference'' held in New Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rbth.com/blogs/2014/12/13/taming_the_babus_biggest_challenge_for_modi_and_putin_40327.html|title=Taming the Babus: biggest challenge for Modi and Putin|newspaper=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|date=13 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The Crimean leader [[Sergey Aksyonov]], who accompanied Putin in New Delhi, met several business delegation to discuss opportunity in the Black sea region although it was termed as unofficial. This has once again raised concerns in Washington, D.C. regarding India's stand on Crimea.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/us-troubled-by-crimean-leaders-india-visit/|title=US 'Troubled' By Crimean Leader's India Visit|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n;Defence ties\nIn the summit, Modi mentioned about his experience with the Russian built carrier [[INS Vikramaditya]] as an example of burgeoning military cooperation and remarked that \"even though India's options have increased, Russia will continue to remain its topmost defence partner\" signalling a long term defence relation. The two sides agreed on joint production of [[Mil Mi-17]] and [[Kamov Ka-226]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/russia-open-for-equal-work-share-on-fgfa/article6712985.ece?widget-art=four-rel|title=India-Russia talks on to finalise copter deal|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=22 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> helicopters with Russian technology in India in compliance with Modi's ''Make in India'' program and also fast forwarding the long pending major projects like the joint development and production of [[Il-214|light transport aircraft]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/russia-expresses-interest-in-aircraft-production-in-india/articleshow/45308203.cms|title= Russia expresses interest in aircraft production in India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The final design contract of fifth generation joint fighter platform [[Sukhoi FGFA|Sukhoi-HAL FGFA]] is expected to be signed soon as it already lagging by more than 2 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rbth.com/economics/2014/12/03/major_defence_deals_set_to_be_signed_during_putin-modi_summit_40089.html|title=Major defence deals set to be signed during Putin-Modi summit|newspaper=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> India is set to lease a second nuclear powered [[Akula-class submarine]] from Russia after [[INS Chakra (2011)]] which is already in service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-to-lease-another-nuclear-submarine-from-russia/articleshow/45544830.cms|title=India to lease another nuclear submarine from Russia|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Weeks before Putin's visit news of Russian Defence Minister [[Sergei Shoigu]]'s Pakistan visit on 20 November 2014, first such visit in more than 40 years, when the two sides inked a defence cooperation pact. Media reports suggested that Russia was mulling a possible sale of [[Mil Mi-35|Mi 35]] attack copter, the first ever combat platform, to India's arch rival Pakistan.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/new-era-in-russia-pakistan-relations/|title=New Era in Russia-Pakistan Relations?|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> These developments have raised concerned in the Indian strategic community as some see this as a counter move to growing Indo-US defence collaboration. Although the official response was much restrained as they termed it 'significant'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/russian-defence-ministers-visit-to-pakistan-significant-india/articleshow/45364640.cms|title=Russian Defence Minister's visit to Pakistan 'significant': India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Such apprehensions in India about Russia's strategic goals in the region was by the Russian Ambassador Kaladin as he said that it will not do anything detrimental to India's security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/will-never-do-anything-detrimental-to-indias-security-russia/articleshow/45412363.cms|title=Will never do anything detrimental to India's security: Russia|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=8 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Later Putin himself in an interview with India's ''[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]'' news agency said that 'Russia-Pakistan ties in India's long-term interest'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/russiapakistan-ties-in-indias-longterm-interest-putin/article6677459.ece|title=Russia-Pakistan ties in India's long-term interest: Putin|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with Africa==\n===India-Africa Forum Summit===\n{{Main|India-Africa Forum Summit}}\n\nThe third summit in a rotation basis was scheduled to be held in [[New Delhi]], India in December 2014. But lately [[Syed Akbaruddin]], the official spokesperson of [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Indian Foreign Ministry]] told the media that the scheduled summit is now postponed to 2015 and will include more no. of African leaders unlike previous two occasions where the event was restricted to only 10\u201315 African countries. Although media reports claimed that [[Ebola]] outbreak in Western African nations played a key role behind the postponement of the summit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Ebola-Scare-Pushes-India-Africa-Summit-to-2015/2014/09/21/article2441381.ece|title=Ebola Scare Pushes India-Africa Summit to 2015|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=21 September 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> The summit is now rescheduled on 26\u201330 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Biggest-diplomatic-event-India-Africa-summit-from-October-26/articleshow/46691914.cms|title=Biggest diplomatic event: India-Africa summit from October 26}}</ref>\n\n===Mauritius===\n[[Mauritius]] was the only country outside South Asia whose head of government attended Modi's swearing-in ceremony in Delhi. With [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|people of Indian origin]] constituting a large share of its population Mauritius has very good bilateral relations with New Delhi. Swaraj made her maiden trip as foreign minister to the island country on 2 November 2014 to attend the celebration of Apravasi Divas, marking 180 years since the first Indian indentured labourers arrived in Mauritius. There she had called on President [[Rajkeswur Purryag]] and Prime Minister [[Navinchandra Ramgoolam]] to discuss bilateral and regional issues of common interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics%20and%20nation/Sushma-Swaraj-hails-India-Mauritius-friendship/articleshow/45012519.cms|title=Sushma Swaraj hails India-Mauritius friendship|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date= 3 November 2014|accessdate= 4 November 2014}}</ref> On top of her agenda was talk on cooperation between [[Indian Navy]] and Mauritian Coast Guard to ensure the safety and security of the strategically vital Indian Ocean region. In support to her stress on the importance of maritime cooperation three major [[List of active Indian Navy ships|Indian war ships]] were docked in Mauritian waters including a destroyer {{INS|Mumbai||6}}, a frigate {{INS|Talwar|F40|6}} and the fleet tanker {{INS|Deepak||6}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-to-cooperate-with-mauritius-to-safeguard-indian-ocean/articleshow/45015810.cms|title=India to cooperate with Mauritius to safeguard Indian Ocean|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2 November 2014|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi made his first state visit to the island country in March 2015 as part of his larger outreach to India's maritime neighbours in the Indian Ocean where he participated in the Mauritias National Day celebration in [[Port Louis]] on 12 March 2015. He was also present during the commissioning ceremony of [[MCGS Barracuda]], the [[Patrol boat|offshore patrol vessels (OPV)]] that Mauritius bought from [[Kolkata]] based [[GRSE]] shipyard. The ship was earlier handed over on 20 December 2014 which marked India's first warship export.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/meet-the-barracuda-the-first-warship-india-will-export-632304?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Meet the Barracuda \u2013 the First Warship India Will Export|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-india-exports-first-warship-to-mauritius-2045616|title=India exports first warship to Mauritius|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Multilateral Engagements==\nIndia, as one of leading developing countries, plays an active role in important multilateral forums for global governance such as [[United Nations]], [[World Trade Organization]], [[G20]] leaders summit, [[East Asia Summit]], [[BRICS]] summit of emerging economies, [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and often seen as a '[[Third World|third world voice]]'. Apart from these big platforms India also engaged in many regional groupings like the [[BASIC]], [[Shanghai Cooperation Organisation]], [[Indian Ocean Rim Association]], [[IBSA Dialogue Forum]], [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]], [[Mekong\u2013Ganga Cooperation]], [[Bay of Bengal Initiative for Multi-Sectoral Technical and Economic Cooperation|BIMSTEC]] among others.\n\n===BRICS summit===\n[[File:BRICS leaders meet on the sidelines of 2016 G20 Summit in China.jpg|thumb|250 px|The BRICS leaders in 2016. Left to right: [[Michel Temer|Temer]], [[Narendra Modi|Modi]], [[Xi Jinping|Xi]], [[Vladimir Putin|Putin]] and [[Jacob Zuma|Zuma]].]]\n\n{{Main|BRICS}}\nModi in his maiden speech at the [[BRICS]], a group of emerging economies comprising Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa, called for brotherhood among the member states citing ''[[Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam]]'', an ancient Indian concept meaning the entire world is one family, to unitedly face the global challenges.\n\nIndia together with its BRICS partner working toward launching of a financial institute rivalling the western dominated [[World Bank]] and [[IMF]] which was first proposed during the [[4th BRICS summit|New Delhi summit]] in 2012 by the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]]. In the [[6th BRICS summit]] held on 14\u201326 July in [[Fortaleza]], Brazil the group have agreed to establish the bank with a corpus of US$100 billion. The bank would be named the [[New Development Bank]] as suggested by the Indian side but Modi government has failed to bag the bank's headquarter for [[New Delhi]] which would be located in [[Shanghai]], China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/brics-summit-to-be-modi-s-first-multilateral-meet-114070700041_1.html |title=BRICS summit to be Modi's first multilateral meet |author=Press Trust Of India |work=[[Business Standard]]|date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n* Later at an event in [[Brasilia]] BRICS leaders met the [[UNASUR]] heads of state/heads of government. At the same time, the Ministry of External Affairs added Spanish to its list of available languages, which the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' read as \"indicative of the government's intent to go beyond Europe, Asia and the US to forge diplomatic and trade ties with Latin American nations.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-leave-for-brazil-tomorrow-for-brics-summit/article1-1239519.aspx |title=BRICS summit: PM Modi leaves for Brazil, also to meet Latin leaders |date= 12 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref> He travelled there via Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/modi-causes-interpreter-crisis-for-external-affairs-ministry-114071200902_1.html?_ga=1.143976821.1702752175.1400080839 |title=Modi causes interpreter crisis for external affairs ministry |date=12 July 2014 |author=Archis Mohan |work=[[Business Standard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit===\n{{Main|Shanghai Cooperation Organisation}}\nIndia is now a full member of the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation, which is known to be a China-backed bloc for military and energy cooperation. It held observer status from 2005 and publicly expressed its wish for a full membership.India and Pakistan joined SCO as full members on 9 June 2017 in Astana, Kazakhstan. Although Russia had all along backed India's entry it was Beijing's reservation which held it so long. However Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] informed Modi during [[6th BRICS summit|BRICS]] summit in Brazil that it is ready to welcome India together with Pakistan in order to project a united front against Islamic extremism in Central Asia including Afghanistan specially after NATO withdrawal. On 11\u201312 September [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|EAM]] Sushma Swaraj attended the [[2014 SCO summit|Dushanbe summit]] in Tajikistan where India formally put its paper for a full membership and it became likely that it would be granted so according to Chinese officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/shanghai-cooperation-organisation-summit-paves-way-for-indias-entry-in-the-group-chinese-experts/articleshow/42396485.cms|title=Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit paves way for India's entry in the group: Chinese experts|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 September 2014|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> Modi participated at the [[heads of government]] summit in [[Astana]], Kazakhstan in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140806/jsp/nation/story_18691973.jsp#.VBEDHvmSzIs|title=Delhigears to join China-Russia club|date=2014-08-06|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===United Nations general assembly===\n{{Main|India and the United Nations}}\nModi delivered his maiden speech in the [[sixty-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly]] on 27 September 2014, where he called for reform and expansion of [[United Nations Security Council]] including India's long standing demand of a permanent membership. He expressed his concerns over the relevance of a 20th-century setup in the 21st century and the need to evaluate UN's performance in the past 70 years. He had also argued why UN should serve as \"G-All\" for global governance instead of several parallel sub-groupings like [[G7]], [[G20]], etc. In the wake of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] threat in West Asia and similar in other parts of the globe he urged for immediate implementation of 'Comprehensive on International Terrorism' by the UN and offered India's pro-active role in it citing India as a victim of terrorism for decades. Prior to his speech he along with External Affairs Minister Swaraj met UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] and discussed UN governance relating issues.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-at-unga-lets-work-towards-a-sustainable-world-move-towards-g-all/articleshow/43642407.cms|title=PM Modi at UNGA: Let's work towards a sustainable world; move towards G-All|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Ridiculing the possibility of any multilateral intervention, a demand [[Nawaz Sharif|Sharif]] has made in his address at the UNGA on 26 September, on Kashmir related matter he stated that his government is ready for 'bilateral talk' to Pakistan provided Pakistan should cultivate suitable environment for talks by giving up terrorism policy against India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cheat-sheet/prime-minister-narendra-modi-s-address-to-un-general-assembly-in-10-points-598833?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Prime Minister Narendra Modi's Address to UN General Assembly in 10 Points|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Modi commented briefly on climate change and use of clean energy, in this regards he also asked world leaders and UN officials for observing International Yoga Day, emphasizing the importance of incorporating [[Yoga]] in modern-day life style.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-asks-world-leaders-to-adopt-international-yoga-day/articleshow/43646752.cms|title=PM Modi asks world leaders to adopt International Yoga Day|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the sidelines, he held bilateral meetings with Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]], Sri Lankan President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] and Nepali Prime Minister [[Sushil Koirala]] taking his 'neighbourhood first' policy forward even in [[New York City]]. But there was no meeting with Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] following the recent low in the relation. Later he also met where [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], in a first meeting in 11 years between the two heads of government, the Israeli Prime Minister who had highlighted the potential of the bilateral relation saying \"sky is the limit\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/prime-minister-narendra-modi-meets-his-israeli-counterpart-benjamin-netanyahu/articleshow/43784668.cms|title=Prime Minister Narendra Modi meets his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===ASEAN-India summit===\nAssociation of South East Asian Nations or ASEAN is the 10 member block, it is one of the most successful regional block in the world. India started looking toward the group seriously from 1992 with the launch of 'Look East policy' and now it occupies the central position in India's policy Southeast Asia. From 2002 onward India and ASEAN started holding an annual summit at the sidelined of ASEAN summit showing the growing level of engagement between the two sides.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29999880|title=Indian PM Narendra Modi begins trip to Myanmar, Australia and Fiji|publisher=BBC|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/narendra-modi-arrives-in-myanmar-to-attend-asean-east-asia-summits-1415705110|title=Narendra Modi Arrives in Myanmar for Regional Summits|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[ASEAN|12th India-ASEAN]] summit, which was Modi's first appearance in an ASEAN meet, he called for greater connectivity with the Southeast Asian countries and mentioned that \"India and ASEAN can be 'great partners'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-and-asean-can-be-great-partners-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45122200.cms|title=India and ASEAN can be 'great partners': PM Narendra Modi |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014}}</ref> Stressing on the importance ASEAN commands in India's foreign policy Modi has repeatedly remarked that his government has in the last 6 months made relation with ASEAN a top priority and turned India's two decade old 'Look East policy' into 'Act East policy' which reflects a renewed momentum in India's approach toward ASEAN nations. The two sides also discussed the scope of extending the existing free trade agreement on service sector as well and ways to increase [[India-ASEAN Free Trade Area|India-ASEAN]] trade which is expected to reach US$100 billion in 2015. Modi also stressed on three 'C's to strengthen the relation and those are commerce, connectivity and cultural links.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/look-east-has-become-act-east-policy-pm-modi-at-asean/|title='Look East' has become 'Act East Policy': PM Narendra Modi at ASEAN|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of ASEAN summit Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including Thai Prime Minister Gen [[Prayuth Chan-ocha]], Singapore's Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]], Sultan of Brunei [[Hassanal Bolkiah]], Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] and South Korean President [[Park Geun-hye]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/narendra-modis-make-in-india-pitch-gets-thai-pms-support/articleshow/45121092.cms|title=Modi's 'Make in India' pitch gets Thai PM's support|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n;ASEAN Regional Forum\nEarlier Swaraj had attended the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|2014 ASEAN Regional Forum]] followed by the related [[East Asia Summit|EAS Foreign Ministers meeting]], held from 8\u201311 August in [[Naypidaw]], Myanmar, which was her first ever appearance in multilateral forums after becoming India's foreign affairs head. At the sidelines of the multilateral meetings she had also held bilateral meetings with her counterparts from seven countries including China, Australia, Canada, Vietnam, Philippines, Brunei and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-08-08/news/52594297_1_india-asean-trade-south-china-east-asia-summit |title=Sushma Swaraj in Myanmar for ASEAN meet, East Asia Summit |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/world/sushma-swaraj-asean-summit-pham-binh-minh-modi-syed-akbaruddin-18260.html |title=Swaraj holds 7 bilateral meetings on sidelines of ASEAN summit |publisher=Indiatvnews.com |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn regards to controversy of territorial ownership in the [[South China Sea]], a contentious issue impacting most [[ASEAN]] member states, where [[ONGC Videsh]] has investment in oil blocks, [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|MEA]] spokesperson [[Syed Akbaruddin]] said: \"India is not a party to the dispute in the South China Sea. We feel that the dispute should be resolved between those who are party to it in a peaceful manner and it should be in accordance with international law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/sushma-swaraj-describes-myanmar-visit-as-very-successful_953902.html|title=Sushma Swaraj Describes Myanmar Visit as Very Successful|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=11 August 2014|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===East Asia summit===\n{{Main|East Asia Summit}}\n[[File:National leaders at the 9th East Asia Summit at Nay Pyi Taw, Myanmar.jpg|thumb|Modi ''(fifth from left)'' with national leaders at the 9th EAS in [[Nay Pyi Daw]], Myanmar.]]\nEast Asia Summit (EAS) which is an ASEAN led dialogue forum comprises 18 countries, 10 core ASEAN nations along with Japan, China, South Korea, India, Australia, New Zealand, Russia and the United States. Over the years EAS has become the most important multilateral body in the Asia pacific region for discussing security, trade and commerce, environment and others unlike [[APEC]] which is purely economic in nature. Modi participated in the [[Ninth East Asia Summit|ninth]] [[East Asia Summit]] in [[Nay Pyi Daw]], Myanmar in November which was his second major multilateral even after [[6th BRICS summit|BRICS]] in July. Describing the importance of the EAS in managing regional security, Modi mentioned \"No other forum brings together such a large collective weight of global population, youth, economy and military strength. Nor is any other forum so critical for peace, stability and prosperity in Asia-Pacific and the world\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/look-east-policy-now-turned-into-act-east-policy-modi/article6595186.ece?homepage=true&ref=relatedNews|title='Look East' policy now turned into 'Act East' policy: Modi|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith a veiled reference of the [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|issue of South China Sea]] Modi has asked the global community for respecting maritime norms and regulations and stressed on the importance of maintaining free and secured sea-lines of communication for regular trade and commerce.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/narendra-modi-calls-for-respect-for-global-maritime-norms/articleshow/45124226.cms|title=Narendra Modi calls for respect for global maritime norms|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> He made a remark that \"In a world of interdependence and globalisation, there is no option but to follow international laws and norms. This also applies to maritime security. For this reason, following international law and norms is important for peace and stability in South China Sea as well\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/many-complex-security-concerns-in-east-asia-region-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45133252.cms|title=Many complex security concerns in East Asia region: PM Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Modi also focused on the role of EAS member countries to tackle the menace of terrorism in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-asean-must-collaborate-to-tackle-terrorism-narendra-modi/articleshow/45138187.cms|title=India, ASEAN must collaborate to tackle terrorism: Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Modi also highlighted the re-opening of [[Nalanda University]] and the role of all EAS member states into it to showcase the joint effort of the block. Among others the issue of [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP) was discussed in details during the summit.\n\nIn the sidelines of EAS Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including Russia Premier [[Dmitry Medvedev]], The Philippines President [[Benigno Aquino III|Benigno Aquino]], Chinese Premier [[Li Keqiang]] and Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/as-aeas-kicksoff-modi-meeds-medvedev-obama-kicks-up-a-row/99/|title=As EAS kicksoff, Narendra Modi meets Medvedev, Obama kicks up a row|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===G-20 leaders summit===\n{{Main|G20}}\n[[File:Heads of the 2014 G-20 member state delegations, invited nations and international organisations (6).jpg|thumb|Modi ''(third from left)'' with national leaders at the 2014 G-20 summit.]]\nG20 or the Group of 20 leading economies (advanced and emerging markets) of the world formed after the [[2008 financial crisis]] for international financial governance. India which ranks 5 in terms of nominal GDP and the fastest growing economy plays an important role in the group since it began in 2008. For the first time in 2014, India was represented by Prime Minister Modi unlike all the previous summits when [[Dr. Manmohan Singh]], a renowned economist, used to be the Prime Minister. The host and President of [[2014 G-20 Brisbane summit|2014 summit]] Australia's [[Tony Abbott]] intended the summit to focus exclusively on revamping the crisis prone fragile economy and to add US$2 trillion in the global economy by additional 2% global GDP growth rate for the next five years but countries like US was more keen to discuss issues of Climate change and reduction of Carbon emission as it sealed a similar pact with China. India's interest was also aligned with Abbott as it wants to reboot its economy and return to the high growth trajectory soon. In <ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/g20-importance-of-the-summit-possible-takeaways-for-india/articleshow/45160632.cms|title=G20: Importance of the summit & possible takeaways for India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi, a chaiwallah (roadside tea vendor) turned politician eventually became the Prime Minister of world's largest democracy winning the highest number of votes in the history, was the most sought after world leader at the G20 in Brisbane and ''[[The Guardian]]'' called Modi the ''G20's political rock star'' commenting on Modi's popularity in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/nov/14/narendra-modi-from-international-pariah-to-the-g20s-political-rock-star|title=Narendra Modi: from international pariah to the G20's political rock star|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> His personal rapport with host Australian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] was something to watch out for. Abbott who was meeting Modi for the third time, after his [[New Delhi]] trip in September and in [[Nay Pyi Daw]] just 2 days back, extended a warm hug toward Modi while welcoming world leaders in the summit venue in Brisbane. This also generated in the Australian media circle as there was 'no hug' even for Abbott's long-time friend Cameron. Modi, on his longest trip of 10 days to three different countries, met leaders from 40 different countries and even his Australia trip didn't end at Brisbane thereafter he visited Sydney, Melbourne and Canberra what is being referred as his 'diplomatic juggernaut'.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/prime-minister-narendra-modi-on-tour-no-time-to-breathe/articleshow/45156376.cms |title= Prime Minister Narendra Modi on tour, no time to breathe!|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe issue of [[Black money|black]] or unaccounted money kept in tax heavens (countries that allow foreigners to dump huge unaccounted money) abroad was also raised by Modi which is also a burning issue in India's domestic polity. He also stressed on the need of changing laws in certain countries to allow better information sharing of black money kept abroad as it is also linked to the terror funding.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-in-brisbane-g20-summit-black-money-cooperation/1/400716.html|title=PM Modi arrives in Australia, global cooperation on black money tops agenda at G20|magazine=[[India Today]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> India the world's largest recipient of remittances with $71 billion sent last year, pushed hard for the reduction in the remittance costs of non-residents at the G20 summit, asking it to work on steps to reduce costs in sending money home from abroad which is as high as 10 per cent in some countries. Earlier India has been able to convince Saudi Arabia to reduce it to 3.5 per cent. G20 agreed to bring down the global average cost of transferring remittances to 5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/forex-and-remittance/g20-vows-to-reduce-cost-of-transferring-remittances-to-5/articleshow/45166444.cms|title=G20 vows to reduce cost of transferring remittances to 5%|publisher=|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of G20 Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], European Union President [[Herman Van Rompuy]], Saudi Crown Prince [[Salman of Saudi Arabia|Salman bin Abdulaziz]], Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and also attended a special dinner hosted by his friend [[Shinzo Abe]], Prime Minister of Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-meets-world-leaders-on-sidelines-of-g20/articleshow/45159594.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi meets world leaders on sidelines of G20 |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> Even before the G20 summit formally begins all five leaders of the [[BRICS]] grouping gathered in Brisbane for an informal meeting at the invitation of Brazilian President [[Dilma Rousseff]] to discuss issues concerning the group like the [[New Development Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/narendra-modi-lauds-brazilian-dilma-rousseffs-leadership/article6603137.ece?homepage=true|title=Narendra Modi lauds Brazilian Dilma Rousseff's leadership|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation===\n{{Main|SAARC}}\nRelations with the immediate neighbours in South Asia, which have allegedly long been neglected by the previous governments, became a priority feature in Modi's foreign policy. He started well by inviting all the heads of states/governments of the neighbouring countries at his inauguration and then pushed for an early summit to encourage cooperation in many regional issues like trade, connectivity, infrastructure, transit facility among the member states. In his [[18th SAARC summit|maiden SAARC summit]] in Nepalese capital [[Kathmandu]] he had focused on greater people to people contacts, better connectivity, commercial linkages within the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/modi-talks-about-closer-south-asian-integrationat-saarc-summit/article6636029.ece?homepage=true&ref=relatedNews|title= Modi talks about 'closer South Asian integration'at SAARC Summit|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nChina, which holds an observer status in the group, was represented by Vice Foreign Minister Liu Zhenmin seen actively promoting a more active role for itself in the region including infrastructure funding through its proposed [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB) and extending its ambitious [[Maritime Silk Road]] project to South Asian nations. Pakistan, China's all weather friend, also vouched for a more participatory role for the observer nations in the summit process, indirectly advocating for a more Chinese involvement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/at-saarc-pakistan-rebuffed-by-india-over-this-china-issue-626011?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=At SAARC, Pakistan Rebuffed by India Over This China Issue|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> Although no such proposal was accepted because of India's reservation.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/china-makes-inroads-into-indias-backyard/|title=China Makes Inroads Into India's Backyard|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIndia had earlier advanced three proposal to boost connectivity in the region and those were the 'Regulation of Passenger and Cargo Vehicular Traffic amongst SAARC Member States' for seamless vehicular movement beyond the national borders the 'SAARC Regional Agreement on Railways' for international rail service and the 'SAARC Framework Agreement for Energy Cooperation (Electricity)' for energy trade in the subcontinent which is often regarded as world's most energy-starved region. Pakistan which is the second largest economy in the block threatened to jeopardise the entire summit by not agreeing any of the three proposed agreements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/saarc-in-trouble-pakistan-opposing-india-s-proposals-say-sources-625834|title=SAARC in Trouble? Pakistan Opposing India's Proposals, say Sources|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> Indian Foreign Minister Sushma Swaraj had a brief interaction with [[Sartaj Aziz]], Pakistan's foreign affairs advisor which was seen as possible ice-breaker but later the Indian side termed it as \u2018courtesy call\u2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/swaraj-aziz-meet-briefly-on-saarc-sidelines/|title=Swaraj, Aziz meet briefly on SAARC sidelines|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> The Nepalese delegation including Prime Minister Koirala, the summit host, tried hard to mediate between India and Pakistan to rescue the summit from total failure which led to a hand-shake between Modi and Sharif at the end.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/nepal-played-key-role-in-narendra-modi-nawaz-sharif-handshake/articleshow/45300842.cms|title=Nepal played key role in Narendra Modi-Nawaz Sharif handshake|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/an-epic-handshake-that-salvaged-the-kathmandu-saarc-summit-114112900792_1.html|title=An epic handshake that salvaged the Kathmandu Saarc summit|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> Finally all the sides agreed to sign the 'SAARC Framework Agreement for Energy Cooperation (Electricity)' only as a face-saving measure for the Kathmandu summit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/saarc-leaders-reach-energy-deal/article6639785.ece?homepage=true|title=SAARC leaders reach last-minute energy deal|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of the main summit, Modi also held bilateral meetings with leaders of Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal, Maldives and Sri Lanka with a notable exception of Pakistan due to ongoing stand-off between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-holds-bilateral-talks-with-saarc-leaders-except-nawaz-sharif/articleshow/45288456.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi holds bilateral talks with SAARC leaders except Nawaz Sharif|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation===\nAlthough India is not a member of [[APEC]], Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]], the host of the [[APEC China 2014|2014 APEC summit]], invited Modi to attend the event in [[Beijing]] as a guest and also showed willingness to support India's bid to join APEC. India already enjoys such support from other member states such as Russia and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/08/chinas-apec-diplomacy|title=China's APEC Diplomacy|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=2014-08-30|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> However, Modi did not participate in the meeting as a host partner country on the line of Pakistan and Bangladesh on the account of busy diplomatic schedule and a likely state visit to China next year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141106/jsp/nation/story_19003980.jsp|title=Air miles axe on Modi China trip|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)]]|date=6 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications===\n{{Main|International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications}}\nPM Modi has brought together 120 countries to form a solar alliance named ''International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications (INSTA)''.<ref>{{citation|title=PM Narendra Modi and French President Francois Hollande to launch game changing solar alliance|url=http://economictimes.com/industry/energy/power/pm-narendra-modi-and-french-president-francois-hollande-to-launch-game-changing-solar-alliance/articleshow/49975568.cms|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|date=30 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Asia Africa Growth Corridor (AAGC) ===\nIn November 2016, Japan's Prime Minister Shinzo Abe and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi in their Summit Joint Statement reiterated the resolve of the two countries to \u201cdevelop industrial corridors and industrial network for the growth of Asia and Africa.\u201d India-Japan economic engagement with Africa, under the aegis of Asia Africa Growth Corridor (AAGC), is based on the premise that the direction of global economic activities is indeed shifting towards the [[Indo-Pacific]] region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekootneeti.in/2017/12/27/africa-jp-ind1/|title=The Growth Triad - India-Japan-Africa {{!}} The Asian Contest for Africa|date=2017-12-27|website=The Kootneeti|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nAAGC seeks to provide an alternative model of development and partnership between developed and developing countries/region for mutual benefit incorporating interconnectivity, infrastructure development, and capacity building.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Prime Ministerial trips made by Narendra Modi]]\n* [[Asian foreign policy of Narendra Modi government]]\n** [[South Asian foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government]]\n** [[Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government]]\n* [[Sushma Swaraj's tenure as External Affairs Minister]]\n* [[Timeline of prime ministership of Narendra Modi]]\n* [[Domestic policy of Narendra Modi]]\n* (PM visits Indian Ocean Island countries )<ref>{{cite web|author=Vikash Anand (Chief Editor) |url=http://janlok.in/pm-visits-indian-ocean-island-countries/ |title=PM visits Indian Ocean Island countriesJanlok &#124; Janlok |publisher=Janlok.in |date= |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>\n*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/narendra-modi-first-foreign-leader-to-address-nepal-parliament-396.html | title=Narendra Modi first foreign leader to address Nepal parliament | publisher=[[India TV]] | date=26 July 2014 | accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \"Indian Foreign Policy:The Modi Era\" by Harsh V Pant \n* \"My Prime Minister Narendra Modi (Foreign Visits & Achievements)\" by NK Sood \n* [https://www.amazon.in/Modi-Doctrine-Foreign-Policy-Minister/dp/9386141159 Sreeram Chaulia (September 2016) ''Modi Doctrine: The Foreign Policy of India's Prime Minister'' \u2013 ''Bloomsbury India'']\n* [http://www.dnaindia.com/analysis/standpoint-do-we-finally-have-an-assertive-foreign-policy-under-pm-narendra-modi-2077065 Jaideep Prabhu (13 April 2015) ''Do we finally have an assertive foreign policy under PM Narendra Modi?'' \u2013 ''DNA'']\n\n{{Foreign relations of India}}\n\n<!-- Categories:  alphabetical -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Policy Of Narendra Modi}}\n[[Category:Foreign relations of India]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy of the Narendra Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy by government|Modi, Narendra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Narendra Modi series}}\n\nThe '''foreign policy of the Modi government''' (also referred to as the '''Modi Doctrine''')<ref name=thediplomat>{{cite magazine|last1=Harsh V. Pant|title=Out With Non-Alignment, In With a 'Modi Doctrine'|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/out-with-non-alignment-in-with-a-modi-doctrine/|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=carnegie>{{cite web|last1=Christophe Jaffrelot|title=A Modi Doctrine?|url=http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/11/20/modi-doctrine|publisher=[[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]]|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> concerns the policy initiatives made towards other states by the current [[Narendra Modi|Modi]] government after he assumed office as the [[Prime Minister of India]] on 26 May 2014.\n\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]], headed by [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs Minister]] [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]] is responsible for executing the foreign policy of India. Modi's foreign policy is currently focused on improving relations with neighboring [[Country|countries]] in [[South Asia]],<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|last=Lakshmi |first=Rama |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/08/05/modis-speech-in-nepal-shows-india-is-paying-attention-to-its-neighbors/ |title=Modi's speech in Nepal shows India is paying attention to its neighbors |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date= |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> engaging the extended neighbourhood of [[Southeast Asia]] and the major global powers. In pursuit of this, he has made official visits to [[Bhutan]], [[Nepal]] and [[Japan]] within the first 100 days of his government, followed by visits to the [[United States]], [[Myanmar]], [[Australia]], and [https://thekootneeti.in/2018/03/26/india-fiji-soft-diplomacy/ Fiji].\nIt is noted that Modi is a leader who seemed to be interested in building his personal and national relationship among world leaders.\n\n==Background==\nWhile being [[List of chief ministers of Gujarat|Chief Minister of Gujarat]], and under sanctions of Western countries like the [[United States]], Modi made several foreign trips to foster his business links with major Asian economic powers. This included meeting [[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]], [[Shinzo Abe]] twice in [[2007]] and [[2012]] and building a personal rapport.<ref name=\"firstpost1\">{{cite news|author=Rajeev Sharma |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/modis-equation-with-shinzo-abe-will-make-mission-japan-a-success-1567795.html |title=Modi's equation with Shinzo Abe will make Mission Japan a success |work=Firstpost |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He also reached out for investment deals with [[China]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/sino-india-ties-set-for-big-boost-under-modi-chinese-media_935216.html |title=Sino-India ties set for \"big boost\" under Modi: Chinese media |publisher=Zeenews.india.com |date= |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> and Israel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/173767/modi-israels-new-best-friend |title=Is Narendra Modi, India's New Prime Minister, Israel's New Best Friend? |date=23 May 2014 |author=Moskowitz, Jeff |work=[[Tablet Magazine]] |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> who sought to increase economic ties beyond defense and [[agriculture]], according to outgoing Israeli [[Ambassador]] [https://embassies.gov.il/delhi/Documents/ISRAEL%20in%20INDIA%20August%20September%202011.pdf Alon Ushpiz].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/politics/israel-to-expand-ties-with-modi-govt-offers-help-in-ganga-clean-up/ |title=Israel to expand ties with Modi govt, offers help in Ganga clean-up |work=The Indian Express |date= |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He was widely appreciated for his endeavor to organize [[Vibrant Gujarat]], a biannual international business summit, to welcome investment in his home state which also helped build a pro-development and business friendly image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Vibrant-Gujarat-Summit-2013-Ratan-Tata-praises-Narendra-Modi/articleshow/17982666.cms |title=Vibrant Gujarat Summit 2013: Ratan Tata praises Narendra Modi |work=The Times of India |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== 2014 general election ==\n{{Copy edit|date=February 2020}}\nAlthough Modi made no major foreign policy speeches during the [[Campaigning in the Indian general election, 2014|general election campaign]] in 2014, he did call out China's potential aggression along the [[Line of actual control|border]] with [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/picture-gallery-others/in-arunachal-narendra-modi-warns-china/#narendramodi-arunachal |title=In Arunachal, Narendra Modi warns China |work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=23 February 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He also highlighted \"illegal immigration\" from [[Bangladesh]], making it an election issue, especially during the later part of his campaign in the [[East India|Eastern States]], including [[Assam]] and [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/column/ls-election-why-modi-is-right-on-the-bangladeshi-migrants-issue/20140513.htm |title= Why Modi is right on the Bangladeshi migrants' issue |work=[[Oneindia.in]] |date= 13 May 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> He also asserted that [[Hindu]]s outside the country would be able to seek asylum in [[India]] if they required it.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/indias-2014-elections-narendra-modi-says-some-illegal-immigrants-bangladesh-are-better-others |title=India's 2014 Elections: Narendra Modi Says Some Illegal Immigrants From Bangladesh Are Better Than Others |work=International Business Times |date=11 September 2001 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He emphasized upon the fact that he (born in [[1950]]) was going to be the first [[Prime Minister of India]] to be born after independence, therefore it would be natural to expect a shift in the world view from that of his predecessors. He also pledged to have a \"strong\" foreign policy, including engaging with [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/business/international/modi-pledges-strong-foreign-policy-1.1700748#.U528WthOVes |title=Modi pledges strong foreign policy |work=IOL.co.za |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> He had asked for the External Affairs Ministry to focus more on trade deals instead of other geopolitical initiatives.<ref>{{cite news|last=Busvine |first=Douglas |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/16/us-india-election-diplomacy-idUSBREA4F0KC20140516 |title=Election landslide to embolden India's Modi on world stage |work=[[Reuters]] |date=16 May 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi's first foreign policy outlook was revealed during the run-up for the Prime Ministerial candidate in his party in 2013 when he was in a [[Network 18]] program called 'Think India, dialogue forum' he had outlined the following points:- {{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n* Improving relations with immediate [[South Asia|neighbors]] would be his priority as peace and tranquillity in [[South Asia]] are essential for realizing his development [[Political agenda|agenda]].\n* He pledged to introduce the concept of [[Paradiplomacy|para diplomacy]] in India where each state and city would have the liberty to forge special relations with countries or federal states or even cities of their interest.\n* Bilateral trade would dominate the relations with most countries except for a few important global powers with which [[India]] shares a [[strategic partnership]].\n\nModi further responded to the many congratulatory messages and phone calls from most [[world]] leaders that he received in the aftermath of his historic election victory.<ref>{{cite news|author=Aswathy |url=http://news.oneindia.in/india/lankan-govt-foreign-media-react-bjp-s-election-victory-lse-1448155.html |title=World leaders, media react to Narendra Modi led BJP's election victory |work=[[Oneindia.in]] |date=17 May 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Inauguration===\n{{Main|First swearing-in ceremony of Narendra Modi}}\nBefore Modi formally took office, as Prime Minister, he invited all the [[heads of state]]/[[heads of government]] of India's neighbors to his inauguration. In doing so, he downplayed his previous reputation as a hardliner. Modi's [[First swearing-in ceremony of Narendra Modi|swearing-in ceremony]] featured nearly all the [[SAARC]] leaders, along with [[Navin Ramgoolam]] of [[Mauritius]] who held observer status at the event. The guest list included Afghanistan's [[Hamid Karzai]], Bhutan's [[Tshering Tobgay]], the Maldives' [[Abdulla Yameen]], Nepal's [[Sushil Koirala]], Pakistan's [[Nawaz Sharif]], Sri Lanka's [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]], and Mauritius' [[Navin Ramgoolam]]. As Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] was traveling, parliamentary Speaker [[Shirin Sharmin Chaudhury]] came instead. [[Lobsang Sangay]], the Prime Minister of [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan Government-in-Exile]], was also seated in the spectators gallery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Krishna Uppuluri |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-narendra-modi-s-swearing-in-offers-a-new-lease-of-life-to-saarc-1991170 |title=Narendra Modi's swearing-in offers a new lease of life to SAARC |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> Previously critical of Modi's foreign policy, international media reacted positively to this event.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/pm-swearing-in-us-media-praises-modi-for-inviting-all-saarc-leaders-1543971.html |title=PM swearing-in: US media praises Modi for inviting all SAARC leaders |work=Firstpost |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Approach of P5 nations\n\nSoon after the new Government took over the office, important world leaders expressed their willingness to work with Modi Government to strengthen their relations with India as it provides them a bigger market. All 5 permanent member states of the [[United Nations Security Council]] sent their envoys to India within the first 100 days from inauguration which is significant, given India's long-standing bid to get a permanent membership at [[United Nations Security Council|UNSC]].\n* {{flagicon|China}} To take the early movers advantage China was first to send its envoy to India after the Modi government came into power, Chinese Foreign Minister [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]] visited [[New Delhi]] on 8 June and held bilateral talks with his counterpart, and also met [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister Modi]]. In other reactions, China indicated a willingness to reach a final settlement over their contested borders .<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-06-10/china-tries-to-woo-indias-prime-minister-narendra-modi |title=China Tries to Woo India's Prime Minister Narendra Modi |work=Businessweek |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Iftikhar Gilani |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-chinese-foreign-minister-wang-yi-seeks-narendra-modi-s-company-to-dominate-the-world-1994552 |title=Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi seeks Narendra Modi's company to dominate the world |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} Russian Deputy Chairman [[Dmitry Rogozin]] visited India on 18\u201319 June 2014 to reach out to the new government led by [[Narendra Modi]]. Where the two sides discussed the cooperation in joint defense production which was one of Modi's top agenda. Later Modi met [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in July on the sidelines of [[6th BRICS summit]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/697/Visit+of+Deputy+Chairman+of+the+Government+of+the+Russian+Federation+to+India+June+1819+2014 | title=Visit of Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation to India (June 18\u201319, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|France}} French Foreign Minister [[Laurent Fabius]] made an official visit to India from 29 June to 2 July and held high-level talks with both the External Affairs Minister and the Prime Minister. Strategic and defense cooperation was on top of his agenda and he expressed hope of speedy completion of [[Dassault Rafale|the Dassault Rafale]] Jet deal as part of the much delayed Indian [[MMRCA]] project under the new government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/702/Official+Visit+of+Foreign+Minister+of+French+Republic+to+India+June+29++July+2+2014 | title=Official Visit of Foreign Minister of French Republic to India (June 29 \u2013 July 2, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} British Foreign Secretary [[William Hague]] visited India on 7\u20138 July. During his meeting with Modi, he lobbied hard for the [[Eurofighter Typhoon]] to be considered for purchase instead of the [[Dassault Rafale]], for which the deal hadn't been signed yet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mea.gov.in/incoming-visit-info.htm?1/703/Visit+of+Foreign+Secretary+of+United+Kingdom+to+India+July+78+2014 | title=Visit of Foreign Secretary of United Kingdom to India (July 7\u20138, 2014) | publisher=Ministry of External Affairs, Government of India}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} Prior to his India trip U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] emphasized the importance of US-India relations in the twenty-first century and borrowed \"Sabka saath, Sabka vikaas\", a [[Hindi]] slogan from Modi's campaign meaning \"everyone's support, everyone's development\" (or simply, inclusive growth) and said America shared this goal and was willing to work in full cooperation with the new government to realize it. He arrived in New Delhi on 1 August and held bilateral talks with his Indian counterpart to make the groundwork ready for Modi's upcoming USA visit and also lobbied to gain India's support for sanctions on Russia amidst the [[2014 Ukraine crisis]]. [[Sushma Swaraj|Swaraj]] said in regards to the appeal: \"There is no change in our policy. We think that foreign policy is in continuity. Foreign policy does not change with the change in the government.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140803/DEFREG01/308030008/ |title=Russia Sanctions: India Defiant, Finland Nervous |publisher=defensenews.com |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign policy team==\n{{Further|Sushma Swaraj's tenure as External Affairs Minister}}\n{{multiple image\n| header = Modi's 2018 foreign policy team\n| footer =\n| footer_align = center\n| align = right\n| image1 = Sushma Swaraj in 2014.jpg\n| width1 = 100\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 = <center>[[Sushma Swaraj]]<br />'''[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs Minister]]'''</center>\n| link1 = Sushma Swaraj\n| image2 = India's Minister of State for External Affairs Vijay Kumar Singh (15760995677) (cropped).jpg\n| width2 = 100\n| length2 =\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 = <center>[[V. K. Singh]]<br />'''[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]]'''</center>\n| link2 = V K Singh\n| image3 = Vijay Gokhale.jpg\n| width3 = 100\n| alt3 =\n| caption3 = <center>[[Vijay Keshav Gokhale]]<br />'''[[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary]]'''</center>\n| link3 = Vijay Gokhale\n| image4 = Ajit Doval 2014.jpg\n| width4 = 100\n| length4 = 120\n| alt4 =\n| caption4 = <center>[[Ajit Doval]]<br />'''[[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]]'''</center>\n| link4 = Ajit Doval\n| direction =\n| total_width =\n}}\n[[Sushma Swaraj]], one of the senior leaders of BJP, was given the portfolio of External Affairs which was going to be a very important ministry with India's growing role in international affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2621719/India-election-2014-DIPLOMATIC-DISPATCH-Who-Modi-appoint-foreign-minister.html|title=DIPLOMATIC DISPATCH: Who will Modi appoint as foreign minister?|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=7 May 2014|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> She was the first woman to hold the office. Earlier on her capacity of [[Leader of the Opposition (India)|leader of opposition in Lok Sabha]] from 2009\u20132014 She met a galaxy of visiting foreign leaders which apparently helped her understand foreign relations. Modi appointed [[Ajit Doval]], a seasoned intelligence officer, as National Security Advisor (NSA).\n\nAjit Doval is believed to be close to the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]], an organization Modi comes from.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/ex-spymaster-ajit-doval-appointed-nsa/article1-1224575.aspx|title=Ex-Intelligence Bureau chief Ajit Doval named NSA|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> On 28 January 2015, only a day after the US President Barack Obama's successful India visit, the Modi government sacked Foreign Secretary Sujatha Singh and appointed [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]] in her place, Jaishankar used to be as India's ambassador to the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/balancing-indias-right/|title=Balancing India's Right|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Modi himself was believed to be unhappy over Singh's ability to lead the foreign office and on the other hand impressed by Jaishankar's diplomatic skills in turning the flagging relationship with US into a flourishing partnership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Modi-tightens-grip-over-foreign-policy-BJP-Cong-lock-horns-over-Sujatha-sacking/articleshow/46052716.cms|title=Modi tightens grip over foreign policy; BJP, Cong lock horns over Sujatha sacking|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> His secondary aides also include [[Arvind Gupta (administrator)|Arvind Gupta]](dep uty NSA) and [[M. J. Akbar|MJ Akbar]](sworn in as the Minister of State for External Affairs).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/arvind-gupta-appointed-deputy-nsa/article6282651.ece|title=Arvind Gupta appointed deputy NSA|date=2014-08-05|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/mos-for-external-affairs-mj-akbar-to-be-nda-governments-e-ahamed/articleshow/53123890.cms|title=MoS for External Affairs MJ Akbar to be NDA government's E Ahamed \u2013 The Economic Times|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n\n==Policy initiative==\nFormer National Security Adviser & Foreign Secretary Shivshankar Menon, an academic at Brookings, opined that the Modi Government's foreign policy is one of \"strategic incoherence\", executed without an \"overarching conceptual framework\".<ref>Ravi Kumar Pillai Kandamath in the Journal of the Royal Society for Asian Affairs. See Ravi Kumar Pillai Kandamath (2018) Shivshankar Menon. Choices: Inside the Making of India\u2019s Foreign Policy, Asian Affairs, 49:1, 151\u2013154, DOI: 10.1080/03068374.2018.1416024</ref> There have been many policy initiatives since that has been taking the headlines:\n\n===Act East policy===\n{{Main|Act East policy}}\nFrom the very beginning the Modi led government made it ample clear that India would focus more and more on improving relations with [[ASEAN]], and other East Asian countries as per India's [[Look East policy (India)|Look East policy]] which was formulated during PM [[Narasimha Rao]]'s government in 1992 for better economic engagement with its eastern neighbours but successive government later successfully turned it into a tool for forging strategic partnership and security cooperation with countries in that region in general and Vietnam and Japan in particular.<ref name=\"Vietnam News Agency\">{{cite web |url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/government/89377/vietnam-among-pillars-of-india-s--look-east--policy.html |title=Vietnam among pillars of India's \"Look East\" policy |date=18 November 2013 |website=english.vietnamnet.vn |publisher=[[Vietnam News Agency]] |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> In her recent visit to [[Hanoi]], Vietnam Sushma Swaraj has stressed on the need for an \"Act East Policy\"<ref name=\"Firstpost\">{{cite web |url=http://firstbiz.firstpost.com/economy/modi-govt-give-greater-push-indias-look-east-policy-says-sushma-swaraj-94718.html|title=Modi govt to give greater push to India's Look East Policy, says Sushma Swaraj|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=2014-08-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> that she said should replace India's over two-decade-old \"Look East Policy\" emphasizing a more proactive role for India in this region.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-08-26/news/53243802_1_india-and-asean-countries-east-asia-strategically-important-region|title=Sushma Swaraj tells Indian envoys to Act East and not just Look East|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/modi-unveils-indias-act-east-policy-to-asean-in-myanmar/|title=Modi Unveils India's 'Act East Policy' to ASEAN in Myanmar|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/look-east-has-become-act-east-policy-pm-modi-at-asean/|title='Look East' has become 'Act East Policy': PM Narendra Modi at ASEAN|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Neighbourhood first policy===\n{{Main|Neighbourhood first policy}}\nOne of the major policy initiatives taken by Modi government is to focus back on its immediate neighbors in South Asia. Gujral doctrine was an important approach where India made its relation with its neighborhood which stands on five important principles. Even before becoming the Prime Minister, [[Narendra Modi]] hinted that his foreign policy will actively focus on improving ties with India's immediate neighbours which is being termed \"neighborhood first: policy in the media\"<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-07-03/news/51057722_1_prime-minister-narendra-modi-friendly-neighbours-nepal|title=Narendra Modi's push for strong relations with neighbours|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"India, Modi and the neighbourhood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatewayhouse.in/india-modi-and-the-neighbourhood/|title=India, Modi and the neighbourhood|publisher=Gateway House|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/nepal-enthralled-by-visit-of-india-s-prime-minister-who-hits-the-right-notes-570277?pfrom=home-otherstories |title=Nepal Enthralled by Visit of India's Prime Minister, Who Hits 'the Right Notes' |date=7 June 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> and he started well by inviting all heads of state/heads of government of South Asian countries in his inauguration and on the second day on office he held bilateral talks with all of them individually which was dubbed as a [[List of SAARC summits|mini SAARC summit]] by the media.<ref name=\"The mini SAARC summit\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/140601/editorial/the-mini-saarc-summit-100977.html|title=The mini SAARC summit|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=1 June 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Later during a launch event at [[ISRO]], he asked Indian scientists to take the endeavour to develop a dedicated [[SAARC satellite]]<ref name=\"claws.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/1248/saarc-satellite-to-strengthen-relations-with-neighbours-radhakrishna-rao.html|title=SAARC Satellite to Strengthen Relations with Neighbours|publisher=Center for Land and Warfare Studies|date=3 September 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> to share the fruits of the technology like tele-medicine, e-learning, etc. with the people across South Asia to complement the currently operating [[Indian Technical and Economic Cooperation Programme]] program in the region.\n\n===Indian Ocean outreach===\nThe [[Indian Ocean]] region (IOR), which has long been considered as India's nautical backyard, is steadily turning into a hotspot thanks to growing Chinese strategic presence over the region's numerous strategically located archipelagos.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/the-small-islands-holding-the-key-to-the-indian-ocean/|title=The Small Islands Holding the Key to the Indian Ocean|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> To counter the recent moves made by China on the name of President Xi's pet [[Maritime Silk Road]] project, India started to reach out its maritime neighbors in the IOR with proposals of enhanced economic and security cooperation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/india-mooring-in-foreign-shores/16031162|title=India: Mooring in foreign shores?|newspaper=[[Mid Day]]|date=3 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The policy towards IOR started to unfold during [[President of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan president]]'s visit to New Delhi in early February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=2104399&sr_no=0|title=Ocean diplomacy: Sirisena visit key for India to tackle China's Maritime Silk Route ambitions|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Following that Modi embarks on a three nations ''Yatraa'' (travel) to Mauritius, Seychelles and Sri Lanka,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/03032015-indian-ocean-modi-on-a-maritime-pilgrimage-analysis/ |title=INDIAN OCEAN: MODI ON A MARITIME PILGRIMAGE \u2013 ANALYSIS |publisher=[[Euresia Review]] |date=3 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304235915/http://www.eurasiareview.com/03032015-indian-ocean-modi-on-a-maritime-pilgrimage-analysis/ |archivedate=4 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-to-offer-sri-lanka-the-maldives-mauritius-and-seychelles-help-to-counter-china-influence/articleshow/46464956.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi to offer Sri Lanka, the Maldives, Mauritius and Seychelles help to counter China influence|work=[[Reuters]]|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> although Maldives was also initially part of this outreach but recent political turmoil in that country led to last-minute cancellation of the scheduled visit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/pm-modi-cancels-trip-to-maldives-is-it-because-of-yameen-govts-rebuttal-in-nasheed-casepm-modi-cancels-trip-to-maldives-is-it-because-yameen-govts-rebuttal-in-nasheed-case-2140761.html|title=PM Modi cancels trip to Maldives: Is it because of Yameen govt's rebuttal in Nasheed case?|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAhead of Modi's scheduled visit to Beijing in May 2015, India wanted to project that it commanded a strategic supremacy over the IOR and that its relations with its maritime neighbors were far more cordial than that of China's with particular reference to [[South China sea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govts-Indian-Ocean-gambit-gathers-pace/articleshow/46281400.cms|title=Govt's Indian Ocean gambit gathers pace|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=18 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/creating-a-security-architecture-for-the-indian-ocean/|title=Creating a Security Architecture for the Indian Ocean|magazine= [[The Diplomat]] |date=25 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/461888/delhi-expand-ties-indian-ocean.html|title=New Delhi to expand ties with Indian Ocean nations|newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Project Mausam===\n{{Main|Project Mausam}}\nOn the back of growing Chinese naval activity in the Indian Ocean region,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/Sri-Lanka-snubs-India-opens-port-to-Chinese-submarine-again/articleshow/45009064.cms|title=Sri Lanka snubs India, opens port to Chinese submarine again|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> which India considers its area of responsibility, the Modi administration have introduced '''[[Project Mausam]]''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaculture.nic.in/project-mausam|title=Mausam: Maritime Routes and Cultural Landscapes|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (India)]]|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> which is believed to rival the Chinese [[Maritime Silk Road]] (MSR) initiative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oneindia.com/feature/project-mausam-india-s-answer-china-s-maritime-might-expla-1523058.html|title=Project Mausam, India's answer to China's maritime might: Explained|publisher=OneIndia.com|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/09/project-mausam-indias-answer-to-chinas-maritime-silk-road/|title=Project Mausam: India's Answer to China's 'Maritime Silk Road'|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> ''Mausam'' (Hindi: \u092e\u094c\u0938\u092e) which means weather or season in many South and Southeast Asian languages is highlighted because of its profound role in cultural exchanges in region as in ancient time maritime trade used to depend on seasonal monsoon winds. The project which is still in the evolving phase, is being with the worked on with the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Cultural Ministry]], will focus on the ancient trade and cultural linkages and emphasize on future maritime cooperation in the Indian Ocean region stretching from Southeast Asia to East Africa with the central location of India, from where the ocean derived its name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Narendra-Modis-Mausam-manoeuvre-to-check-Chinas-maritime-might/articleshow/42562085.cms|title=Narendra Modi's 'Mausam' manoeuvre to check China's maritime might|newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=16 September 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cooperation with Pacific Islands===\n{{Main|Forum for India-Pacific Islands cooperation}}\nModi chose to visit Fiji soon after democracy was re-established in the island country after 8 years. There apart from bilateral meeting, he also met heads of state/government from 14 pacific island states to enhance India's engagement in the region and proposed a 'Forum for India- Pacific Islands Cooperation' (FIPIC) be held on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/PM-Modi-woos-Fiji-days-ahead-of-Xis-visit/articleshow/45211853.cms|title=PM Modi woos Fiji days ahead of Xi's visit|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=20 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> He conveyed there India's keenness to work closely with Pacific Island nations to advance their development priorities in this regard a number of measures to strengthen India's partnership in the region were proposed which include setting up of a 'special fund of $1 billion' for adapting climate change vis-a-vis clean energy, establishing a 'trade office' in India, 'Pan Pacific Islands e-network' to close the physical distance between the islands by improving digital connectivity, extending visa on arrival at Indian airports for all the fourteen Pacific Island countries, 'space cooperation' in space technology applications for improving the quality of life on the islands, 'training to diplomats' from Pacific Island countries to increase mutual understanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijilive.com/news/2014/11/modi-proposes-forum-for-india-pacific-cooperation/59709/ |title=Modi proposes Forum for India-Pacific |publisher=[[Fiji Live]] |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075131/http://fijilive.com/news/2014/11/modi-proposes-forum-for-india-pacific-cooperation/59709/ |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref> He also expressed his willingness to host the leaders in any of India's coastal town for the next summit in 2015. It was quite significant to see [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chinese President]] Xi following Modi's trail visited Fiji on 21 November (just 2 days after Modi's trip) to meet a similar gathering of leaders indicating a struggle for influence between the two Asian giants in the island countries of south pacific.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.claws.in/1288/india-china-chase-now-extends-to-fiji-with-modi-and-xis-visits-dr-monika-chansoria.html|title=India-China Chase now Extends to Fiji with Modi and Xi's Visits|publisher=Centre for Land and Warfare Studies|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/fijian-stopover-as-narendra-modi-and-xi-jinping-charm-pacific/story-e6frg6nf-1227130089619|title=Fijian stopover as Narendra Modi and Xi Jinping charm Pacific|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fast-track Diplomacy===\nOn completion of the first 100 days of Modi government, the External Affairs Ministry published a booklet called '''\"Fast Track Diplomacy\"'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/in-focus-article.htm?23980/Fast+Track+Diplomacy|title=Fast Track Diplomacy}}</ref> show-casing the achievement made in the foreign policy arena. In her first media interaction, the minister [[Sushma Swaraj]] said the catchphrase for her tenure was \"fast-track diplomacy\" and said it had three faces \u2013 proactive, strong and sensitive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modis-100-days-sushma-swaraj-talks-tough-on-pakistan-china-and-us/articleshow/42059026.cms|title=PM Modi's 100 days: Sushma Swaraj talks tough on Pakistan, China and US|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2014-09-09 |accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> Since taking office the External Affairs Minister held round-table meeting with all Indian heads of missions to the SAARC region, ASEAN region and the Middle East separately as a follow up measure to carry forward the leads gained by high-profile visits and exchanges.\n\n===Para Diplomacy===\nOne of the innovative ideas of Modi government is the introduction of elements of [[Paradiplomacy|para diplomacy]] in India's foreign policy where each state and cities would be encouraged to forge special relation with countries or federal states of another country or even cities of their interest in order.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/paradiplomacy-a-new-way-for-indian-foreign-policy/|title=Paradiplomacy: A New Way for Indian Foreign Policy?|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the upcoming visit of Chinese President Xi Jinping [[Town twinning]] agreement between [[Mumbai]] and [[Shanghai]], [[Ahmedabad]] and [[Guangzhou]] and a similar 'sister states' agreement between [[Gujarat]] and [[Guangdong]] province of China will likely to be signed. Earlier [[Varanasi]] signed partnership agreement with [[Kyoto]], Japan.\n\n==East Asia policy==\n{{Main|Asian foreign policy of Narendra Modi government}}\nFrom the very beginning, the Modi led government made it ample clear that India would focus more and more on improving relation with [[ASEAN]] and other East Asian countries as per India's [[Look East policy (India)|Look East policy]] which was formulated during [[Narasimha Rao]]'s government in 1992 for better economic engagement with its eastern neighbors, but successive government later successfully turned it into a tool for forging strategic partnership and security cooperation with countries in that region in general and Vietnam and Japan in particular.<ref name=\"Vietnam News Agency\"/> In her recent visit to [[Hanoi]], Vietnam Sushma Swaraj has stressed on the need for an [[Act East policy]]<ref name=\"Firstpost\"/> that she said should replace India's over two decade-old Look East Policy emphasizing a more proactive role for India in this region.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\"/>\n\nEast Asia being the major focus area of his foreign policy, Modi and his foreign minister chose several Asian countries for their initial bilateral visits. He has made state visits to Bhutan and Nepal and Japan within the first 100 days of his government followed by visits of Myanmar and Australia and also hosted Asia leaders like Australian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]], Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]] and Vietnamese Prime Minister [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]] apart from inviting [[SAARC]] leaders in his inauguration ceremony. External Affairs Minister Swaraj has also made official visits to several Asian capitals like [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh, [[Kathmandu]], Nepal, [[Naypidaw]], Myanmar, [[Singapore]], [[Hanoi]], Vietnam, [[Manama]], Bahrain, [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, [[Dushanbe]], Tajikistan, [[Male]], Maldives, [[Abu Dhabi]], United Arab Emirates [[Seoul]], South Korea and [[Beijing]], China.\n\n===South China Sea disputes===\nThough India's exclusive economic zone does not extend into the [[South China Sea]], the region is geopolitically important to India as a high volume of its trade passes through the South China Sea. Modi intends India to act as a stabilizing force in the Indo-Pacific Region as a part of Modi's underlying [[Look East policy (India)|Act East]] foreign policy initiative .<ref>{{citation|title=Trump Is Driving Xi into Modi's Arms|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/04/27/trump-is-driving-xi-into-modis-arms/|publisher=[[Foreign Policy]]|date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==South Asia policy==\n{{Further|South Asian foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government}}\nEven before becoming the Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] hinted that his foreign policy will actively focus on improving ties with India's immediate neighbors which is being termed as \"neighborhood first\" policy in the media<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/><ref name=\"India, Modi and the neighbourhood\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times\"/> and he started well by inviting all heads of state/heads of government of South Asian countries in his inauguration and on the second day on office he held bilateral talks with all of them individually which was dubbed as a [[List of SAARC summits|mini SAARC summit]] by the media.<ref name=\"The mini SAARC summit\"/> Later during a launch event at [[ISRO]] he has asked Indian scientists to take the endeavor to develop a dedicated ''SAARC satellite''<ref name=\"claws.in\"/> to share the fruits of the technology like tele-medicine, e-learning etc. with the people across South Asia to complement the currently operating [[Indian Technical and Economic Cooperation Programme]] program in the region.\n\n==West Asia policy==\n{{Further|Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government}}\nIndian External Affairs Ministry refers to the region of 'Middle East' as West Asia and not as Middle East which is a more popular attribution, particularly in the western countries. The region plays a vital role in India's economy as it supplies nearly two third of India's total oil import, bilateral trade is also flourishing in recent years particularly with UAE and other Gulf states. Over the years millions of Indians mostly working class have migrated to the gulf looking for jobs and they account for a sizeable share in the total remittances received from abroad.\n\n===Link West policy===\nIn an attempt to strengthen ties with India's western neighbors specially the [[Persian gulf|gulf countries]], Modi proposed this policy to complement his [[Act East policy]] concerning East Asia. Although it is called 'Link West' (West of India) which gives it a bigger geographical connotation, it is most likely to focus on the [[Middle East|middle-east]] and some of India's strategic thinkers are calling it as Modi's middle-east policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/modi-and-the-middle-east-towards-a-link-west-policy/|title=Modi and the Middle East: Towards a Link West Policy|author=C Raja Mohan|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=5 October 2014|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref> The West Asia Approach of India<ref>[http://www.dnd.com.pk/the-west-asia-approach-of-india-and-its-relations-with-middle-east/103010]</ref> is working successfully and its relations with Middle East are improving since Modi came in power. The \"West Asia Approach\" of India is now its key strategy to win Middle East. Indian foreign policy makers say that India's interests in the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC countries]] are intimately linked with its energy security, trade, employment for Indians and remittances while Middle Eastern foreign policy experts believe that India has showcased itself as \"Security Partner\" during Modi's visit to UAE. Given the economic and human security interests, the stability and security of the GCC countries is crucial for India because huge flow of remittances comes from GCC to the Indian economy.<ref>{{citation |title=India suffers steep decline in remittances from GCC nations |url=http://m.thenational.ae/business/economy/india-suffers-steep-decline-in-remittances-from-gcc-nations |work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date=23 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Stand against ISIS===\nOn 16 December 2014, [[Home Minister of India|Home Minister]] [[Rajnath Singh]] announced in the Parliament that [[ISIS]] is banned as a terrorist organization under the United Nations schedule.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/indian-government-bans-islamic-state-terror-organisation/article6698369.ece|title=India bans IS|agency=Press Trust of India|work=The Hindu|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><!--public announcement says \"we have banned\"--> Following the arrest of few Indian individuals with ISIS connections, on 26 February 2015 India put fresh bans on 'The Islamic States/Islamic States of Iraq and Syria/Islamic States of Iraq and Levant' with all its manifestation and all its affiliates under the [[Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-bans-ISIS-under-UAPA/articleshow/46382427.cms|title=India bans ISIS under UAPA|publisher=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]/''[[The Times of India]]''|date=26 February 2015|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/terror-group-isis-to-be-banned-in-india-739417|title=Terror Group ISIS to be Banned in India|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=13 February 2015|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Israel-Hamas conflict===\n{{Duplication|section=yes|dupe=Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government#Israel|date=April 2018}}\nAt the height of the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|tension between Israel and Hamas]] in July, India offered a rhetorical condemnation holding both sides responsible for erupting violence and asked Israel to stop \"disproportionate use of force\" in Gaza which was read by many{{who|date=May 2017}} as departure from tradition of more vocal supports for the Palestinian cause. External Affairs Minister Swaraj insisted that \"there is absolutely no change in India's policy towards Palestine, which is that we fully support the Palestinian cause while maintaining good relations with Israel. \" clarifying India's current position on the issue. That might sound like fence-sitting, but it is a policy shared by all Indian governments of the past 20 years following the establishment of formal diplomatic relation in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/8/3/modi-israel-relations.html|title=Why Modi's India aligns more closely with Israel than with Palestinians|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=3 August 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nSushma Swaraj, a seasoned parliamentarian, had herself blocked the opposition demand in [[Rajya Sabha]] for passing a resolution condemning Israel for [[2014 Israel-Gaza conflict]] by saying that \"India has friendly relation with both Israel and Palestine and therefore any such move may impact its friendship negatively\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/report/modi-govts-dilemma-over-israel-palestine-conflict/20140716.htm|title=Modi govt's dilemma over Israel-Palestine conflict|publisher=[[Rediff]]|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Although later in a symbolic gesture, India joined other BRICS nations in voting at the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] for a probe into the alleged human rights violation in Gaza which generated mixed response among media and analysts in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/gaza-crisis-modi-govts-unhrc-vote-against-israel-must-be-lauded-1633149.html|title=Gaza crisis: Modi govt's UNHRC vote against Israel must be lauded|work=Firstpost|date=25 July 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Overseas Indian crisis===\n;Iraq\n{{Further|Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)|Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)}}\nWith the rise of [[ISIS]] in northern Iraq, where hundreds of thousands of Indian migrant workers live, the security of those overseas Indians came under threat. On 16 June, the Ministry of External Affairs (MEA) set up a 24-hour helpline at the Indian embassy in [[Baghdad]] for assistance of Indian nationals stranded in the conflict cities. It has been reported that 46 Indian nurses were abducted from the Iraqi town of Mosul<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/06/india-condemns-attacks-and-seizure-in-northern-iraq-by-terrorists/ |title=India condemns attacks and Seizure in Northern Iraq by terrorists |publisher=Bihar Prabha |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> who were later freed and flown back to India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-28173993 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |date=5 July 2014 |title=Indian nurses freed in Iraq given rapturous home welcome |work=[[BBC News]] }}</ref> Moreover, 39 Indian workers from mainly from [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] were taken hostages and the fate of those workers still not known. There were widespread speculations about their lives and on 27 November 2014 ''[[ABP News]]'' reported, citing Bangladeshi migrant co-workers, death of all the 39 men. Although the following day, External Affairs Minister (EAM) Swaraj made a statement to the [[Parliament of India|parliament]] neither rejecting nor confirming such possibility and re-assured the nation about MEA's commitment for continuing search for the Indians in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/govt-sources-say-indians-kidnapped-by-isis-in-iraq-still-alive-efforts-on-to-trace-them-sushma-swaraj/|title=Govt believes 39 Indians held hostage by ISIS in Iraq still alive|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/39-indians-kidnapped-by-isis-in-iraq-are-alive-foreign-affairs-minister-sushma-swaraj-2863311/|title=39 Indians kidnapped by ISIS in Iraq are alive: Sushma Swaraj|date=2016-06-19|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n;Libya\n{{Further|2014 Libyan conflict}}\nA similar situation occurred in Libya where many Indian nationals are stranded because of the armed conflict that broke in [[Benghazi]] and other parts of the country. Swaraj informed the parliament that her ministry was evaluating all possibilities to secure the safe evacuation of all Indians stranded in both Iraq and Libya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-government-to-ensure-safe-return-of-indians-from-iraq-says-sushma-swaraj-2007861|title=Government to ensure safe return of Indians from Iraq, says Sushma Swaraj |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=4 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> A chartered flight from [[Djerba]], Tunisia brought over 200 nationals back to India. A further 216 nationals left on 8 August, with a total of another 1,500 nationals having been evacuated. About 3,000 more nationals registered with the embassy in Tripoli in order to return.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/200-more-Indians-evacuated-from-Libya/articleshow/39848755.cms |title=200 more Indians evacuated from Libya |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> On 5 August, 44 nurses returned to India on a special [[Air India]] flight; they were predominantly from Kerala with some from Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mahim Pratap Singh |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala-nurses-back-from-libya-thank-government/article6299247.ece |title=Nurses thank Indian Mission in Libya, MEA |work=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> A further three Goans were reported to be safe in Libya with full employment and had not requested repatriation. Goa's Director of NRI Affairs U. D. Kamat said that it was ascertaining whether there were Goan workers in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=PTI |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Goans-in-Libya-are-Safe-NRI-Commissionerate/2014/08/12/article2376098.ece |title=Goans in Libya are Safe: NRI Commissionerate |work=The New Indian Express |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Yemen\n{{Main|Operation Raahat (India)}}\nAfter the outbreak of aerial attacks by the Saudi led coalition following the coup by the [[Houthis|Houthi rebels]] in [[Yemen]], Government of India launched a massive rescue operation called ''[[Operation Raahat]]'' (meaning: Relief) to save hundreds of non-residential Indians located there.<ref name=onein2015>{{cite web | title=India evacuates 4,640 nationals, 960 others from Yemen | website=www.oneindia.com | date=2015-04-10 | url=http://www.oneindia.com/india/india-evacuates-4640-nationals-960-others-from-yemen-1711703.html | accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref> Minister of State for External Affairs General [[Vijay Kumar Singh|V K Singh]] himself oversaw the entire rescue operation right from the battle ground towns of [[Sana'a]] and [[Aden]] in Yemen and the Indian base of operation in [[Djibouti]]. In the process, the [[Indian Navy]] deployed its front line ships such as {{INS|Mumbai||6}}, [[INS Sumitra]] and others while the Indian Air Force too deployed its [[C-17 Globemaster]] tactical airlifter to airlift the stranded Indians and the national carrier [[Air India]] also took active part by ferrying passengers.<ref name=hindu-evac>{{cite news|title=India begins evacuating citizens|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-begins-evacuating-citizens/article7054994.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The operation was highly successful and received huge acclamation from across the globe as it rescued not only Indians but thousands of foreigners stranded in the war torn country too.<ref name=\"Firstposta2015\">{{cite web | title=1000 nationals from 41 countries: India's Yemen evacuation finally ends and the world is floored | website=Firstpost | date=2015-04-10 | url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/1000-nationals-41-countries-indias-yemen-evacuation-finally-ends-world-floored-2192271.html | accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"The Times2015\">{{cite web | title=India appreciates Pakistan's gesture of evacuating its nationals from Yemen | website=The Times of India | date=2015-04-08 | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/India-appreciates-Pakistans-gesture-of-evacuating-its-nationals-from-Yemen/articleshow/46852396.cms | accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with North and South America==\n===United States===\n[[File:President Trump's Trip to Germany and the G20 Summit (35741357046).jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] with Modi at the [[2017 G20 Hamburg summit|G20 Hamburg summit]] in July 2017.]]\n\nDuring the run-up to the general election there was wide-ranging scepticism regarding future of the [[India-USA relations|strategic bilateral relation]] under Modi's premiership as in 2005 he was, while [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]], denied a U.S. visa<ref>{{cite news|title=No entry for Modi into US: visa denied|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/No-entry-for-Modi-into-US-visa-denied/articleshow/1055543.cms|work=The Times of India|date=18 March 2005|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> during the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] for his alleged [[2002 Gujarat riots|poor]] human rights records.<ref name=WSJ-visa>{{cite news|last1=Mann|first1=James|title=Why Narendra Modi Was Banned From the U.S.|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303380004579520041301275638?mg=reno64-wsj|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2 May 2014}}</ref> However sensing Modi's inevitable victory well before the election, the [[United States Ambassador to India|US Ambassabor]] [[Nancy Powell]] had reached out to him as part of greater re-approachment from the west. Moreover, following his 2014 election as the Prime Minister of India [[Presidency of Barack Obama|President Obama]] congratulated him over telephone and invited him to visit the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/05/16/readout-president-s-call-prime-ministerial-candidate-narendra-modi-india|title=Readout of the President's Call with Prime Ministerial Candidate Narendra Modi of India|publisher=Whitehouse.gov|date=16 May 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker-may14\">{{cite news|last=Cassidy|first=John|title=What Does Modi's Victory Mean for the World?|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/05/narendra-modi-india-prime-minister-victory.html|accessdate=21 May 2014|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|date=16 May 2014}}</ref> U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] visited New Delhi on 1 August to prepare the grounds for Modi's first ever US visit as Prime Minister. In September 2014, days before visiting the US in an interview to [[CNN]]\u2019s [[Fareed Zakaria]], Modi said that \"India and the United States are bound together, by history and culture\" but acknowledged that there have been \"ups and downs\" in relations.<ref name=CNN-fareed>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/09/21/what-does-modis-cnn-interview-say-about-indias-relationship-with-the-u-s/|title=What Does Modi's CNN Interview Say About India's Relationship With the U.S.?|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=21 September 2014}}</ref> Modi travelled to US from 27\u201330 September 2014,<ref name=hectic>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/narendra-modi-has-hectic-schedule-lined-up-for-maiden-us-trip/articleshow/42122631.cms|title= Narendra Mosi has hectic schedule lined up for maiden US trip |publisher=' ' [[The Economic Times]] ''|date=2014-09-11|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref> beginning with his maiden address in the [[sixty-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly|United Nations general assembly]] followed by attending a gala public reception by the Indian American community in New York's [[Madison Square Garden]] before heading Washington, D.C. for the bilateral talk with Obama. While there, Modi also met several American business leaders and invited them to join his ambitious [[Make in India]] program in a bid to make India a manufacturing hub.<ref name=gmodi>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/28/narendra-modi-india-new-york-prime-minister|title=US turns on charm as Narendra Modi roadshow rolls into New York|last=Burke|first=Jason|date=28 September 2014|newspaper= The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=nytmodi>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/28/world/asia/narendra-modi-madison-square-garden-united-states-indian-diaspora.html|title=Indian Leader Narendra Modi, Once Unwelcome in U.S., Gets Rock Star Reception|last=Sinha|first=Shreeya|date=27 September 2014|newspaper= The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indias-modi-begins-rock-star-like-us-tour/2014/09/26/eeabe78b-9327-4643-a131-33ab5c59174a_story.html|title=India's Modi begins rock star-like U.S. tour|last=Gowen|first=Annie|date=26 September 2014|newspaper= Washington Post}}</ref> Later President Obama greeted Modi by calling him a \"Man of Action\" during their brief interaction at the Gala dinner hosted by Myanmar's President on the eve of [[Ninth East Asia Summit|ninth]] [[East Asia Summit]] this was their second meeting since Obama hosted a rare dinner for Modi at the White House on 29 September 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/barack-obama-meets-prime-minister-narendra-modi-calls-him-a-man-of-action/articleshow/45126409.cms|title=Barack Obama meets Prime Minister Narendra Modi; calls him a 'man of action'|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> On 9 December 2014 [[US Senate]] confirmed [[Richard Verma|Richard Rahul Verma]] as the US Ambassador to India, the first Indian American to hold the office, signalling the Obama administration's will to elevate the relation with India to a newer height. He assumed office in the US Embassy in New Delhi on 19 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/rich-verma-confirmed-as-us-ambassador-to-india/article1-1294981.aspx|title=Rich Verma confirmed as US ambassador to India|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi invited President Obama to be the first US President to grace the [[Republic Day of India|66th Republic Day]] celebration as [[List of state visits to India#Republic Day Parade Guests|Chief guest]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/republic-day-pm-modis-decision-to-invite-obama-aimed-at-sending-a-strong-message-to-china/articleshow/45243213.cms|title=Republic Day: PM Modi's decision to invite Obama aimed at sending a strong message to China |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=23 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> an honour typically reserved for India's closest ally. President Obama was the first US President to visit India twice in office and the two leaders now scheduled to hold back to back summits within six months which is being referred as Modi's diplomatic coup by the media.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/modis-diplomatic-chutzpah/|title=Modi's Diplomatic Chutzpah|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> \"This Republic Day, we hope to have a friend over\u2026 invited President Obama to be the 1st US president to grace the occasion as chief guest.\"- Modi tweeted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.economictimes.indiatimes.com/letterfromwashington/it-took-a-modi-to-finally-invite-a-us-president-for-republic-day/|title=It took a Modi to finally invite a US president for Republic Day|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2017, Modi met with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] in [[Washington, DC]] where they discussed trade, specifically airplanes and natural gas, and terrorism.<ref>Office of the Press Secretary. [https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/06/26/remarks-president-trump-and-prime-minister-modi-india-joint-press Remarks by President Trump and Prime Minister Modi of India in Joint Press Statement], The White House, Washington, DC, 26 June 2017. Retrieved 27 June 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=George |first=Steve |date=27 June 2017 |title=Trump and Modi reaffirm Indian-US relations with a hug |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/27/politics/modi-trump-india-us/index.html |work=[[CNN]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |access-date=27 June 2017 |quote=The first face-to-face meeting between US President Donald Trump and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi was sealed with a bear hug Monday, as the two leaders looked to publicly underscore their newfound friendship.}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\nNarendra Modi met the [[Brazilian President]], [[Dilma Rousseff]] on the sidelines of the [[6th BRICS summit]] in [[Brasilia]], [[Brazil]], in July 2014. Describing Brazil as a key global partner for India, Modi noted that as two democracies and major emerging economies, India and Brazil not only had vast potential for bilateral cooperation, but also to strengthen each other in international forums and advance the interest of the developing world at large. President Rousseff emphasized the special place this relationship enjoyed in Brazil's foreign policy, because of the potential for bilateral cooperation and the international significance of their partnership. She congratulated Narendra Modi for his victory in the elections and wished him all success for India's progress and development. The two leaders also agreed to take steps to further expand and diversify trade and investment flows and deepen cooperation in agriculture and dairy science, conventional and renewable energy, space research and applications, defence, [[Computer security|cyber security]] and environment conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/prime-minister-modi-meets-brazilian-president-dilma-rousseff-155147462.html|title=Prime Minister Modi meets Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff|date=16 July 2014|work=Yahoo News India|accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nIn April 2015 Modi visited [[Canada]] and was the first bilateral visit to that country by an [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] in 42 years. India made a nuclear deal with the Canada's biggest producer of uranium, [[Cameco]], signed a $280 million, five-year deal to supply uranium to fuel Indian nuclear reactors. The long-term deal announced later that Cameco will sell 7.1 million pounds of uranium to India, through 2020.<ref name=\"livemint\">{{cite news|title=10 takeaways from Narendra Modi's trip to France, Germany and Canada|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/Rpfdeth2dn2gPrptUJZhFO/10-takeaways-from-Narendra-Modis-trip-to-France-Germany-an.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=livemint|date=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nModi held bilateral talks with Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]], and signed various [[Memorandum of understanding|MoUs]] like in areas of cybersecurity, skill development, cooperation in the railways and civil aviation front.<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\nModi received \"rockstar\" reception in Canada where he addressed a crowd of over 10,000 at the [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]] Stage in [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"livemint\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=10,000 Indo-Canadians throng Narendra Modi's 'rockstar' show|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/10000-indocanadians-throng-narendra-modis-rockstar-show/540144-3.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=IBNLive|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Rockstar reception' awaits Modi in Toronto|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rockstar-reception-awaits-modi-in-toronto/article7106594.ece|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Hindu|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Indian community to give rock star welcome to Modi|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/canada-s-indian-community-to-give-rock-star-welcome-to-modi-115041500187_1.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=Business Standard|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with European Nations==\n{{See also|India\u2013European Union relations}}\n\n===France===\nFrance is a valuable strategic partner of India in western Europe. Both countries have invested political capital to deepen collaboration in the cultural, economic, social, technological and military realms. Modi met French President [[Francois Hollande]] at the 2014 G-20 Summit in Brisbane, and discussed bilateral strategic, space and defence issues besides committing to global cooperation against terrorism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-meets-french-president-francois-hollande-calls-for-common-fight-against-terror-697514|title=PM Narendra Modi Meets French President Francois Hollande, Calls For Common Fight Against Terror|publisher=[[NDTV]]/[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Following the January 2015 ''[[Charlie Hebdo shooting|Charlie Hebdo]]'' terror attack in Paris, Modi condemned the act of terror and called Hollande to convey condolences on behalf of the people of India as well as express solidarity with the people of France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/NXXrNTEWZRO0mFHjwI8JtM/Modi-calls-Hollande-condemns-Charlie-Hebdo-attack.html|title=Modi calls Hollande, condemns 'Charlie Hebdo' attack|publisher='[[Live Mint]]''date=10 January 2015|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\nFrench foreign minister Laurent Fabius made several visits to New Delhi to unlock stalled negotiations regarding [[Dassault Rafale]] fighter aircraft for [[Indian Air Force]] and the 9900 MW [[Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project|nuclear power plant in Jaitapur]] by the French firm [[Areva]].<ref name=\"Jaitapur n-reactors flagged off but liability concerns remain\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Jaitapur-n-reactors-flagged-off-but-liability-concerns-remain/721283|title=Jaitapur n-reactors flagged off but liability concerns remain|last=Roy|first=Shubhajit |date=7 December 2010|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=18 December 2010|location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Modi choose Paris as his first destination in Europe as part of his ''Link West'' outreach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-visit-france-in-april-invites-french-companies-737310|title=PM Narendra Modi to Visit France in April, Invites French Companies|publisher=[[NDTV]]/[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|date=5 February 2015|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Modi's visit resulted in a government-to-government deal for 36 [[Dassault Rafale]] fighter aircraft in fly-away condition. India and France signed an initial agreement between [[Nuclear Power Corporation of India]] and [[Areva]] regarding the setting up of Jaitapur nuclear power plant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/toi-edit-page/scripting-a-west-side-story-modis-visits-to-france-germany-and-canada-adapt-lessons-learnt-from-chinas-economic-miracle/|title=Scripting a west side story: Modi's visits to France, Germany and Canada adapt lessons learnt from China's economic miracle|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Modi toured the aircraft assembly facilities of [[Dassault Aviation]] in [[Bordeaux]] and [[Airbus]] in [[Toulouse]] where he promoted the ''[[Make in India]]'' campaign by urging the aerospace giants to cultivate manufacturing opportunities in India (Airbus committed to increase its outsourcing from India from current level of US$400 million to US$2 billion by 2020). Modi travelled to [[Lille]] in the north of France to pay hommage at [[Neuve-Chapelle Indian Memorial]] dedicated to the remembrance of 4742 soldiers of the [[Indian Army (1895\u20131947)|British Indian Army]] who died during World War I & II.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/modi-s-make-in-india-dream-takes-off-with-airbus/article1-1336207.aspx|title=Modi in France: Prime Minister visits Airbus facility, pays homage to Indian soldiers|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2015, Indian Prime-Minister Narendra Modi travelled to France for a 2-day visit to attend the ''COP 21'' [[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Modi set to travel 60,000 km in 30 days|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/modi-set-to-travel-60000-km-in-30-days/article7766970.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=16 October 2015}}</ref> Narendra Modi and Fran\u00e7ois Hollande jointly invited over 100 world leaders to join ''InSPA'' (International Agency for Solar Policy & Application) \u2013 a global initiative to promote low-carbon renewable solar energy technologies.<ref>{{cite news|title=France supports India's global solar alliance|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/france-supports-indias-global-solar-alliance/article7900712.ece|newspaper=Hindu Business Line|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paris climate meet: India-led global solar alliance to counter developed nations|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/world/paris-climate-meet-indialed-global-solar-alliance-to-counter-developed-nations/article7916353.ece|newspaper=Hindu Business Line|date=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Narendra Modi, Francois Hollande invite over 100 countries for solar alliance|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/narendra-modi-francois-hollande-invite-over-100-countries-for-solar-alliance/articleshow/49925633.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Climate Change Treaty itself was under threat with President Trump announcing the withdrawal of USA -one of the major polluters as such, USA did become a part of the International Solar Alliance and lauded the efforts of the Indian leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekootneeti.in/2018/03/24/int-solar-alliance-india/|title=International Solar Alliance: India's Expanding Diplomacy|date=2018-03-23|website=The Kootneeti|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIndia invited French President Francois Hollande to be the chief guest at the [[Delhi Republic Day parade|Republic Day parade]] in New Delhi on 26 January 2016. The invitation was conveyed through the visiting French Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius, making France the only country to be invited a record setting [[List of state visits to India#Republic Day Parade Guests|5 times]] to the highly symbolic national ceremonial event.<ref>{{cite news|title=French President Hollande invited as Republic Day guest|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/french-president-hollande-to-be-chief-guest-at-republic-day-celebrations-next-year/|newspaper=Indian Express|date=22 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hollande to be Republic Day chief guest|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/513294/hollande-republic-day-chief-guest.html|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=21 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Francois Hollande to be Chief Guest at 2016 Republic Day celebrations|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/francois-hollande-to-be-the-chief-guest-at-2016-republic-day-celebrations/article7903666.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUK Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] was one of the first world leaders to congratulate Modi soon after his landslide victory in the [[2014 Indian general election|election]]. The two leaders met for the first time on 14 November 2014 on the sidelines of the G20 leaders summit in [[Brisbane]], where the British Prime Minister said improving relations with India was the \"top priority\" of UK foreign policy. He also invited Modi to visit his country at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/relations-with-india-top-priority-david-cameron-to-narendra-modi/articleshow/45150377.cms|title=Relations with India top priority: David Cameron to Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nEarlier Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]] attributed the growth story of South Asia, which was going to grow fastest in 2014\u201315 outside the East Asia region, to the election of Prime Minister Modi and his recent efforts to turn around the economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uk-deputy-pm-nick-clegg-attributes-south-asias-growth-to-modi-dividend/articleshow/45120370.cms|title=UK Deputy PM Nick Clegg attributes South Asia's growth to \"Modi dividend\"|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref> UK hailed Modi's [[Make in India]] policy and is all set to invest in Rajasthan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uk-hails-make-in-india-campaign-plans-investment-in-rajasthan/articleshow/45127676.cms|title=UK hails Make in India camp|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi paid a state visit to the UK in late 2015, meeting [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and prime minister David Cameron. On 13 November 2015 Modi addressed a rally at the new [[Wembley Stadium]] at [[Wembley Park]], north-west [[London]]. 60,000 people, mostly [[British Indian]]s, attended.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34806511|title=Modi visit: UK and India's 'special relationship' hailed|work=BBC News|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nIn April 2015 Modi visited [[Germany]] where he held bilateral talks with [[Chancellor of Germany|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]]. Modi also inaugurated [[Hannover Messe|Hannover Fair 2015]]-world's largest industrial fair,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Modi set to inaugurate world's largest industrial fair in Germany|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-germany-hannover-messe-fair-chancellor-angela-merkel/1/429728.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=India Today|date=12 April 2015}}</ref> where India was the partner country.<ref>{{cite news|title=With Make in India on mind, Prime Minister Narendra Modi opens Hannover fair|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-04-13/news/61103173_1_hannover-fair-prime-minister-narendra-modi-angela-merkel|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nModi made the strongest pitch for the [[Make in India]] initiative in Hannover fair. He said, \"The entire world is looking at India. Demography, democracy and demand are attracting the world to India.\"<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\nThere were announcements of strengthened cooperation in sectors like energy, skill development, science & technology, and the Modi government's initiatives like [[Digital India]] and [[Swachh Bharat Abhiyan|Clean India]].<ref name=\"livemint\"/>\n\n==Relations with Eurasia==\n===Russia===\n[[File:Putin and Modi in New Delhi in 2014.jpeg|thumb|270px|Modi and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] shake hands in New Delhi in 2014]]\nRussia, India's long term strategically for more than half a century, enjoys a special privileged strategic cooperation unparalleled in India's foreign relations. But over the years especially after their end of cold war the relation experienced strain as India started diversifying its defence purchases from a totally Soviet-dominated one. But with Putin and Modi, both with [[Strongman (politics)|strongman]] image at their home country, at the helm of affairs in their respective foreign policy it is expected to get a push.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/for-a-warmer-russian-bear-hug/article6676864.ece?homepage=true|title=For a warmer Russian bear hug|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/india-russia-here-and-now/99/|title=India, Russia, here and now|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> During the 20th 'India-Russia Inter-Governmental Commission on Trade, Economic, Scientific, Technological and Cultural Cooperation' (IRIGC-TEC) held on 5 November 2014 in New Delhi Modi met the Russian deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin and had reassured the visiting side that the new dispensation in New Delhi will continue to attach very high importance to the time-tested and special strategic partnership with Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-attaches-high-importance-to-ties-with-russia-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45047950.cms|title=India attaches high importance to ties with Russia: PM Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=5 November 2014|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> The annual commission meeting had identified new areas of cooperation including prioritising the International North South Corridor Project (INSTC), start negotiating on a Free Trade Agreement between India and the Eurasian customs union, focusing on enhancing economic partnership in areas like energy, civil aviation and diamond trade along with Russian participation in Modi's smart city project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/india-and-russia-to-give-shape-to-joint-economic-vision-package/articleshow/45049613.cms|title=India and Russia to give shape to joint 'economic vision' package|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date= 5 November 2014|accessdate= 4 November 2014}}</ref> Earlier on his first meeting with Putin, emphasising Russia's indispensable position in India's foreign policy Modi went on to saying that even a child in India considers Russia as its ''best friend''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/narendra-modi-vladimir-putin-russia-friendship-brazil-brics-summit/1/372606.html|title=Narendra Modi Vladimir Putin Russia friendship Brazil BRICS summit |magazine=[[India Today]]|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> This meeting in Brazil at the sidelines of BRICS summit served well as the familiarisation between the two leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/pm-narendra-modi-meets-vladimir-putin-says-india-wants-to-deepen-ties-with-russia_947781.html|title=PM Narendra Modi meets Vladimir Putin says India wants to deepen ties with Russia|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nPresident Putin visited New Delhi on 11 December 2014 for the annual summit, first after Modi assumed office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/india-visit-productive-and-positive-vladimir-putin_1513812.html|title=India visit productive and positive: Vladimir Putin|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://inserbia.info/today/2014/11/putins-upcoming-visit-crucial-for-india/|title=Putin's Upcoming Visit Crucial For India|publisher=InSerbia News|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/op-edge/203719-india-russia-ties-summit/|title=Putin's India visit to focus on deeper trade & investment ties|publisher=[[Russia Today]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Trade and energy cooperation dominated the talks as they set a target of US$30 billion of bilateral trade by 2025 with equal amount of investment in each other's economy. On the backdrop of increasing western sanctions Putin earlier signed a gas deal with China worth US$400 billion believed to be heavily tilted in China's favour. India too was keen to strike an energy agreement on line of above.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-27/putin-to-deepen-india-energy-ties-as-modi-seeks-china-treatment.html|title=Putin Eyes India Energy Deals as Modi Seeks China Treatment|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> During the summit both sides agreed for a joint feasibility study of building gas pipeline through China.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/vladimir-putins-productive-india-visit/|title=Vladimir Putin's Productive India Visit|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The two sides signed a total of 16 agreements and memorandum of understanding on various fields. Agreements on long term oil and gas cooperation have been signed between [[ONGC Videsh]] and [[Essar Oil]] of India and Russia's [[Rosneft]], [[Gasprom]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/putin-for-reversing-decline-in-bilateral-trade-with-india/articleshow/45441910.cms|title=Putin for reversing decline in bilateral trade with India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Putin also vowed to install 10 more nuclear reactors in next 20 years including adding more units to [[Kudankulam Nuclear Power Plant|Kudankulam plant]]. Another burgeoning aspect in bilateral relations emerged in the form of Diamond trading, While Russia is the largest producer of raw diamond, India is the global hub of cutting and polishing raw diamonds. Russia has agreed to export raw diamonds to India directly bypassing mediators like Dubai and Belgium. On this occasion the two leaders also attended a ''World Diamond Conference'' held in New Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rbth.com/blogs/2014/12/13/taming_the_babus_biggest_challenge_for_modi_and_putin_40327.html|title=Taming the Babus: biggest challenge for Modi and Putin|newspaper=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|date=13 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The Crimean leader [[Sergey Aksyonov]], who accompanied Putin in New Delhi, met several business delegation to discuss opportunity in the Black sea region although it was termed as unofficial. This has once again raised concerns in Washington, D.C. regarding India's stand on Crimea.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/us-troubled-by-crimean-leaders-india-visit/|title=US 'Troubled' By Crimean Leader's India Visit|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n;Defence ties\nIn the summit, Modi mentioned about his experience with the Russian built carrier [[INS Vikramaditya]] as an example of burgeoning military cooperation and remarked that \"even though India's options have increased, Russia will continue to remain its topmost defence partner\" signalling a long term defence relation. The two sides agreed on joint production of [[Mil Mi-17]] and [[Kamov Ka-226]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/russia-open-for-equal-work-share-on-fgfa/article6712985.ece?widget-art=four-rel|title=India-Russia talks on to finalise copter deal|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=22 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> helicopters with Russian technology in India in compliance with Modi's ''Make in India'' program and also fast forwarding the long pending major projects like the joint development and production of [[Il-214|light transport aircraft]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/russia-expresses-interest-in-aircraft-production-in-india/articleshow/45308203.cms|title= Russia expresses interest in aircraft production in India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> The final design contract of fifth generation joint fighter platform [[Sukhoi FGFA|Sukhoi-HAL FGFA]] is expected to be signed soon as it already lagging by more than 2 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rbth.com/economics/2014/12/03/major_defence_deals_set_to_be_signed_during_putin-modi_summit_40089.html|title=Major defence deals set to be signed during Putin-Modi summit|newspaper=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> India is set to lease a second nuclear powered [[Akula-class submarine]] from Russia after [[INS Chakra (2011)]] which is already in service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-to-lease-another-nuclear-submarine-from-russia/articleshow/45544830.cms|title=India to lease another nuclear submarine from Russia|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Weeks before Putin's visit news of Russian Defence Minister [[Sergei Shoigu]]'s Pakistan visit on 20 November 2014, first such visit in more than 40 years, when the two sides inked a defence cooperation pact. Media reports suggested that Russia was mulling a possible sale of [[Mil Mi-35|Mi 35]] attack copter, the first ever combat platform, to India's arch rival Pakistan.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/new-era-in-russia-pakistan-relations/|title=New Era in Russia-Pakistan Relations?|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> These developments have raised concerned in the Indian strategic community as some see this as a counter move to growing Indo-US defence collaboration. Although the official response was much restrained as they termed it 'significant'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/russian-defence-ministers-visit-to-pakistan-significant-india/articleshow/45364640.cms|title=Russian Defence Minister's visit to Pakistan 'significant': India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Such apprehensions in India about Russia's strategic goals in the region was by the Russian Ambassador Kaladin as he said that it will not do anything detrimental to India's security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/will-never-do-anything-detrimental-to-indias-security-russia/articleshow/45412363.cms|title=Will never do anything detrimental to India's security: Russia|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=8 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Later Putin himself in an interview with India's ''[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]'' news agency said that 'Russia-Pakistan ties in India's long-term interest'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/russiapakistan-ties-in-indias-longterm-interest-putin/article6677459.ece|title=Russia-Pakistan ties in India's long-term interest: Putin|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with Africa==\n===India-Africa Forum Summit===\n{{Main|India-Africa Forum Summit}}\n\nThe third summit in a rotation basis was scheduled to be held in [[New Delhi]], India in December 2014. But lately [[Syed Akbaruddin]], the official spokesperson of [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Indian Foreign Ministry]] told the media that the scheduled summit is now postponed to 2015 and will include more no. of African leaders unlike previous two occasions where the event was restricted to only 10\u201315 African countries. Although media reports claimed that [[Ebola]] outbreak in Western African nations played a key role behind the postponement of the summit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Ebola-Scare-Pushes-India-Africa-Summit-to-2015/2014/09/21/article2441381.ece|title=Ebola Scare Pushes India-Africa Summit to 2015|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=21 September 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> The summit is now rescheduled on 26\u201330 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Biggest-diplomatic-event-India-Africa-summit-from-October-26/articleshow/46691914.cms|title=Biggest diplomatic event: India-Africa summit from October 26}}</ref>\n\n===Mauritius===\n[[Mauritius]] was the only country outside South Asia whose head of government attended Modi's swearing-in ceremony in Delhi. With [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|people of Indian origin]] constituting a large share of its population Mauritius has very good bilateral relations with New Delhi. Swaraj made her maiden trip as foreign minister to the island country on 2 November 2014 to attend the celebration of Apravasi Divas, marking 180 years since the first Indian indentured labourers arrived in Mauritius. There she had called on President [[Rajkeswur Purryag]] and Prime Minister [[Navinchandra Ramgoolam]] to discuss bilateral and regional issues of common interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics%20and%20nation/Sushma-Swaraj-hails-India-Mauritius-friendship/articleshow/45012519.cms|title=Sushma Swaraj hails India-Mauritius friendship|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date= 3 November 2014|accessdate= 4 November 2014}}</ref> On top of her agenda was talk on cooperation between [[Indian Navy]] and Mauritian Coast Guard to ensure the safety and security of the strategically vital Indian Ocean region. In support to her stress on the importance of maritime cooperation three major [[List of active Indian Navy ships|Indian war ships]] were docked in Mauritian waters including a destroyer {{INS|Mumbai||6}}, a frigate {{INS|Talwar|F40|6}} and the fleet tanker {{INS|Deepak||6}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-to-cooperate-with-mauritius-to-safeguard-indian-ocean/articleshow/45015810.cms|title=India to cooperate with Mauritius to safeguard Indian Ocean|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2 November 2014|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi made his first state visit to the island country in March 2015 as part of his larger outreach to India's maritime neighbours in the Indian Ocean where he participated in the Mauritias National Day celebration in [[Port Louis]] on 12 March 2015. He was also present during the commissioning ceremony of [[MCGS Barracuda]], the [[Patrol boat|offshore patrol vessels (OPV)]] that Mauritius bought from [[Kolkata]] based [[GRSE]] shipyard. The ship was earlier handed over on 20 December 2014 which marked India's first warship export.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/meet-the-barracuda-the-first-warship-india-will-export-632304?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Meet the Barracuda \u2013 the First Warship India Will Export|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-india-exports-first-warship-to-mauritius-2045616|title=India exports first warship to Mauritius|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Multilateral Engagements==\nIndia, as one of leading developing countries, plays an active role in important multilateral forums for global governance such as [[United Nations]], [[World Trade Organization]], [[G20]] leaders summit, [[East Asia Summit]], [[BRICS]] summit of emerging economies, [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and often seen as a '[[Third World|third world voice]]'. Apart from these big platforms India also engaged in many regional groupings like the [[BASIC]], [[Shanghai Cooperation Organisation]], [[Indian Ocean Rim Association]], [[IBSA Dialogue Forum]], [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]], [[Mekong\u2013Ganga Cooperation]], [[Bay of Bengal Initiative for Multi-Sectoral Technical and Economic Cooperation|BIMSTEC]] among others.\n\n===BRICS summit===\n[[File:BRICS leaders meet on the sidelines of 2016 G20 Summit in China.jpg|thumb|250 px|The BRICS leaders in 2016. Left to right: [[Michel Temer|Temer]], [[Narendra Modi|Modi]], [[Xi Jinping|Xi]], [[Vladimir Putin|Putin]] and [[Jacob Zuma|Zuma]].]]\n\n{{Main|BRICS}}\nModi in his maiden speech at the [[BRICS]], a group of emerging economies comprising Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa, called for brotherhood among the member states citing ''[[Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam]]'', an ancient Indian concept meaning the entire world is one family, to unitedly face the global challenges.\n\nIndia together with its BRICS partner working toward launching of a financial institute rivalling the western dominated [[World Bank]] and [[IMF]] which was first proposed during the [[4th BRICS summit|New Delhi summit]] in 2012 by the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]]. In the [[6th BRICS summit]] held on 14\u201326 July in [[Fortaleza]], Brazil the group have agreed to establish the bank with a corpus of US$100 billion. The bank would be named the [[New Development Bank]] as suggested by the Indian side but Modi government has failed to bag the bank's headquarter for [[New Delhi]] which would be located in [[Shanghai]], China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/brics-summit-to-be-modi-s-first-multilateral-meet-114070700041_1.html |title=BRICS summit to be Modi's first multilateral meet |author=Press Trust Of India |work=[[Business Standard]]|date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n* Later at an event in [[Brasilia]] BRICS leaders met the [[UNASUR]] heads of state/heads of government. At the same time, the Ministry of External Affairs added Spanish to its list of available languages, which the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' read as \"indicative of the government's intent to go beyond Europe, Asia and the US to forge diplomatic and trade ties with Latin American nations.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pm-narendra-modi-to-leave-for-brazil-tomorrow-for-brics-summit/article1-1239519.aspx |title=BRICS summit: PM Modi leaves for Brazil, also to meet Latin leaders |date= 12 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref> He travelled there via Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/modi-causes-interpreter-crisis-for-external-affairs-ministry-114071200902_1.html?_ga=1.143976821.1702752175.1400080839 |title=Modi causes interpreter crisis for external affairs ministry |date=12 July 2014 |author=Archis Mohan |work=[[Business Standard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit===\n{{Main|Shanghai Cooperation Organisation}}\nIndia is now a full member of the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation, which is known to be a China-backed bloc for military and energy cooperation. It held observer status from 2005 and publicly expressed its wish for a full membership.India and Pakistan joined SCO as full members on 9 June 2017 in Astana, Kazakhstan. Although Russia had all along backed India's entry it was Beijing's reservation which held it so long. However Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] informed Modi during [[6th BRICS summit|BRICS]] summit in Brazil that it is ready to welcome India together with Pakistan in order to project a united front against Islamic extremism in Central Asia including Afghanistan specially after NATO withdrawal. On 11\u201312 September [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|EAM]] Sushma Swaraj attended the [[2014 SCO summit|Dushanbe summit]] in Tajikistan where India formally put its paper for a full membership and it became likely that it would be granted so according to Chinese officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/shanghai-cooperation-organisation-summit-paves-way-for-indias-entry-in-the-group-chinese-experts/articleshow/42396485.cms|title=Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit paves way for India's entry in the group: Chinese experts|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 September 2014|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> Modi participated at the [[heads of government]] summit in [[Astana]], Kazakhstan in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140806/jsp/nation/story_18691973.jsp#.VBEDHvmSzIs|title=Delhigears to join China-Russia club|date=2014-08-06|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===United Nations general assembly===\n{{Main|India and the United Nations}}\nModi delivered his maiden speech in the [[sixty-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly]] on 27 September 2014, where he called for reform and expansion of [[United Nations Security Council]] including India's long standing demand of a permanent membership. He expressed his concerns over the relevance of a 20th-century setup in the 21st century and the need to evaluate UN's performance in the past 70 years. He had also argued why UN should serve as \"G-All\" for global governance instead of several parallel sub-groupings like [[G7]], [[G20]], etc. In the wake of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] threat in West Asia and similar in other parts of the globe he urged for immediate implementation of 'Comprehensive on International Terrorism' by the UN and offered India's pro-active role in it citing India as a victim of terrorism for decades. Prior to his speech he along with External Affairs Minister Swaraj met UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] and discussed UN governance relating issues.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-at-unga-lets-work-towards-a-sustainable-world-move-towards-g-all/articleshow/43642407.cms|title=PM Modi at UNGA: Let's work towards a sustainable world; move towards G-All|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Ridiculing the possibility of any multilateral intervention, a demand [[Nawaz Sharif|Sharif]] has made in his address at the UNGA on 26 September, on Kashmir related matter he stated that his government is ready for 'bilateral talk' to Pakistan provided Pakistan should cultivate suitable environment for talks by giving up terrorism policy against India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cheat-sheet/prime-minister-narendra-modi-s-address-to-un-general-assembly-in-10-points-598833?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Prime Minister Narendra Modi's Address to UN General Assembly in 10 Points|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Modi commented briefly on climate change and use of clean energy, in this regards he also asked world leaders and UN officials for observing International Yoga Day, emphasizing the importance of incorporating [[Yoga]] in modern-day life style.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-asks-world-leaders-to-adopt-international-yoga-day/articleshow/43646752.cms|title=PM Modi asks world leaders to adopt International Yoga Day|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the sidelines, he held bilateral meetings with Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]], Sri Lankan President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] and Nepali Prime Minister [[Sushil Koirala]] taking his 'neighbourhood first' policy forward even in [[New York City]]. But there was no meeting with Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] following the recent low in the relation. Later he also met where [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], in a first meeting in 11 years between the two heads of government, the Israeli Prime Minister who had highlighted the potential of the bilateral relation saying \"sky is the limit\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/prime-minister-narendra-modi-meets-his-israeli-counterpart-benjamin-netanyahu/articleshow/43784668.cms|title=Prime Minister Narendra Modi meets his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===ASEAN-India summit===\nAssociation of South East Asian Nations or ASEAN is the 10 member block, it is one of the most successful regional block in the world. India started looking toward the group seriously from 1992 with the launch of 'Look East policy' and now it occupies the central position in India's policy Southeast Asia. From 2002 onward India and ASEAN started holding an annual summit at the sidelined of ASEAN summit showing the growing level of engagement between the two sides.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29999880|title=Indian PM Narendra Modi begins trip to Myanmar, Australia and Fiji|publisher=BBC|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/narendra-modi-arrives-in-myanmar-to-attend-asean-east-asia-summits-1415705110|title=Narendra Modi Arrives in Myanmar for Regional Summits|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[ASEAN|12th India-ASEAN]] summit, which was Modi's first appearance in an ASEAN meet, he called for greater connectivity with the Southeast Asian countries and mentioned that \"India and ASEAN can be 'great partners'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-and-asean-can-be-great-partners-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45122200.cms|title=India and ASEAN can be 'great partners': PM Narendra Modi |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014}}</ref> Stressing on the importance ASEAN commands in India's foreign policy Modi has repeatedly remarked that his government has in the last 6 months made relation with ASEAN a top priority and turned India's two decade old 'Look East policy' into 'Act East policy' which reflects a renewed momentum in India's approach toward ASEAN nations. The two sides also discussed the scope of extending the existing free trade agreement on service sector as well and ways to increase [[India-ASEAN Free Trade Area|India-ASEAN]] trade which is expected to reach US$100 billion in 2015. Modi also stressed on three 'C's to strengthen the relation and those are commerce, connectivity and cultural links.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/look-east-has-become-act-east-policy-pm-modi-at-asean/|title='Look East' has become 'Act East Policy': PM Narendra Modi at ASEAN|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of ASEAN summit Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including Thai Prime Minister Gen [[Prayuth Chan-ocha]], Singapore's Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]], Sultan of Brunei [[Hassanal Bolkiah]], Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] and South Korean President [[Park Geun-hye]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/narendra-modis-make-in-india-pitch-gets-thai-pms-support/articleshow/45121092.cms|title=Modi's 'Make in India' pitch gets Thai PM's support|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n;ASEAN Regional Forum\nEarlier Swaraj had attended the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|2014 ASEAN Regional Forum]] followed by the related [[East Asia Summit|EAS Foreign Ministers meeting]], held from 8\u201311 August in [[Naypidaw]], Myanmar, which was her first ever appearance in multilateral forums after becoming India's foreign affairs head. At the sidelines of the multilateral meetings she had also held bilateral meetings with her counterparts from seven countries including China, Australia, Canada, Vietnam, Philippines, Brunei and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-08-08/news/52594297_1_india-asean-trade-south-china-east-asia-summit |title=Sushma Swaraj in Myanmar for ASEAN meet, East Asia Summit |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/world/sushma-swaraj-asean-summit-pham-binh-minh-modi-syed-akbaruddin-18260.html |title=Swaraj holds 7 bilateral meetings on sidelines of ASEAN summit |publisher=Indiatvnews.com |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn regards to controversy of territorial ownership in the [[South China Sea]], a contentious issue impacting most [[ASEAN]] member states, where [[ONGC Videsh]] has investment in oil blocks, [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|MEA]] spokesperson [[Syed Akbaruddin]] said: \"India is not a party to the dispute in the South China Sea. We feel that the dispute should be resolved between those who are party to it in a peaceful manner and it should be in accordance with international law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/sushma-swaraj-describes-myanmar-visit-as-very-successful_953902.html|title=Sushma Swaraj Describes Myanmar Visit as Very Successful|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=11 August 2014|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===East Asia summit===\n{{Main|East Asia Summit}}\n[[File:National leaders at the 9th East Asia Summit at Nay Pyi Taw, Myanmar.jpg|thumb|Modi ''(fifth from left)'' with national leaders at the 9th EAS in [[Nay Pyi Daw]], Myanmar.]]\nEast Asia Summit (EAS) which is an ASEAN led dialogue forum comprises 18 countries, 10 core ASEAN nations along with Japan, China, South Korea, India, Australia, New Zealand, Russia and the United States. Over the years EAS has become the most important multilateral body in the Asia pacific region for discussing security, trade and commerce, environment and others unlike [[APEC]] which is purely economic in nature. Modi participated in the [[Ninth East Asia Summit|ninth]] [[East Asia Summit]] in [[Nay Pyi Daw]], Myanmar in November which was his second major multilateral even after [[6th BRICS summit|BRICS]] in July. Describing the importance of the EAS in managing regional security, Modi mentioned \"No other forum brings together such a large collective weight of global population, youth, economy and military strength. Nor is any other forum so critical for peace, stability and prosperity in Asia-Pacific and the world\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/look-east-policy-now-turned-into-act-east-policy-modi/article6595186.ece?homepage=true&ref=relatedNews|title='Look East' policy now turned into 'Act East' policy: Modi|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith a veiled reference of the [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|issue of South China Sea]] Modi has asked the global community for respecting maritime norms and regulations and stressed on the importance of maintaining free and secured sea-lines of communication for regular trade and commerce.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/narendra-modi-calls-for-respect-for-global-maritime-norms/articleshow/45124226.cms|title=Narendra Modi calls for respect for global maritime norms|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> He made a remark that \"In a world of interdependence and globalisation, there is no option but to follow international laws and norms. This also applies to maritime security. For this reason, following international law and norms is important for peace and stability in South China Sea as well\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/many-complex-security-concerns-in-east-asia-region-pm-narendra-modi/articleshow/45133252.cms|title=Many complex security concerns in East Asia region: PM Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Modi also focused on the role of EAS member countries to tackle the menace of terrorism in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-asean-must-collaborate-to-tackle-terrorism-narendra-modi/articleshow/45138187.cms|title=India, ASEAN must collaborate to tackle terrorism: Narendra Modi|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Modi also highlighted the re-opening of [[Nalanda University]] and the role of all EAS member states into it to showcase the joint effort of the block. Among others the issue of [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP) was discussed in details during the summit.\n\nIn the sidelines of EAS Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including Russia Premier [[Dmitry Medvedev]], The Philippines President [[Benigno Aquino III|Benigno Aquino]], Chinese Premier [[Li Keqiang]] and Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/as-aeas-kicksoff-modi-meeds-medvedev-obama-kicks-up-a-row/99/|title=As EAS kicksoff, Narendra Modi meets Medvedev, Obama kicks up a row|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===G-20 leaders summit===\n{{Main|G20}}\n[[File:Heads of the 2014 G-20 member state delegations, invited nations and international organisations (6).jpg|thumb|Modi ''(third from left)'' with national leaders at the 2014 G-20 summit.]]\nG20 or the Group of 20 leading economies (advanced and emerging markets) of the world formed after the [[2008 financial crisis]] for international financial governance. India which ranks 5 in terms of nominal GDP and the fastest growing economy plays an important role in the group since it began in 2008. For the first time in 2014, India was represented by Prime Minister Modi unlike all the previous summits when [[Dr. Manmohan Singh]], a renowned economist, used to be the Prime Minister. The host and President of [[2014 G-20 Brisbane summit|2014 summit]] Australia's [[Tony Abbott]] intended the summit to focus exclusively on revamping the crisis prone fragile economy and to add US$2 trillion in the global economy by additional 2% global GDP growth rate for the next five years but countries like US was more keen to discuss issues of Climate change and reduction of Carbon emission as it sealed a similar pact with China. India's interest was also aligned with Abbott as it wants to reboot its economy and return to the high growth trajectory soon. In <ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/g20-importance-of-the-summit-possible-takeaways-for-india/articleshow/45160632.cms|title=G20: Importance of the summit & possible takeaways for India|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nModi, a chaiwallah (roadside tea vendor) turned politician eventually became the Prime Minister of world's largest democracy winning the highest number of votes in the history, was the most sought after world leader at the G20 in Brisbane and ''[[The Guardian]]'' called Modi the ''G20's political rock star'' commenting on Modi's popularity in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/nov/14/narendra-modi-from-international-pariah-to-the-g20s-political-rock-star|title=Narendra Modi: from international pariah to the G20's political rock star|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> His personal rapport with host Australian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] was something to watch out for. Abbott who was meeting Modi for the third time, after his [[New Delhi]] trip in September and in [[Nay Pyi Daw]] just 2 days back, extended a warm hug toward Modi while welcoming world leaders in the summit venue in Brisbane. This also generated in the Australian media circle as there was 'no hug' even for Abbott's long-time friend Cameron. Modi, on his longest trip of 10 days to three different countries, met leaders from 40 different countries and even his Australia trip didn't end at Brisbane thereafter he visited Sydney, Melbourne and Canberra what is being referred as his 'diplomatic juggernaut'.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/prime-minister-narendra-modi-on-tour-no-time-to-breathe/articleshow/45156376.cms |title= Prime Minister Narendra Modi on tour, no time to breathe!|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe issue of [[Black money|black]] or unaccounted money kept in tax heavens (countries that allow foreigners to dump huge unaccounted money) abroad was also raised by Modi which is also a burning issue in India's domestic polity. He also stressed on the need of changing laws in certain countries to allow better information sharing of black money kept abroad as it is also linked to the terror funding.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-in-brisbane-g20-summit-black-money-cooperation/1/400716.html|title=PM Modi arrives in Australia, global cooperation on black money tops agenda at G20|magazine=[[India Today]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> India the world's largest recipient of remittances with $71 billion sent last year, pushed hard for the reduction in the remittance costs of non-residents at the G20 summit, asking it to work on steps to reduce costs in sending money home from abroad which is as high as 10 per cent in some countries. Earlier India has been able to convince Saudi Arabia to reduce it to 3.5 per cent. G20 agreed to bring down the global average cost of transferring remittances to 5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/forex-and-remittance/g20-vows-to-reduce-cost-of-transferring-remittances-to-5/articleshow/45166444.cms|title=G20 vows to reduce cost of transferring remittances to 5%|publisher=|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of G20 Modi also held several bilateral meetings with his counterparts including British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], European Union President [[Herman Van Rompuy]], Saudi Crown Prince [[Salman of Saudi Arabia|Salman bin Abdulaziz]], Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and also attended a special dinner hosted by his friend [[Shinzo Abe]], Prime Minister of Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-meets-world-leaders-on-sidelines-of-g20/articleshow/45159594.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi meets world leaders on sidelines of G20 |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> Even before the G20 summit formally begins all five leaders of the [[BRICS]] grouping gathered in Brisbane for an informal meeting at the invitation of Brazilian President [[Dilma Rousseff]] to discuss issues concerning the group like the [[New Development Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/narendra-modi-lauds-brazilian-dilma-rousseffs-leadership/article6603137.ece?homepage=true|title=Narendra Modi lauds Brazilian Dilma Rousseff's leadership|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=15 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation===\n{{Main|SAARC}}\nRelations with the immediate neighbours in South Asia, which have allegedly long been neglected by the previous governments, became a priority feature in Modi's foreign policy. He started well by inviting all the heads of states/governments of the neighbouring countries at his inauguration and then pushed for an early summit to encourage cooperation in many regional issues like trade, connectivity, infrastructure, transit facility among the member states. In his [[18th SAARC summit|maiden SAARC summit]] in Nepalese capital [[Kathmandu]] he had focused on greater people to people contacts, better connectivity, commercial linkages within the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/modi-talks-about-closer-south-asian-integrationat-saarc-summit/article6636029.ece?homepage=true&ref=relatedNews|title= Modi talks about 'closer South Asian integration'at SAARC Summit|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nChina, which holds an observer status in the group, was represented by Vice Foreign Minister Liu Zhenmin seen actively promoting a more active role for itself in the region including infrastructure funding through its proposed [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB) and extending its ambitious [[Maritime Silk Road]] project to South Asian nations. Pakistan, China's all weather friend, also vouched for a more participatory role for the observer nations in the summit process, indirectly advocating for a more Chinese involvement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/at-saarc-pakistan-rebuffed-by-india-over-this-china-issue-626011?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=At SAARC, Pakistan Rebuffed by India Over This China Issue|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> Although no such proposal was accepted because of India's reservation.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/china-makes-inroads-into-indias-backyard/|title=China Makes Inroads Into India's Backyard|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIndia had earlier advanced three proposal to boost connectivity in the region and those were the 'Regulation of Passenger and Cargo Vehicular Traffic amongst SAARC Member States' for seamless vehicular movement beyond the national borders the 'SAARC Regional Agreement on Railways' for international rail service and the 'SAARC Framework Agreement for Energy Cooperation (Electricity)' for energy trade in the subcontinent which is often regarded as world's most energy-starved region. Pakistan which is the second largest economy in the block threatened to jeopardise the entire summit by not agreeing any of the three proposed agreements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/saarc-in-trouble-pakistan-opposing-india-s-proposals-say-sources-625834|title=SAARC in Trouble? Pakistan Opposing India's Proposals, say Sources|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> Indian Foreign Minister Sushma Swaraj had a brief interaction with [[Sartaj Aziz]], Pakistan's foreign affairs advisor which was seen as possible ice-breaker but later the Indian side termed it as \u2018courtesy call\u2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/swaraj-aziz-meet-briefly-on-saarc-sidelines/|title=Swaraj, Aziz meet briefly on SAARC sidelines|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> The Nepalese delegation including Prime Minister Koirala, the summit host, tried hard to mediate between India and Pakistan to rescue the summit from total failure which led to a hand-shake between Modi and Sharif at the end.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/nepal-played-key-role-in-narendra-modi-nawaz-sharif-handshake/articleshow/45300842.cms|title=Nepal played key role in Narendra Modi-Nawaz Sharif handshake|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/an-epic-handshake-that-salvaged-the-kathmandu-saarc-summit-114112900792_1.html|title=An epic handshake that salvaged the Kathmandu Saarc summit|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> Finally all the sides agreed to sign the 'SAARC Framework Agreement for Energy Cooperation (Electricity)' only as a face-saving measure for the Kathmandu summit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/saarc-leaders-reach-energy-deal/article6639785.ece?homepage=true|title=SAARC leaders reach last-minute energy deal|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the sidelines of the main summit, Modi also held bilateral meetings with leaders of Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal, Maldives and Sri Lanka with a notable exception of Pakistan due to ongoing stand-off between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-holds-bilateral-talks-with-saarc-leaders-except-nawaz-sharif/articleshow/45288456.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi holds bilateral talks with SAARC leaders except Nawaz Sharif|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation===\nAlthough India is not a member of [[APEC]], Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]], the host of the [[APEC China 2014|2014 APEC summit]], invited Modi to attend the event in [[Beijing]] as a guest and also showed willingness to support India's bid to join APEC. India already enjoys such support from other member states such as Russia and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/08/chinas-apec-diplomacy|title=China's APEC Diplomacy|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=2014-08-30|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> However, Modi did not participate in the meeting as a host partner country on the line of Pakistan and Bangladesh on the account of busy diplomatic schedule and a likely state visit to China next year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141106/jsp/nation/story_19003980.jsp|title=Air miles axe on Modi China trip|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)]]|date=6 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications===\n{{Main|International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications}}\nPM Modi has brought together 120 countries to form a solar alliance named ''International Agency for Solar Technologies & Applications (INSTA)''.<ref>{{citation|title=PM Narendra Modi and French President Francois Hollande to launch game changing solar alliance|url=http://economictimes.com/industry/energy/power/pm-narendra-modi-and-french-president-francois-hollande-to-launch-game-changing-solar-alliance/articleshow/49975568.cms|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|date=30 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Asia Africa Growth Corridor (AAGC) ===\nIn November 2016, Japan's Prime Minister Shinzo Abe and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi in their Summit Joint Statement reiterated the resolve of the two countries to \u201cdevelop industrial corridors and industrial network for the growth of Asia and Africa.\u201d India-Japan economic engagement with Africa, under the aegis of Asia Africa Growth Corridor (AAGC), is based on the premise that the direction of global economic activities is indeed shifting towards the [[Indo-Pacific]] region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekootneeti.in/2017/12/27/africa-jp-ind1/|title=The Growth Triad - India-Japan-Africa {{!}} The Asian Contest for Africa|date=2017-12-27|website=The Kootneeti|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nAAGC seeks to provide an alternative model of development and partnership between developed and developing countries/region for mutual benefit incorporating interconnectivity, infrastructure development, and capacity building.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Prime Ministerial trips made by Narendra Modi]]\n* [[Asian foreign policy of Narendra Modi government]]\n** [[South Asian foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government]]\n** [[Middle Eastern foreign policy of the Narendra Modi government]]\n* [[Sushma Swaraj's tenure as External Affairs Minister]]\n* [[Timeline of prime ministership of Narendra Modi]]\n* [[Domestic policy of Narendra Modi]]\n* (PM visits Indian Ocean Island countries )<ref>{{cite web|author=Vikash Anand (Chief Editor) |url=http://janlok.in/pm-visits-indian-ocean-island-countries/ |title=PM visits Indian Ocean Island countriesJanlok &#124; Janlok |publisher=Janlok.in |date= |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>\n*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/narendra-modi-first-foreign-leader-to-address-nepal-parliament-396.html | title=Narendra Modi first foreign leader to address Nepal parliament | publisher=[[India TV]] | date=26 July 2014 | accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \"Indian Foreign Policy:The Modi Era\" by Harsh V Pant \n* \"My Prime Minister Narendra Modi (Foreign Visits & Achievements)\" by NK Sood \n* [https://www.amazon.in/Modi-Doctrine-Foreign-Policy-Minister/dp/9386141159 Sreeram Chaulia (September 2016) ''Modi Doctrine: The Foreign Policy of India's Prime Minister'' \u2013 ''Bloomsbury India'']\n* [http://www.dnaindia.com/analysis/standpoint-do-we-finally-have-an-assertive-foreign-policy-under-pm-narendra-modi-2077065 Jaideep Prabhu (13 April 2015) ''Do we finally have an assertive foreign policy under PM Narendra Modi?'' \u2013 ''DNA'']\n\n{{Foreign relations of India}}\n\n<!-- Categories:  alphabetical -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Policy Of Narendra Modi}}\n[[Category:Foreign relations of India]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy of the Narendra Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy by government|Modi, Narendra]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_policy_of_the_Narendra_Modi_government"}
{"title_page": "Fukui Fumimasa", "text_new": "Fukui Fumimasa<ref>Fukui's monastic name was 'Bunga'.</ref> (June 6, 1934<ref name=\"Gendai 2007\">Gendai 2007</ref> - May 4, 2017) was a Japanese Buddhist scholar-monk, [[Sinology]] scholar and [[Tendai]] monk; he was a monk in the second highest grade.  He was born in [[Nikk\u014d, Tochigi|Nikk\u014d]], located in [[Tochigi Prefecture]].  He was the chief monk at Yuishinin Temple located at Nikkozan [[Rinn\u014d-ji]] Temple and was professor emeritus at [[Waseda University]]. His father was Fukui K\u014djun, and his younger brother was Fukui Shigemasa.  Both father and brother are Asian Studies scholars and Tendai Buddhist monks.\n\n== Brief History ==\nFukui was born in Tokyo.  He went to [[Waseda University Honjo Senior High School]] and specialized in Asian Philosophy at Waseda University's Literature Department.  Fukui pursued advanced studies at Waseda and received both his Masters and Doctorate degrees there.  He went abroad to study in France and was a student of [[Paul Demi\u00e9ville]] (1894-1979).  Fukui later became a professor at Waseda University.\nFukui specialized in the historical [[philology]] of the [[Heart Sutra]] and the theories on the formation of [[Taoism|Daoism]]. \nIn 1991, he was honored with the rank of chevalier in the French [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]] for his extraordinary scholastic merit. \nIn 2014, he was honored with the Japanese [[Order of the Sacred Treasure]]. \nHe was a member of the 17th and 18th [[Science Council of Japan]].\nFrom 1996 to 2004, he was the eighth president of Waseda University's Young Buddhist Association.<ref name=\"Fukui70\">The Committee 2005</ref> (For a detailed introduction to Fukui, please read some of the 48 essays found in \"Thought and Ritual in the Asian Cultural Sphere.\")\n\n== Selected Bibliography ==\n\n===Sole Author===\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui|first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5)|script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u7684\u7814\u7a76|trans-title=Study of the History of the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra|publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]]|year=1987|language=ja,zh,en|isbn=978-4393111284}}\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6b27\u7c73\u306e\u6771\u6d0b\u5b66\u3068\u6bd4\u8f03\u8ad6 |trans-title=Study of European and American Oriental Studies |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Ry\u016bbunkan]] |year=1991 |language=ja |isbn=978-4897473147}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u4e2d\u56fd\u601d\u60f3\u7814\u7a76\u3068\u73fe\u4ee3 |trans-title=Research into Chinese Thought and Today |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Ry\u016bbunkan]] |year=1991 |language=ja |isbn=978-4897473154}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u5316\u570f\u306e\u601d\u60f3\u3068\u5b97\u6559 \u5112\u6559\u3001\u4ecf\u6559\u3001\u9053\u6559 |trans-title=Thought and Religion in the Sinographic Sphere : Confucianism, Buddhism and Daoism |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=1998 |language=ja |isbn=978-4795253933}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u306e\u7dcf\u5408\u7684\u7814\u7a76 \u6b74\u53f2\u30fb\u793e\u4f1a\u30fb\u8cc7\u6599 |trans-title=History of Research into the Synthesis of the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra : History, Society and Historical Data |publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]] |year=2000 |language=ja |isbn=978-4393112045}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u9053\u6559\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u69cb\u9020 \u5897\u88dc\u4fee\u8a02 |trans-title=History of Daoism and its Formation - Revised and Supplemented |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2000 |language=ja |isbn=}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u5316\u570f\u306e\u5ea7\u6a19 |trans-title=The Sinographic Cultural Sphere |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2002 |language=ja,zh,en,fr |isbn=978-4896197419}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u30c9\u30ea\u30eb |trans-title=Exercises in the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra |publisher=[[Hitotsubashi Group|Hitotsubashi Shoten]] |year=2005 |language=ja |isbn=978-4565076007}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u601d\u60f3\u6982\u8ad6 |trans-title=Outline of Asian Thought |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2006 |language=ja |isbn=978-4896197433}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u30e8\u30fc\u30ed\u30c3\u30d1\u306e\u6771\u65b9\u5b66\u3068\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u7814\u7a76\u306e\u6b74\u53f2 |trans-title=History of European Oriental Studies and Research into the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2008 |language=ja |isbn=978-4896197440}}\n\n=== Co-authored Works===\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |editor-last=Makita |editor-first=Tairy\u014d (\u7267\u7530\u8ae6\u4eae) |script-title=ja:\u6566\u714c\u3068\u4e2d\u56fd\u4ecf\u6559\u3000\u8b1b\u5ea7\u6566\u714c7 |trans-title=Dunhuang and Chinese Buddhism, Lectures on Dunhuang Volume 7 |publisher=[[:ja:\u5927\u6771\u51fa\u7248\u793e|Dait\u014d Shuppansha]] |year=1984 |volume=7 |language=ja |isbn=4500004564}}\n* {{Citation |editor-last=Fukui  |editor-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |editor-last2=Nitta |editor-first2=Daisaku (\u65b0\u7530\u5927\u4f5c) |script-title=ja:\u30c1\u30e3\u30ec\u30f3\u30b8\u6f22\u548c\u8f9e\u5178 |trans-title=Challenge Chinese&ndash;Japanese Dictionary |publisher=[[Benesse|Fukutake Shoten]] |year=1991 |language=ja |isbn=978-4828804309}}\n* {{Citation |author-last=Fukui  |author-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |editor-last=Yamada |editor-first=Toshiaki (\u5c71\u7530\u5229\u660e) |editor-last2=Maeda |editor-first2=Shigeki (\u524d\u7530\u7e41\u6a39) |script-title=ja:\u9053\u6559\u3068\u4e2d\u56fd\u601d\u60f3\u3000\u8b1b\u5ea7\u9053\u6559 4 |trans-title=Daoism and Chinese Thought&ndash; Lectures on Daoism Volume 4 |publisher=[[:ja:\u96c4\u5c71\u95a3|Y\u016bzankaku]] |year=1991 |volume=4 |language=ja |isbn=978-4639016946}}\n* {{Citation |editor-last=Fukui  |editor-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6771\u65b9\u5b66\u306e\u65b0\u8996\u70b9 |trans-title=New Viewpoints on East Asian Studies |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2003 |language=ja |isbn=978-4896197426}}\n\n=== Translations by Fukui Fumimasa ===\n* {{Citation |author-last=Gernet |author-first=Jacques |author-link=Jacques Gernet |translator-last=Fukui  |translator-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u53e4\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd |trans-title=Ancient China |publisher=[[:ja:\u767d\u6c34\u793e|Hakusuisha]]/Collection [[Que sais-je?]] |last=|first=|title=La Chine Ancienne|volume=|pages=|year=1965 |language=ja |others=(Original language in French)}}\n* {{Citation |author-last=Chen |author-first=Kenneth Kuan Sheng |author-link=Kenneth K.S. Chen |translator-last=Fukui  |translator-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |translator-last2=Okamoto |translator-first2=Tensei (\u5ca1\u672c\u5929\u6674) |script-title=ja:\u4ecf\u6559\u3068\u4e2d\u56fd\u793e\u4f1a |trans-title=Buddhism and Chinese Society |publisher=[[:ja:\u91d1\u82b1\u820e|Kinbanasha]] |series=The World of Buddhist Culture (\u53e2\u66f8\u30fb\u4ecf\u6559\u6587\u5316\u306e\u4e16\u754c) |last=|first=|title=The Chinese Transformation of Buddhism|volume=|pages=|year=1981 |language=ja}}\n* {{Citation |author-last=Stein |author-first=Rolf |author-link=Rolf Stein |translator-last=Fukui  |translator-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |translator-last2=Myojin |translator-first2=Hiroshi (\u660e\u795e\u6d0b) |script-title=ja:\u76c6\u683d\u306e\u5b87\u5b99\u8a8c |trans-title=The Universe of Bonsai |publisher=[[:ja:\u305b\u308a\u304b\u66f8\u623f|Serika Shob\u014d]] |series=Asian Culture (\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u6587\u5316\u53e2\u66f8) |last=|first=|title=Jardins en miniature d'Extreme-Orient|volume=|pages=|year=1985 |language=ja |others=(Original language in French)|isbn=978-4796701433}}\n* {{Citation |translator-last=Fukui  |translator-first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |translator-last2=Matsuo |translator-first2=Yoshiki (\u677e\u5c3e\u826f\u6a39) |script-title=ja:\u5927\u4e57\u4ecf\u5178\u3000\u4e2d\u56fd\u30fb\u65e5\u672c\u7bc710\u3000\u6566\u714c\u2160 |trans-title=Mahayana Buddhist Sutras: Chinese and Japanese works Volume 10, Dunhuang Part 1 |publisher=[[Chuokoron-Shinsha|Ch\u016b\u014dk\u014dronsha]] |volume=10 |year=1992 |language=ja |others=(Original language in Chinese)|isbn=978-4124026306}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note|35em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|}}\n* {{citation |last=Gendai |trans-title=Who's who in Modern Japan 2004 |author-link=Nichigai WHO |script-title=ja:\u73fe\u4ee3\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u540d\u9332 |year=2004 |publisher=Nichigai Associates}}\n* {{citation |last=The Committee for the Printing of Collected Essays Commemorating Dr. Fukui Fumimasa's 70th Birthday and Retirement (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5\u535a\u58eb\u53e4\u7a00\u30fb\u9000\u8077\u8a18\u5ff5\u8ad6\u96c6\u520a\u884c\u4f1a) |isbn=978-4393112335 |script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u6587\u5316\u306e\u601d\u60f3\u3068\u5100\u793c |trans-title=Thought and Ritual in the Asian Cultural Sphere |language=ja,en|year=2005 |publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ci.nii.ac.jp/author?q=\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5 CiNii>\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5] (in Japanese)\n* [http://tripitaka.l.u-tokyo.ac.jp/INBUDS/search.php?m=sch&a=&uekey=\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5 INBUDS>\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5] (in Japanese)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fukui Fumimasa}}\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo Metropolis]]\n[[Category:Waseda University alumni]]\n[[Category:Waseda University faculty]]\n[[Category:Japanese sinologists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Japanese orientalists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist scholars]]\n", "text_old": "Fukui Fumimasa<ref>Fukui's monastic name was 'Bunga'.</ref> (June 6, 1934<ref name=\"Gendai 2007\">Gendai 2007</ref> - May 4, 2017) was a Japanese Buddhist scholar-monk, [[Sinology]] scholar and [[Tendai]] monk; he was a monk in the second highest grade.  He was born in [[Nikk\u014d, Tochigi|Nikk\u014d]], located in [[Tochigi Prefecture]].  He was the chief monk at Yuishinin Temple located at Nikkozan [[Rinn\u014d-ji]] Temple and was professor emeritus at [[Waseda University]]. His father was Fukui K\u014djun, and his younger brother was Fukui Shigemasa.  Both father and brother are Asian Studies scholars and Tendai Buddhist monks.\n\n\n== Brief History ==\nFukui was born in Tokyo.  He went to [[Waseda University Honjo Senior High School]] and specialized in Asian Philosophy at Waseda University's Literature Department.  Fukui pursued advanced studies at Waseda and received both his Masters and Doctorate degrees there.  He went abroad to study in France and was a student of [[Paul Demi\u00e9ville]] (1894-1979).  Fukui later became a professor at Waseda University.\nFukui specialized in the historical [[philology]] of the [[Heart Sutra]] and the theories on the formation of [[Taoism|Daoism]]. \nIn 1991, he was honored with the rank of chevalier in the French [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]] for his extraordinary scholastic merit. \nIn 2014, he was honored with the Japanese [[Order of the Sacred Treasure]]. \nHe was a member of the 17th and 18th [[Science Council of Japan]].\nFrom 1996 to 2004, he was the eighth president of Waseda University's Young Buddhist Association.<ref name=\"Fukui70\">The Committee 2005</ref> (For a detailed introduction to Fukui, please read some of the 48 essays found in \"Thought and Ritual in the Asian Cultural Sphere.\")\n\n\n== Selected Bibliography ==\n\n===Sole Author===\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui|first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5)|script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u7684\u7814\u7a76|trans-title=Study of the History of the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra|publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]]|year=1987|language=ja,zh,en|isbn=978-4393111284}}\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6b27\u7c73\u306e\u6771\u6d0b\u5b66\u3068\u6bd4\u8f03\u8ad6 |trans-title=Study of European and American Oriental Studies |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Ry\u016bbunkan]] |year=1991 |language=ja |isbn=978-4897473147}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u4e2d\u56fd\u601d\u60f3\u7814\u7a76\u3068\u73fe\u4ee3 |trans-title=Research into Chinese Thought and Today |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Ry\u016bbunkan]] |year=1991 |language=ja |isbn=978-4897473154}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u5316\u570f\u306e\u601d\u60f3\u3068\u5b97\u6559 \u5112\u6559\u3001\u4ecf\u6559\u3001\u9053\u6559 |trans-title=Thought and Religion in the Sinographic Sphere : Confucianism, Buddhism and Daoism |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=1998 |language=ja |isbn=978-4795253933}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u306e\u7dcf\u5408\u7684\u7814\u7a76 \u6b74\u53f2\u30fb\u793e\u4f1a\u30fb\u8cc7\u6599 |trans-title=History of Research into the Synthesis of the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra : History, Society and Historical Data |publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]] |year=2000 |language=ja |isbn=978-4393112045}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u9053\u6559\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u69cb\u9020 \u5897\u88dc\u4fee\u8a02 |trans-title=History of Daoism and its Formation - Revised and Supplemented |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2000 |language=ja |isbn=}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u5316\u570f\u306e\u5ea7\u6a19 |trans-title=The Sinographic Cultural Sphere |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2002 |language=ja,zh,en,fr |isbn=978-4896197419}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u30c9\u30ea\u30eb |trans-title=Exercises in the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra |publisher=[[Hitotsubashi Group|Hitotsubashi Shoten]] |year=2005 |language=ja |isbn=978-4565076007}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u601d\u60f3\u6982\u8ad6 |trans-title=Outline of Asian Thought |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2006 |language=ja |isbn=978-4896197433}}\n* {{Citation |last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |script-title=ja:\u30e8\u30fc\u30ed\u30c3\u30d1\u306e\u6771\u65b9\u5b66\u3068\u822c\u82e5\u5fc3\u7d4c\u7814\u7a76\u306e\u6b74\u53f2 |trans-title=History of European Oriental Studies and Research into the Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101 S\u016btra |publisher=[[:ja:\u9686\u6587\u9928|Goy\u014dshob\u014d]] |year=2008 |language=ja |isbn=978-4896197440}}\n\n=== Co-authored Works===\n* {{Citation|last=Fukui  |first=Fumimasa (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5) |editor-last=Makita |editor-first=Tairy\u014d (\u